<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0744 05-01 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0744,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Malley; Separates moved as a0681 on Ackerman and a0695
on Boyd.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Anne Ackerman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Annie Ackerman, 75, the powerful
political activist whose support was courted by candidates ranging
from condominum board members to a president, died Monday of cancer.
   Ms. Ackerman political activism included volunteer work for the
campaigns of the late Mayor Richard Daley of Chicago and
accelerated when she moved to a waterfront Florida condominium in
1969.
   Ms. Ackerman successfully roused retirees from political apathy
and mobilized them into powerful voting blocs. Famed for turnouts
ranging past 90 percent, they were dubbed ``condo commandos.''
   Her political friends included President Jimmy Carter, fellow
Democrats Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis, and nearly every
well-known Democratic politician in Florida.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Boyd</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Boyd, who fought off leftists to lead the
powerful British union of engineering workers, died Sunday. He was
71. A cause of death was not available.
   Boyd started his career as an engineering worker but began work
as a trade union organizer in 1946. He stepped up to the presidency
of the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions in 1964.
   Boyd spent years fighting communists and left-wing elements for
control of the 1.5 million-member Amalgamated Union of Engineering
Workers. From 1975 to 1982, he served as general secretary of the
union, which is one of the largest in Britain.
   From 1967 to 1975, Boyd sat on the general council of the Trades
Union Congress, the national organization of unions. Boyd was a
director of the British Steel Corp. from 1981-86.
   A chairman of the Labor Party in 1967, he was knighted in 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Malley</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST SENECA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Malley a deputy managing editor
at The Buffalo News was killed Sunday after his car spun out of
control. He was 49. Malley joined The News as a copy editor in 1966
and was promoted to assistant news editor in 1969 and then Sunday
magazine editor in 1977. He was named assistant managing editor in
1980 and deputy managing editor in 1987.
</TEXT>
