<FIRST>r a PM-Names     05-01 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0943</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush has puppy love written
all over her face.
   Puppy love times six, that is.
   That's how many puppies first dog Millie gave birth to about a
month ago.
   ``I have not named the puppies,'' Mrs. Bush writes in a cover
story in this month's Life magazine. ``I know them intimately, but
I don't want to give them names and get attached because I want
everyone who gets one to name his or her puppy.''
   The English springer spaniel is a dog without bad habits, the
first lady notes.
   ``I never had a girl dog before. I had boy dogs all my married
life. George loves Millie, but she is attached to me,'' Mrs. Bush
says. ``She gets White House table scraps when the president slips
them to her. He gives her showers _ how else do you wash your dog?
Every week or two, we climb right in the shower with our dog.''
   Clean or not, there won't be any more puppies during the Bush
tenure at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave.
   ``She won't have any more puppies, not because of her age (she's
only 3), but because I think you can ask a household to do this
only once. I would like more if I lived privately,'' Mrs. Bush said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Bacon knew as a child he wanted
to be an actor, and says he used to go to the movies and then dress
up as one of the characters once he got home.
   Bacon, who stars in the movie ``Criminal Law,'' said his mother,
who was a nursery school teacher, encouraged him to be creative.
   ``I fantasized, enjoyed dressing up in costumes. My favorite toy
was a big box of old clothes my mother saved for me,'' he said in
Sunday's Chattanooga News-Free Press.
   ``Every day I would be someone else,'' he said.
   ``I went to the movies as a kid and enjoyed the movies, but
couldn't wait to get out and get dressed as the character and act
it out _ Davy Crockett or Robin Hood,'' he said. ``It wasn't enough
for me to sit and watch it. I think I wanted to be the center of
attention.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The smell of marijuana wafted through the air,
and plenty of iced beer was on hand as about 2,000 people lined up
to buy tickets for The Who's reunion concert.
   During the weekend, some of the fans huddled under small tents,
braved rain and chilly temperatures outside Radio City Music Hall
for a shot at the tickets, priced from $75 to $2,000.
   Amy Yankowitz, a Manhattan legal secretary, claimed the first
spot in line by getting there Friday night. She slept through rain
showers, chased scalpers away from her spot and then learned that
the tickets were going to be issued by lottery.
   Promoters allowed those in line to draw a bracelet from a box.
The bracelets, numbered from one to 500, allowed the bearer to
return this morning and claim a place in line according to the
number drawn. Each person is limited to two tickets.
   The British rock band will be performing its rock opera
``Tommy'' in its entirety for the first time in 17 years.
   ``Is it worth it? Yeah, I worship this band!'' said Yankowitz,
who saw The Who perform at Shea Stadium in the group's farewell
tour in 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor John Goodman, who plays Roseanne Barr's
hefty husband in the TV series ``Roseanne,'' and his real-life
sweetheart were among the celebrities in the audience at the New
Orleans Jazz &amp; Heritage Festival.
   ``This is my third Jazz Fest,'' said Goodman, who attended
Saturday with his fiancee, Annabeth Hartzog.
   Most celebrities try to attend the festival without being
recognized, said Anna Zimmerman of the festival staff.
   ``The ones we make arrangements for don't want us to talk about
it,'' she said. ``They just want to come in and enjoy it with
everyone else. The people at the T-shirt tent always seem to
recognize them. They must all go there to get T-shirts.''
   ``It gives us a chance to see a lot of acts as well as
perform,'' singer Rita Coolidge said. ``You always see other
performers in the audience.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronnie Milsap, who has been successful
with pop and country audiences, says he's not afraid to return to
his country roots in his latest album.
   ``Most folks are afraid, I think, after you've had some pop and
rock success, to turn around and cut a country album again, but I'm
not ashamed to do that because I love country music so much
anyway,'' Milsap said recently.
   The Robbinsville, N.C., native, who has been blind since birth,
said he was exposed to classical music at a Raleigh school.
   ``I was taught to play and to listen to and to observe all kinds
of things _ then I came to Nashville and they say you can only be
one thing,'' he said.
   ``There's all kinds of albums that I see in my future if we're
able to make them happen.''
   The new album, ``Stranger Things Have Happened,'' has already
yielded two hits, including ``Don't You Ever Get Tired of Hurting
Me,'' and ``Houston Solution.''
   Milsap's other hits include ``Stranger In My House'' and ``I'm a
Stand By My Woman Man.''
</TEXT>
