<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     05-01 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Oil Use Down in US Food Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of so-called tropical oils by U.S.
food manufacturers has fallen considerably in recent years, but the
Agriculture Department says it won't make much difference
economically.
   Imported products such as palm oil, palm kernel oil and coconut
oil have been attacked vigorously by many U.S. farm and consumer
interests because of their high levels of saturated fats and
possible effects on health.
   The department's Economic Research Service says the United
States used about 14.5 billion pounds of fats and oils in food
products in the last year but that only 550 million pounds, or 4
percent, were tropical oils.
   Soybean oil accounted for more than 10 billion pounds; corn oil,
950 million pounds; and cottonseed oil, 800 million. Animal fats _
lard and tallow _ totaled about 1.1 billion pounds. Other sources
of vegetable oil include sunflower seed and rapeseed.
   Major edible uses of fats and oils are salad and cooking oils;
baking and frying fats; and margarine.
   Economists Bob Cummings and Jim Schaub said that use of tropical
oils in the United States may average about 1.84 billion pounds
since 1985, but the portion used in food products is expected to
average only about 650 million pounds a year, down from the record
1.6 billion pounds in the mid-1970s.
   In 1986, the American Soybean Association, after watching palm
oil and other tropical oils nudge into the lucrative U.S. market,
launched a campaign highlighting the health benefits of soybean
oil's relatively low saturated fat content.
   Cummings and Schaub, writing in the May issue of Agricultural
Outlook magazine, said the soybean people were joined by the
National Heart Savers Association, which began promoting the use of
oils low in saturated fats.
   Tropical oil interests deny adverse health effects, and the
Malaysian Palm Oil Growers Council has mounted an information
campaign and has underwritten medical studies to support its case.
   But Cummings and Schaub said saturated fats ``have been linked
with high blood cholesterol levels and heart disease,'' citing last
year's report by the U.S. surgeon general recommending reduced
intake of dietary fats, especially saturated fats.
   Several major food companies have eliminated tropical oils in
all or most of their products, and others plan to follow.
   ``If edible use of tropical oils were cut 50 percent, the effect
on U.S. fats and oils markets would be marginal, because these oils
are only a small portion of total use,'' the economists said in
their report. ``Substitute oils would capture some of the small
market share held by tropical oils.''
   The report added: ``Prices also would be little affected. Those
manufacturers using large quantities of relatively low-priced palm
oil would experience the largest impact. Consumers would hardly be
affected, because tropical oils account for only a small part of
the price of finished food products.''
   Cummings and Schaub also said that a 50 percent reduction in
U.S. food use of tropical oils would have little effect on U.S.
imports and world trade, and the effect on suppliers such as
Malaysia would likewise be minor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A final order is expected to be issued soon by
the Agriculture Department clearing the way for a watermelon
checkoff plan to finance a national research and promotion program.
   The department's Agricultural Marketing Service said the next
steps after the formal order is to hold meetings and solicit
nominations for a 29-member board that will oversee the program.
Those nominations are expected to be submitted by the end of July.
   After a board is selected, a proposed spending budget will be
drawn up and submitted for review. The agency says it may be fall
or later before everything is wrapped up.
   In any case, the watermelon assessments _ which are mandatory
but can be refunded _ are expected to be ready for 1990 production.
   The assessments and the program were authorized by Congress in
the 1985 farm law. A referendum was held in February in which
approximately 52 percent of the growers and 56 percent of the
handlers approved the plan.
   Agency officials said an estimated 7,000 watermelon producers
and handlers would be covered by the checkoff program.
   The assessment, to be recommended by the board and then set by
USDA, can be levied at rate of up to two cents per 100 pounds of
watermelons sold by producers and two cents per 100 pounds for
handlers.
   All producers of watermelons having five acres or more and first
handlers are required to pay the assessment. A grower of five acres
or more who also handles watermelons would have to pay both
assessments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of cut flowers, potted plants, greenery
and other commercially grown floriculture crops in 1988, a time of
severe drought in much of the nation, dropped 2 percent to an
estimated $2.24 billion, according to the Agriculture Department.
   An annual survey of 28 crops showed that wholesale values of cut
flowers increased 3 percent from 1987 to about $452 million, while
the value of potted flowering plants declined 3 percent to $494
million.
   Sales of foliage, including hanging baskets and potted foliage,
declined 7 percent to $477 million.
   The wholesale value of plants used for bedding and gardens
declined 2 percent to $724 million last year, the report said.
</TEXT>
