<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0728 05-01 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0728,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply, Key Index Finishes At Record High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with closing Nikkei, dollar figures; pick
up 4th graf pvs, `Traders said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen
Monday and the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished at
yet another high.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at a record 33,793.17,
gaining 79.82 points, or 0.24 percent. The index had gained 212.52
points for a record closing of 33,713.35 on Friday.
   The dollar finished trading at 133.90 yen, up 1.41 yen from
Friday's 132.49-yen close. The currency started at 133.00 yen and
ranged between 132.98-133.90 yen.
   Traders said the dollar started higher in Tokyo following its
rise in New York overnight.
   Daiwa Bank's Takamasa Yamasaki said the dollar was strong though
the only economic factor to encourage dollar-buying was market
players' expectation that the central bank is unlikely to raise the
official interest rate soon.
   ``Participants were less inclined to buy the yen because their
expectation for the interest-rate hike seemed to have faded away,''
he said.
   He said the Bank of Japan conducted a rate check shortly after
the trading began, and then sold some $100 million by mid-morning
to halt the dollar's further rise.
   ``But $100 million would not be enough to reverse the current
uptrend of the dollar,'' he said, adding that the central bank was
only trying to discourage the market's dollar-buying mood.
   The Bank of Japan does not comment on its monetary activities.
   On the stock exchange market, ``trading was quiet mainly because
of the yen's weakness on the foreign exchange and a holiday week,''
said an analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The index inched up as some participants bought issues including
steels and real estate, but most market players remained on the
sidelines, he said.
   Stock and exchange markets are to be closed for national
holidays on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday.
</TEXT>
