<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardROTC     05-01 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard ROTC,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Council Tenatively Reverses Resolution Asking ROTC Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard's undergraduate student council
has reversed its decision to ask ROTC back to the campus, declaring
an earlier vote a violation of the undergraduate constitution.
   But the debate is not over.
   The university forced Reserve Officers' Training Corps programs
from campus in 1969 by declaring the programs extracurricular
activities without special privileges. The move followed a building
takeover and student strike.
   Last week, the student council voted 41-24 to ask the
administration to negotiate with the military and bring ROTC back.
   Sunday night, about 400 students attended the meeting where the
council voted 43-39 against its week-old resolution.
   The resolution effectively said bringing ROTC back was in
violation of the student constitution because the program denies
membership and, therefore, scholarships to homosexual students.
   About 150 activists wearing pink arm bands and T-shirts
demonstrated outside before the meeting and chanted, ``2-4-6-8, no
to ROTC _ gay or straight!''
   During the debate, some students argued that barring ROTC may
deny economically disadvantaged students ROTC benefits.
   ``The issue is one of symbolism verses practicality,'' said
Garrett Price, who supported bringing ROTC back.
   Others said fewer than 20 of the 150 Harvard students who take
part in ROTC programs do so at nearby Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and receive less money from ROTC because their program
was not on campus.
   ``Harvard has a need-blind admissions policy,'' said Deepak
Bhargava, a ROTC opponent. ``If it's not living up to this policy,
we should force it to do so.''
   Although the council reversed itself Sunday, members next week
will consider the measure that would approve ROTC on campus if the
military did not bar homosexuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
