<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-India-Missile     05-01 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Missile,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Again Postpones Ballistic Missile Test-firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India today postponed the test-firing of
its first intermediate-range ballistic missile for a second time
after a leak was discovered in the rocket's liquid fuel propellant,
military sources said.
   A military official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
scientists detected the leak minutes before the scheduled launch
time and attempts to repair it quickly were abandoned three hours
later.
   On April 20, firing of the missile, named ``Agni'', was canceled
after a last-minute hitch in the ignition system.
   The military official said senior defense officers and
scientists had not yet decided when a third attempt would be made.
   The 7.5-ton missile has a range of 1,550 miles, Indian military
experts say. It was to be boosted in the first stage by a solid
propellant engine and in the second stage by a liquid fuel motor.
   A successful launch would make India the sixth nation in the
world to demonstrate ballistic missile capability. The others are
the United States, the Soviet Union, France, Britain and China.
   The Agni _ fire in the Hindi language _ was to have been
launched from the Chandipur test range on the Bay of Bengal about
750 miles southeast of New Delhi. The postponement was met by
cheers and blowing of conch shells by many of the 12,000 villagers
who were temporarily evacuated from their homes around the launch
site.
   The villagers fear they will be permanently shifted from their
homes if the missile launch is successful and the test range is
used for more firings.
   Agni is the fourth missile India has developed since the
Integrated Guided Missile Development Program started in 1983.
   India has already test-fired three surface-to-surface and
surface-to-air missiles with ranges from 20 to 155 miles.
   Defense experts say Agni's one-ton payload enables it to carry a
nuclear warhead, although New Delhi has said its demonstrated
nuclear capability is for peaceful purposes such as generating
power.
   India exploded a nuclear device 15 years ago, and Western
nuclear experts believe scientists can assemble an atomic weapon in
one week.
   The test-firing of the Intermediate Range Ballistic Missile is
intended to be only ``a technology demonstration of the country's
capabilities,'' according to the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
