<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-01 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply, Nikkei Hits New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply higher against the
Japanese yen today despite central bank efforts to check its rise,
and the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index finished at a new high.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 79.82 points, or 0.24
percent, closing at 33,793.17. The index had gained 212.52 points
to set a 33,713.35 record close on Friday.
   The dollar closed at 133.90 yen, up 1.41 yen from Friday's close
of 132.49 yen. It opened at 133.00 yen and ranged between 132.98
yen and 133.90 yen.
   Traders said the Bank of Japan bought about $300 million in
efforts to brake the dollar's rise against the yen.
   But Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank said the central bank's
intervention encouraged dollar buying instead of pushing the
currency down.
   ``Until the BOJ intervened, trading was rather quiet, with
little fluctuation in the rate,'' she said.
   ``Because the BOJ's dollar-buying didn't work at all, investors
were reconfirmed in their feeling of the dollar's strength and
continued to buy it,'' Ms. Takeuchi added.
   She said the market's demand for the dollar is still strong
because market players expect no immediate change in U.S. economic
policies.
   On the stock market, Daiwa Securities dealer Kenji Ishizuka said
the market's main index rose in the afternoon session as
institutional investors bought about 20,000 shares of each of the
225 issues in the index.
   He said reduced concerns about an immediate interest rise in
Japan encouraged buying. Media reports have said the central bank
might raise its official interest rate by 0.5 percentage point to 3
percent, but many in the market now expect that this will not
happen soon. Higher domestic interest rates generally discourage
stock buying.
   Trading was relatively active, Ishizuka said, with first section
volume estimated at 900 million shares. Friday's volume was 1.1
billion. Among the gainers were steel, ship building and
supermarket issues.
   The markets will be open Tuesday, but then will close until next
Monday for a series of national holidays known in Japan as ``Golden
Week.''
</TEXT>
