<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0734 05-01 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0734,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Ghetto,' A Play by Joshua Sobol, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with comments from other critics; No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months after 50,000 of the 70,000 Eastern
European Jews living in the Vilna Ghetto of Poland during World War
II were slaughtered, a theater company was started by some of the
survivors.
   It was an extraordinary event _ the founding of an artistic
community at the height of the Holocaust to keep alive the spirits
as well as the lives of those still trapped by its horrors.
   The story of the theater's birth in 1942 and its death two years
later is told disjointedly in Joshua Sobol's ``Ghetto'' which
opened Sunday at Broadway's Circle in the Square Theater. The play,
even with the addition of songs and music, is heavy on philosophic
discussion and short on dramatic continuity and character
development.
   That might seem strange, considering the thousands of
unspeakable tragedies that occurred in Vilna. But Sobol is more
concerned with historical events than individuals. The events _
some real and some imaginary _ are told in flashback by Srulik, a
ventriloquist and the artistic director of the fabled theater. His
remembrances make for some striking images but confusing story
lines.
   Director Gedalia Besser captures the audience's attention
immediately as Srulik, as an old man, sits on stage in a hospital
wheelchair and remembers. Suddenly, the back wall falls, and
mountains of bags containing the clothes of dead Jews tumble to the
floor as a prison wall topped with barbed wire rises in its place.
It's a mesmerizing beginning to the play, and an image that not's
topped during the rest of the evening.
   In the ghetto, Srulik carries a ventriloquist's dummy, played by
a real actor, Gordon Joseph Weiss. Weiss is made up to look like
the lascivious master of ceremonies in the musical ``Cabaret.'' The
dummy is the one occupant of the ghetto who talks back to the Nazi
officers, particularly the commandant, Kittel, played with sneering
ferocity by Stephen McHattie.
   It's Kittel who has the idea for the theater company, and he
orders Jacob Gens, the Zionist leader of the Jewish police in the
ghetto, to carry it out. The play eventually becomes an argument
about the existence of the company between Gens and other members
of the ghetto, particularly Hermann Kruk, founder of the ghetto
library.
   Gens is a practical man who will sacrifice some Jews so others
can be saved. If only Jews who work can be kept alive, he will give
them jobs in the theater. But Kruk is appalled at the idea and
proclaims, ``In a cemetery there can be no theater.''
   George Hearn as the realistic Gens and Jarlath Conroy as the
more cultured Kruk enunciate their arguments well, but not much is
learned about them from the play except their opposite stands on
the theater company.
   Avner Eisenberg, best known as the clown Avner the Eccentric,
plays Srulik. He isn't given much of an opportunity to develop his
character, even though the story is told through his eyes. Srulik
serves primarily as an excuse for announcing the various excerpts
of the company's theatrical productions which are shown only in
brief segments.
   There are a few interesting characters, particularly a cabaret
singer played with heart-breaking desperation by Helen Schneider.
She sings the songs, both original numbers from the ghetto theater
as well as new material written by William Schimmel, with
authenticity. And Donal Donnelly has some incisive moments as a
tailor who helps organize workers to mend German uniforms and which
helps keep them alive.
   Sobol's play, translated by David Lan, never develops
dramatically once the ghetto residents establish the theater
company. It goes from incident to incident without shedding more
light on the characters or why they participated in it.
   The theater finally was closed down by the Nazis in 1944, which
the play depicts in a bloody and unsatisfactory finale. Even after
more than two and a half hours, the audience is left wondering
about the inhabitants of Vilna, marveling at their determination to
survive, but wanting to know a lot more about what they were really
like than ``Ghetto'' manages to tell.
   In other reviews, The New York Times' Frank Rich said the
presentation is lifeless and is ``aiding rather than combating
historical amnesia.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel said the play ``has moments in
which harsh images come to life. But for long stretches it is
curiously uninvolving.''
   Clive Barnes, writing in the New York Post, said ``Sobol has
theatricalized this fragmentary morality play with great skill.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Chernobyl     05-01 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chernobyl,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety No Longer Top Priority At Chernobyl, Soviet Official Laments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The local Communist Party chief is complaining
that safety standards have eased at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant and well-trained specialists are in short supply at the
facility.
   Grigory I. Revenko, first secretary of the Kiev region, says in
an article in Sunday's Pravda that workers still are searching for
the best way to seal the plant's No. 4 reactor, which exploded and
spewed radiation three years ago last week in the world's worst
nuclear accident.
   After the April 26, 1986 accident, which killed at least 31
people, the reactor was encased in concrete to prevent further
radiation leaks.
   Revenko, a Ukrainian who was recently elected to the new Soviet
parliament, did not say why additional measures were needed to seal
the reactor.
   While that work continues, however, ``Problems with the safe
operation of the station more and more are being moved back to
second priority,'' Revenko wrote in the Communist Party daily.
   ``The understanding of the acuteness of the problems, including
those concerning the safety of the station, has dulled. We consider
this unacceptable and demand decisive intervention by'' the
government, he said.
   Other reactors at the plant are working and reportedly have
generated more than 40 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity since
the accident.
   Revenko, 53, said Chernobyl workers either have not received the
equipment and high-quality spare parts they need or have received
them after long delays. He also said scientists and technical
specialists throughout the country are poorly coordinating their
work on eliminating the accident's consequences.
   In addition, he said, the Atomic Energy Ministry is not sending
enough workers capable of coping with the special problems at the
plant.
   The three-column article said it was taking too long to build
housing and other buildings for Chernobyl plant workers in a new
town, Slavutich, and that an off-limits, contaminated zone around
the plant is being poorly managed.
   Recent Soviet news reports have said thousands more people will
be evacuated because their land is contaminated by Chernobyl
radiation and that deformed animals are routinely born on
contaminated Ukrainian farms.
   The reports also have complained that despite the Kremlin's
policy of greater openness, the government recently adopted a rule
forbidding disclosure of the illnesses people suffer from Chernobyl
contamination.
   Soviet public opinion turned against nuclear power after the
accident, and several nuclear power projects have been scrapped
around the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
