<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-01 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Bash Texas with Hail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms bashed Texas with hail as big as baseballs
and a reprise of winter weather dumped snow on Colorado, while rain
soaked the Southeast.
   The storms and heavy hail were centered over central Texas.
Baseball-size hail crashed in and around Tin Top, Breckenridge,
Mason and Mountain Home, and 3-inch hail pelted Cool. Golf
ball-size hail peppered Kerrville for almost 10 minutes and
completely covered the ground.
   Snow hit part of the plains and mountains of Colorado on Sunday.
Almost 4 inches fell in Denver by the evening, and flights at
Stapleton International Airport were delayed up to an hour earlier
in the day. Colorado Springs also got up to 4 inches.
   Rain was widespread across much of the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys and the southern Appalachians, with locally heavy rain
expected to continue in the latter region. Flash flood watches were
in effect from northeast Georgia across eastern Tennessee and much
of North Carolina to southwest Virginia and southern West Virginia.
   Pope Air Force Base at Fayetteville, N.C., recorded over 2\
inches of rain in the six hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT.
   An area of low pressure over the Gulf of Mexico was spreading
showers and thunderstorms into the eastern Gulf Coast.
   Light rain was falling behind a cold front from south central
Iowa into northeast Kansas. Rain also was falling in Oregon and the
northern California coast.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
portions of the southern Plains across the lower Mississippi Valley
and the Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast states. Scattered
rain was predicted from Missouri across the middle Mississippi and
Ohio valleys to New York and Pennsylvania, and in the Pacific
Northwest, Idaho and northeast Nevada. Rain was forecast to be
widespread over the central Appalachians and the mid-Atlantic
states.
   Highs were expected to be in the 40s and 50s from the Great
Lakes across the upper Mississippi Valley and Nebraska to eastern
Colorado; the 80s from the southern Atlantic Coast across the Gulf
Coast and southern Texas to interior portions of central
California; the 80s and 90s in the desert Southwest; and the 60s
and 70s in much of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 21 degrees at Custer,
S.D., to 80 degrees at Glendale, Ariz., and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 foggy; Boston 46 cloudy; Buffalo 46 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 71 fair; Cincinnati 57 rain; Cleveland 53 cloudy;
Detroit 47 cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 51 foggy; Philadelphia
58 foggy; Pittsburgh 55 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 45 foggy;
Washington 65 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 35 partly cloudy; Chicago 48 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 65 thunderstorms; Denver 32 fair; Des Moines 43
rain; Indianapolis 52 rain; Kansas City 49 cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 36 fair; Nashville 59 rain; New Orleans 69 rain; St. Louis 54
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 54 partly cloudy; Anchorage 41 fair; Las
Vegas 67 cloudy; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 76 partly cloudy;
Salt Lake City 46 partly cloudy; San Diego 61 fair; San Francisco
55 fair; Seattle 55 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 fair; Toronto 45 hazy.
</TEXT>
