<FIRST>r i PM-SailorsOverboard     05-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sailors Overboard,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Submarine Sailors Washed Overboard, Two Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rodrigues in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese and U.S. ships searched off southwestern
Japan today for two U.S. sailors missing from a Navy submarine
after a wave washed them overboard while they were standing watch,
officials said.
   A third sailor also washed overboard before dawn Sunday was
spotted by a rescue plane and saved by his ship, the 2,145-ton
Barbel, the U.S. Forces Media Liaison Office said in a statement.
   The rescued sailor's condition was not given, and U.S. military
spokesman Master Gunnery Sgt. Jake Rodrigues said he had no further
information.
   ``The three crew members were standing watch on the sail during
surface operations in international waters when the accident
occurred at 2:30 a.m.,'' the statement said.
   Yoshikazu Nakamura of the Maritime Safety Agency's office in
Kagoshima prefecture said there probably were numerous big waves at
the time because a fog and strong-wind alert was in effect for the
area.
   The Navy statement said the submarine was off Japan's
southernmost main island of Kyushu, about 650 miles southwest of
Tokyo.
   Nakamura said there was no way to determine the height of any
waves or the wind speed.
   Kiyoshi Harada, a spokesman for the maritime agency, said three
Japanese aircraft and four vessels, including three Japanese patrol
boats, searched today for the missing sailors.
   A Japanese defense official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that before the accident, the submarine surfaced
because it was taking on water from a hatch. He refused to
elaborate.
   A U.S. Navy spokesman denied that. ``We have no information that
there is anything wrong with the Barbel, and it is taking part in
the search,'' Lt. Jeff Gradeck said.
   The diesel-powered Barbel, built in 1956 and equipped with six
torpedo tubes in its bow, has a crew of 77, said a U.S. military
official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The official said the 219-foot Barbel belongs to the last class
of non-nuclear combat submarines built by the Navy.
</TEXT>
