<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WarDebt     05-01 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-War Debt,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Home For Aged Repays Gentile's War Heroism By Admitting Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a teen-ager in Poland during World War II,
Irene Opdyke risked death at the hands of the Gestapo by hiding 12
Jewish friends in the basement and attic of a German officer's
villa where she worked.
   All survived the Holocaust, as did countless others who were
saved because Mrs. Opdyke shared information overheard from Gestapo
officers planning roundups in Jewish communities.
   Last week, an old war debt was repaid.
   Administrators at the Jewish Home for the Aged in the San
Fernando Valley community of Reseda waived admissions policies and
admitted Ms. Opdyke's 80-year-old husband, William, to their
Alzheimer's disease unit.
   ``We violated all the rules _ he's not from our region, we are
sectarian, we are so short of beds _ but there are certain times
when there are no rules. This is one of those times,'' Executive
Director Sheldon Blumenthal said. ``In caring for Bill, we are
repaying a debt to her. We owe her.''
   Opdyke is one of only a few non-Jews at the 875-bed facility
that provides communal living for old people.
   Mrs. Opdyke, 68, said she vowed to help her Jewish friends when
she saw the way Hitler's army treated Jews during the 1939 invasion
of Poland. She called it ``a nightmare that changed my life.''
   ``I saw a man with a white beard and a little white hat, running
carrying a Torah,'' she said. ``Little ones were screaming `Mama!
Mama!' I saw a soldier pull a baby out of its mother's arms and
throw him to the ground. Later, I heard shooting. They were killing
innocent people.''
   While working as a housekeeping for a German major, she hid
Jewish friends for nearly eight months, sometimes in the home's
attic, other times in the basement.
   Recently, as Ms. Opdyke's husband began suffering from the
advanced stages of Alzheimer's disease, administrators at the
Jewish Home for the Aged said they felt a special obligation to
care for him.
   ``She risked her life and this is the return we want to give
her,'' said Dena Schulman, spokeswoman for the home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
