<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Protest     05-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Protest,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Dissident Leaders Under Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight leaders of underground political groups
remained in custody today, a day after being arrested while selling
their magazines on the Arbat pedestrian mall, an activist said.
   The eight dissidents probably will stay under ``preventive
arrest'' through the two-day May Day holiday that ends Tuesday,
said Yuri Mityunov, a member of the self-styled opposition party
Democratic Union.
   Leaders of the Democratic Union, Express-Chronicle, Free
Migration, Debate, and Trust groups were detained Sunday after
ignoring police calls to disperse.
   ``Down with the fascists!'' one man yelled at police as they
grabbed the activists.
   In their publications and in telephone calls to Western
reporters, the groups declared Sunday a ``samizdat holiday.''
``Samizdat'' is Russian for self-published and is used to describe
underground newspapers and magazines.
   On Sunday, the dissidents perched atop concrete planters outside
the Vakhtangov theater on Arbat Street, silently holding makeshift
bulletin boards bearing copies of their publications.
   Thousands of onlookers strolled along the mall in the 70 degree
weather and peeked at the publications. The most sensational of the
newspapers was a copy of the Communist Party daily Pravda that had
pasted to it cartoons lampooning Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin.
One cartoon portrayed Lenin as a devil.
   A policeman announced through a megaphone that the gathering was
not sanctioned, and he ordered the dissidents to disperse. About 15
minutes later, officers moved in.
   The Democratic Union, formed in May, seeks multiparty elections,
independent trade unions, a new constitution and the withdrawal of
Soviet troops from Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
