<DOCNO> AP890501-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RobotRetrieved     05-01 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robot Retrieved,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sunken Robot Retrieved, But Substitute Sub Will Star in Underwater
Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oceanographers have recovered Jason, the errant
submersible robot that took a dive last week, but have decided to
give its understudy, Medea, the starring role in an underwater show.
   Jason, a high-tech, propeller-driven submersible equipped with
video cameras and maneuverable arms, was retrieved from the bottom
of the Mediterranean Sea on Saturday. It sank 2,100 feet to the
ocean floor Wednesday when its cable to the support ship Star
Hercules snapped.
   Meanwhile, the submersible Medea, which was used to recover
Jason, was expected to take center stage today as the first of
250,000 students in 12 cities across the United States and Canada
hook up via two-way satellite with marine explorers off the coast
of Italy.
   Over the next two weeks, museum officials and elementary and
high school students will watch via satellite as Medea inspects the
wreckage of a sunken Spanish galleon.
   Medea is a six-foot-long, one-ton platform carrying three
television cameras, two color and one black-and-white. Unlike
Jason, it is not remotely operated with its own propulsion system;
it is towed behind a surface craft and its cameras operate as it
passes a target.
   Organizers had hoped Jason would be able to go on with the show,
but Sonya Hagopian of the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, a
sponsor of the program, said Jason will undergo a complete
evaluation before returning to service.
   ``Jason will probably be going back in, but not right away,''
Hagopian said Sunday from Cape Cod. ``It could be a matter of just
a few days.''
   About 2,000 museum officials, teachers and technicians were
testing a satellite hookup last week when Jason, the younger
brother of the robot that first rummaged through the Titanic's
wreckage, unceremoneously sank on its debut mission.
   Hagopian said that while most of the damage to Jason appeared to
be cosmetic, technicians planned to run it through a series of
tests before returning it to the water.
   ``I understand that there is minimal damage to it. It is still
very usable. It's not bad at all,'' she said. ``On a scale of one
to 10, with one being minimal damage, I'd say we're at a one.''
   The May 1-14 project's sponsors include Woods Hole, Turner
Broadcasting System, the National Geographic Society and Electronic
Data Systems.
   Participating museums, mostly science and natural history
museums, are in Boston; Denver; Detroit; Charlotte, N.C.; Chicago;
Dallas; Memphis, Tenn.; Philadelphia; Rochester, N.Y.; Sarasota,
Fla.; Washington, D.C.; and Victoria, British Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
