<DOCNO> AP890501-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-01 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems and Christians Violate Ceasefire; Two Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces battled with
mortar and tank fire in the hills above Beirut today, killing two
people and wounding seven, the first casualties in a 3-day-old
truce called by the Arab League.
   Fighting raged from nightfall Sunday to daybreak today in the
mountaintop town of Souk el-Gharb, where Syrian troops and Druse
militiamen surrounded a Christian army garrison, police said.
   Mortar and tank cannon rounds crashed in Christian and Druse
villages around Souk el-Gharb, wounding seven villagers, police
said.
   Two Lebanese soldiers also died in the fighting, the first
fatalities reported by officials since a truce went into effect
Friday in an Arab League-mediated attempt to halt eight weeks of
bloodshed.
   ``This is the gravest violation of the truce. It's worse than
the sporadic bombardment of the coastline of the Christian enclave
in the past two days,'' according to a police spokesman said.
   ``The coastal shelling underlined the dispute over blockaded
seaports, but the fighting in Souk el-Gharb has wider dimensions
that could undermine the Arab League's peace plan altogether,'' he
said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Souk el-Gharb sits atop a strategic network of mountain roads
leading from the Druse hinterland southeast of Beirut to the
Christian heartland north and northeast of the capital. If the
Christian-controlled town falls to the allied Syrians and Druse,
Christians would lose the central mountain stronghold shielding
their 310-square-mile enclave.
   The latest casualties increased the overall toll to 275 people
killed and 1,000 wounded since March 6, when army commander Gen.
Michel Aoun's 20,000 mainly Christian troops blocked illegal Moslem
militia-run ports. The Syrian-Druse alliance responded by
blockading the Christian enclave.
   A spokesman at Aoun's command claimed the Syrian army and
militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist
Party were ``trying to provoke us into a mass retaliation to
undermine the Arab League's cease-fire.''
   ``But the general is determined to strip them from that excuse.
We're not responding,'' said the spokesman, who requested anonymity.
   He said Aoun's army was merely defending front positions and was
not shelling Moslem residential areas or distant Syrian targets.
   Jumblatt, meanwhile, issued a May Day statement calling for
Aoun's removal from power as a condition for peace.
   ``It's impossible to reach a compromise with Michel Aoun. He
must be removed or toppled,'' said Jumblatt. ``This must be clear
to all other Christian leaderships.''
   The political and military wrangling underlined a dispute over
the second provision of the latest cease-fire that calls for the
lifting of air, land and sea blockades.
   Aoun, who heads a Christian military Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, refused to call off the blockade of illegal harbors,
which he says deprive the state of $100 million yearly in lost
taxes. He said his gunboats and helicopter gunships were applying
Lebanese laws.
   But the rival Moslem Cabinet under acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss has insisted Aoun's blockade be lifted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Car-TruckCrash     05-01 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Car-Truck Crash,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Adults, Four Children Dead in Car-Truck Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLOWERY BRANCH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car rounding a steep curve in the
driving rain crashed into a tractor-trailer, killing six of the
car's eight occupants, state police said.
   Four of the dead in Sunday's crash were children. A 47-year-old
woman was in extremely critical condition at North Fulton Medical
Center and a 10-year-old girl was in critical condition at Scottish
Rite Hospital in DeKalb County, hospital spokesmen said today.
   The driver of the truck was unhurt, said Georgia State Patrol
Cpl. Mike Nash.
   Nash said the accident occurred about 2:40 p.m. on a state road,
during ``a torrential downpour.'' The car was descending a hill and
rounding a curve when the driver ``evidently lost it and got over
in front of the tractor-trailer,'' he said.
   The Forsyth County sheriff's office identified the victims as
Sherry Rogers Thompson, 21, the driver; her brother, Gerald Kevin
Rogers, 27; Tiffany Rogers, 3; Ashley Thompson, 3; and Jamie
Rogers, 6, all of Cumming, and Francesca Rogers, 3, of
Lawrenceville.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
