<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle     05-01 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Confers With Camdodian Resistance Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Marilyn Quayle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said today
he had a productive meeting with Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, but the two did not broach the subject of U.S.
military aid.
   ``It was a good meeting,'' Quayle said after the 45-minute
session with Sihanouk. ``I had not met him before.'
   Aides to the vice president arranged the meeting with Sihanouk
after learning that the two would be in Jakarta at the same time.
   Quayle, who arrived here today after five days in Australia,
also held discussions throughout the day with a host of
Indonesians, including President Suharto and three human rights
activists.
   Quayle said that in his meeting with Sihanouk, he did not talk
about the possibility of providing military assistance to Cambodian
resistance forces, although that option is under consideration in
Washington.
   ``We talked about the process and moving the process forward and
what coalition may or may not be, who the players are and what some
of the expectations would be,'' the vice president told reporters.
   Cambodia's future _ and U.S. policy toward the country _ is one
of the top items on Quayle's agenda during his 12-day trip to the
Pacific region. Vietnam has said it plans to end its military
occupation of its Southeast Asian neighbor this fall.
   The United States supports having Sihanouk lead an interim
government until elections can be scheduled in Cambodia. Others
jockeying to run the country include factions led by Hun Sen, the
head of the Vietnamese puppet government in Phnom Penh; the Khmer
Rouge and an anti-communist group headed by Son Sann.
   Both Hun Sen and Son Sann were in Jakarta for meetings with
Sihanouk.
   While the United States has yet to clearly define its policy
toward Cambodia, Quayle and his aides have firmly rejected a
takeover by the Khmer Rouge, the Chinese-backed group that was
responsible for killing as many as 1.5 million people in the late
1970s.
   Sihanouk has called for an international conference in Paris
that would devise an enforcement mechanism for the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops and the transition toward an elected government.
   A senior aide to Quayle said that in his meetings with Suharto,
the vice president reiterated that the United States wants to
follow the lead of its Asian allies in devising its policy toward
Cambodia.
   Washington does not want to do ``anything that is
counterproductive,'' said the aide, who asked to remain anonymous.
   Quayle also discussed trade with the Indonesian leader and said
the United States is interested in human rights issues such as the
situation in East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by
Indonesia in 1975.
   While the United States views Indonesia as a reliable ally, it
wants to see Jakarta develop more openness on the political side as
well as economically.
   Underscoring his commitment to human rights, Quayle met with
three local activists to hear their concerns. The vice president
did not agree with all of the activists' issues, but he ``listened
and received material about individual cases'' of alleged human
rights abuses, the Quayle aide said.
   More than 30 members of Congress asked the vice president last
week to raise the human rights issue with the Indonesians,
especially to pursue reports that the country is holding as many as
400 political prisoners.
   Quayle and his wife Marilyn, leaves for Singapore on Tuesday
before heading to Thailand and Alaska, where he will view the
cleanup operation from the devastating March 24 oil spill of the
tanker Exxon Valdez.
</TEXT>
