<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Collaborators     05-01 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Collaborators,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attacks On Collaborators Ordered By PLO Officials Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO officials abroad approve most of the orders
to kill Arabs suspected of collaborating with Israel after
underground ``trials'' are conducted by local Palestinian
activists, Palestinian sources said today.
   The PLO headquarters in Tunis had no immediate comment on the
report.
   In the latest attack on an alleged collaborator, Ahed Ramini, a
30-year-old Palestinian, was fatally stabbed today by attackers in
the occupied West Bank city of Tulkarem, Arab reports said.
   His death brought to 41 the number of alleged collaborators
killed since the Palestinian uprising began nearly 16 months ago,
most the victims of attackers who support the Palestine Liberation
Organization. More than 60 alleged collaborators have been wounded.
   In recent weeks, the Palestinian underground has established a
clandestine system to conduct what they say are trials of those
accused of cooperating with Israel's military government in the
occupied West Bank and occupied Gaza Strip.
   Palestinian sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
so-called trials included testimony from witnesses, and that notes
or tape recordings were made of the proceedings.
   ``As the Palestinian organization becomes more disciplined,
there have been situations where people have been pulled in and
questioned. Testimony has been taken as well as confessions, which
are tape recorded and signed,'' said one Palestinian believed to
have close contacts with underground activists.
   On the basis of such statements, recommendations were forwarded
to PLO officials abroad, said another source, adding that a ``black
list'' had been compiled of Palestinians who informed or worked
with Israeli military authorities.
   The Palestinian sources said the orders to kill the alleged
collaborators were approved by a Moslem clergyman who was deported
by Israel from the West Bank in 1980 and is now believed to be
based in Iraq.
   The sources said orders are relayed via coded messages broadcast
by Baghdad Radio.
   An Israeli military official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said the PLO had encouraged and cooperated in attacks on
Palestinians who had dealings with Israel or adopted anti-PLO
positions. He also confirmed the clergyman was involved in
approving such reprisals.
   According to Israeli government figures, 960 attacks were
carried out between December 1987 and mid-April, most of them
warnings such as firebombs hurled at houses or cars.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said there was a ``wave of terror''
being waged to intimidate moderates who might otherwise support
Israel's proposal to hold elections in the occupied territories to
choose Palestinian negotiators.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel told reporters April was
the bloodiest month for Palestinian attacks on Palestinians with at
least 10 killed. He was unable to cite evidence that Palestinians
were killed for political beliefs but contended the attacks had a
chilling effect on diplomatic efforts.
   ``It is impossible to convince people to start working on the
elections in this atmosphere,'' Liel said, confirming newspaper
reports that Arens complained to U.S. Ambassador William Brown that
terror was being used to thwart Israel's attempts to find
Palestinian partners for dialogue.
   Palestinians denied the killings were designed to rein in
dissidents and said collaborators were punished because they
endangered the lives of underground activists who were sought by
Israeli authorities.
   One source said the United National Leadership of the Uprising,
which guides the revolt against Israeli occupation, had issued an
internal memo recently stressing that no reprisals could be taken
against collaborators without permission of the underground.
   ``If anything, there are less attacks as a result,'' said one
Palestinian.
   A leaflet distributed in Nablus today and signed by Fatah,
Yasser Arafat's PLO faction, vowed to ``strangle anyone who will
think of interfering with the intefadeh (uprising) and those who
collaborate.''
</TEXT>
