<FIRST>u i PM-Paraguay-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru a0458 05-01 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0458,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguayans Vote For New President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with voting beginning; picks up
6th graf pvs: Stroessner, 76...; edits thereafter to eliminate redundancies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguayans voted today for a
president and congress to replace the 34-year regime of Gen.
Alfredo Stroessner, who was toppled in a Feb. 3 coup.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez, the candidate of the ruling Colorado
Party and the man who ousted Stroessner, was expected to easily
defeat former exile Domingo Laino and six other rivals. The
Colorados were expected to retain control of congress.
   Laino denounced election irregularities, such as a lack of
indelible ink at some stations to prevent double voting and a voter
registration list that favored the ruling party.
   But he said this morning that some flaws were unavoidable and if
fraud was not ``generalized'' his party, the country's second
biggest, would accept the results.
   Voters interviewed shortly after polls opened at 7 a.m. (8 a.m.
EDT) said the elections were as free as any they had voted in.
   Voting was conducted in privacy and the ballots of all eight
parties were available, said architect Ricardo Facetti. ``That
didn't use to happen'' in the days when Paraguayans were encouraged
to vote for Stroessner and the Colorado Party.
   ``Before, I wouldn't even have talked with you. What if a
policeman saw?'' said Cesar Ramon Gonzalez, 57, a retired public
accountant. ``Now the atmosphere is completely different.''
   Polls indicate Rodriguez will receive as much as 70 percent of
the vote.
   Stroessner, 76, seized power in a 1954 coup and brooked little
opposition during his lengthy rule, arranging to be elected every
five years. He was unseated on Feb. 3 and sent into Brazilian exile.
   The 65-year-old Rodriguez has been hailed by Paraguayans for
toppling Stroessner, but opposition parties _ banned under
Stroessner _ have complained they were not given enough time to
prepare for today's elections.
   Eight parties have fielded candidates in the voting for
president, 36 senators and 72 deputies to finish the five-year
terms begun by Stroessner and congress following elections in
February 1988.
   The parties are responsible for providing their own ballots and
presidential candidate Fernando Vera said his opposition
Revolutionary Febrerista Party was not sure its ballots would be
available at all of the more than 10,000 polling places nationwide.
   ``We've distributed our ballots to the main places, but I'm not
sure we've gotten through'' to smaller, more remote villages in the
nation of 4 million, he said.
   The Colorado Party has controlled the government for 42 years
and Rodriguez has broadened his base by improving relations among
its factions as well as with foreign governments and the Roman
Catholic Church, to which most Paraguayans at least nominally
belong.
   At a campaign rally Saturday night, Rodriguez repeated his
pledge to complete only Stroessner's term and to hand over power in
August 1993 to ``my successor, freely elected by the people at the
ballot box.''
   The opposition contends the Colorados will benefit from dated
voter registration lists. Even the Central Electoral Board says
that up to 600,000 names on the list of 2.2 million may be invalid.
   The main campaign issue has been who can best move a country
that has never had a democratic government in that direction.
   Rodriguez has broadened civil liberties and pledged to reform
the constitution, electoral laws and penal code.
   The polls were to open at 7 a.m. and close at 4 p.m. with
unofficial results expected tonight. Paraguayans ages 18 to 60 are
required by law to vote. Violators face small fines.
</TEXT>
