<DOCNO> AP890501-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Chamber     05-01 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Chamber,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices to Study Michigan Campaign Spending Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to restudy, in
a case involving the Michigan Chamber of Commerce, what limits
should be placed on campaign spending by political groups that
incorporate themselves.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Michigan officials that
is supported by the Federal Election Commission.
   The Michigan Chamber of Commerce has about 8,000 dues-paying
members, about three-fourths of them corporations.
   The chamber planned in 1985 to place a paid advertisement in the
Grand Rapids Press in support of Richard Bandstra, a Republican
candidate for the state House of Representatives.
   Fearing the ad would be considered illegal under Michigan's
Campaign Finance Act, the business group filed a federal lawsuit
seeking to have the law declared unconstitutional. The chamber said
the act violates its free-speech rights.
   The state law generally prohibits corporations from spending in
behalf of political candidates and carries a maximum $10,000 fine.
   The law permits a corporation to make such expenditures if it
sets up a special fund, or political action committee, that is
required to keep records and disclose the names of contributors.
   The Chamber of Commerce has such a fund. However, it wanted to
pay for the newspaper ad for Bandstra out of its general treasury,
which is exempt from the record-keeping and reporting requirements
of the state campaign finance law.
   A federal judge ruled that the chamber may not spend money from
its general treasury in behalf of a political candidate. The judge
said the state campaign finance act, aimed at heading off
corruption of the political process, applied to the chamber's
activities.
   But the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last September
overturned the judge's decision.
   ``We conclude that indirect expenditures made by a
non-traditional corporation, like the Michigan Chamber of Commerce,
formed for essentially ideological purposes and to disseminate
economic and political ideas and not to amass capital, do not pose
the threat or appearance of corruption,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court relied heavily on a 1986 Supreme Court
decision limiting the federal government's power to regulate
corporate political spending.
   The justices said then that the Federal Election Campaign Act of
1971 violates freedom of speech when applied to corporations formed
primarily to influence public opinion, not to make a profit.
   The high court ruled in favor of a Massachusetts group formed to
protest the legalization of abortion.
   The 1986 ruling said corporations formed to promote political
ideas, that have no shareholders and are not established by
business corporations or labor unions, should not be subject to the
federal campaign spending law.
   The 6th Circuit court said the Michigan Chamber of Commerce fits
that description.
   The appeals court also said there was no danger the chamber's
corporate members will use the business group ``as a conduit for
massive undisclosed corporate political spending.''
   Anyone contributing more than $100 to a political candidate _
through the chamber or otherwise _ still must file a report
disclosing that spending under state law, the appeals court said.
   In a dissenting opinion, Judge Gilbert Merritt said the ruling
allows corporate giants, such as General Motors, Ford and Chrysler,
to funnel large sums of money through the chamber to favorite
candidates without revealing the spending.
   The Federal Election Commission joined Michigan officials in
urging the Supreme Court to overturn the appeals court ruling.
   The decision, if applied to federal law, ``would substantially
undermine congressionally mandated limitations upon the use of
corporate wealth to influence the outcome of federal elections,''
the FEC said.
   The case is Austin vs. Michigan Chamber of Commerce, 88-1569.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
