<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Profits     05-01 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Profits,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Study Goodyear's Use of Foreign Laws to Ease Tax Bite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to hear a Bush
administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to collect
potentially hundreds of millions of dollars in taxes from
multinational corporations.
   In a case involving Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co., the court said
it will review a ruling that allows multinationals to use foreign
tax laws to reduce their U.S. taxes.
   The case stems from operations of Goodyear's British subsidiary
in the early 1970s.
   The Ohio-based corporation's subsidiary incurred net losses in
1972 and 1973 _ at least under British tax law. The subsidiary's
1973 loss included British tax deductions that were not allowed
under American tax law.
   As a result, the British government refunded to the subsidiary
the tax payments it made there for 1970 and 1971.
   The refunds prompted the U.S. Internal Revenue Service to
recompute the taxes it said Goodyear owed in this country.
   Multinationals are entitled to claim a share of taxes paid by
subsidiaries overseas as credits against U.S. taxes.
   In the Goodyear case, since American law did not recognize the
1973 deductions permitted the company in Great Britain the
corporation's loss was converted into a profit.
   The redetermination had the further effect of wiping out, for
U.S. tax purposes, the foreign tax credits previously allowed in
1970 and 1971.
   As a result, the IRS assessed Goodyear $791,240 in taxes and
interest for 1970 and 1971.
   Goodyear then sued in the U.S. Claims Court, saying the IRS
erred in applying American law instead of British law to determine
the company's accumulated profits.
   The claims court ruled against Goodyear. But a federal appeals
court here reversed the decision last August.
   The appeals court said a multinational company is entitled to
use a foreign nation's tax laws to determine accumulated profits
made by a subsidiary in that country.
   Administration officials said the ruling could have ``enormous
importance'' for U.S. tax revenues.
   Justice Department lawyers, in the appeal acted on today, said
more than 25,000 foreign subsidiaries of U.S. companies are doing
business in more than 100 countries. The government said its most
recent figures show the companies claimed more than $9 billion in
foreign tax credits in 1982.
   The IRS is reviewing $150 million in claimed refunds in such
cases and expects the appeals court ruling will prompt an
additional $750 million in refund claims.
   The government appeal conceded that the impact of the appeals
court ruling has been blunted by a 1986 change in U.S. tax law that
may mean multinationals no longer will be able to use a foreign
country's calculation of its accumulated profits for most future
tax payments here.
   The case is U.S. vs. Goodyear, 88-1474.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Synanon     05-01 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Synanon,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Looks At Synanon Tax Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today appeared to clear the
way for a federal trial against nine current and former Synanon
Foundation figures accused of illegally conspiring to regain the
group's tax-exempt status.
   The justices sent the case back to a federal appeals court for
restudy in light of their March 28 ruling that criminal defendants
may not immediately appeal a judge's refusal to dismiss an
indictment for alleged grand jury abuses by prosecutors.
   The Synanon Foundation figures had sought to throw out an
indictment that charges them with destroying evidence of violent
activities at the California-based organization.
   The defendants said the 1985 indictment should be dismissed
because of prosecutorial misconduct.
   Synanon was founded by Charles Dederich some 30 years ago as a
non-profit center for rehabilitating drug and alcohol users. In the
late 1970s it became embroiled in allegations of violence, threats,
and harassment of former members and opponents.
   Dederich has been accused of converting the organization into a
violent cult. In October 1978, Paul Morantz, a California lawyer
representing two former Synanon members in a suit against Synanon,
was bitten by a rattlesnake he found in his mailbox.
   Dederich and two other Synanon members pleaded no contest to
charges of conspiracy to murder Morantz.
   The indictment involved in the case acted on today did not name
Dederich. But it said nine others, including his daughter, Cecelia
Jason Dederich, altered or destroyed evidence that could undermine
Synanon's claim to be a charitable, non-violent foundation.
   The indictment said they plotted to deceive the Internal Revenue
Service, which had revoked Synanon's tax-exempt status. The
foundation, later called Synanon Church, faces millions of dollars
in tax liens.
   The indictment said destroyed documents and tapes had evidence
of violence against perceived enemies of Synanon, acquisition of an
arsenal of guns, diversion of Synanon money into private hands and
so-called ``love matches'' and other activities of sexual
promiscuity.
   The nine defendants said the government engaged in misconduct by
using University of California Professor Richard Ofshe as a witness
before the grand jury that indicted them.
   The grand jury was not told that Ofshe was suing Synanon for
millions of dollars and that Ofshe was allowed to listen to tape
recordings to help identify individuals who were indicted, the
defendants said.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last July said, ``The
prosecutor's failure to disclose Ofshe's source of potential bias
was a breach of duty to the grand jury. However, it does not by
itself justify dismissal of the indictment.''
   The other defendants named in the indictment are Synanon counsel
Philip C. Bourdette, former counsel Dan L. Garrett Jr., David
Benjamin, Elizabeth Missakian, Steven Simon, Miriam Bourdette, Dan
Sorkin, and Sybil Schiff.
   The case is Benjamin vs. U.S., 88-1290.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Nuclear     05-01 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Nuclear,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Licensing Fees for Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed the government
to impose annual licensing fees of around $1 million for nuclear
power plants.
   The justices, without comment, rejected an appeal by 29
companies that own or operate nuclear reactors.
   The licensing fee for nuclear plants was adopted by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission under a 1986 budget bill passed by Congress.
   The measure, the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act,
authorizes the NRC to pay for one-third of its annual budget by
assessing such fees.
   The commission imposed a fee of $950,000 last year on each
holder of a nuclear plant license. The fee is expected to be more
than $1 million for the current fiscal year.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here upheld the fee last May.
The appeals court rejected arguments that the fee should be tied
directly to services the NRC performs for the benefit of a
particular nuclear plant.
   The appeals court also said the fee is a constitutional
delegation of Congress' power to impose taxes.
   The appeals court said Congress may delegate ``the tax power
where adequate standards are set for implementation of
congressional intent.''
   The fee bears a reasonable relationship to regulatory services
performed by the NRC, the appeals court added.
   The justices last week unanimously upheld federal ``safety user
fees'' imposed on pipelines that transport natural gas and
hazardous liquids.
   The case acted on today is Florida Power &amp; Light vs. U.S.,
88-234.
</TEXT>
