<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Asbestos     05-01 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Asbestos,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses To Hear Hawaiian Asbestos Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear an
appeal by Hawaii officials seeking to recover from asbestos
manufacturers the cost of removing the product from public schools
in the state.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings from Pennsylvania
that included Hawaii in a so-called class-action settlement of
claims against the asbestos companies.
   Hawaii officials said they were not given a proper opportunity
to remove themselves from the class-action court settlement in
which thousands of school districts are eligible to receive money
from an asbestos clean-up fund.
   Hawaii wants to be excused from the general lawsuit so that it
can sue two manufacturers, Proko Industries Inc. and Owens-Illinois
Inc., for millions of dollars in Hawaii state courts.
   Hawaii officials said they first learned of the class-action
settlement pending before a federal judge in Pennsylvania in May
1987.
   At that time, they were told they had until Aug. 1, 1987, to
notify the judge they did not wish to be a part of the settlement
group, thereby preserving their right to sue separately.
   The officials said they were not alerted to a change in the
deadline that moved it up to June 22, 1987, and later extended for
a month. As a result, they said, they failed to notify the federal
judge that they wished to opt out of the settlement.
   The officials also contended that the settlement violates the
Constitution's 11th Amendment that limits federal court authority
over states.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals based in Philadelphia
ruled against Hawaii last October.
   The case is Hawaii vs. Proko Industries, 88-1484.
</TEXT>
