<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>July Trial Date Set for Former CIA Operative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today set a July 10 trial
date for a former CIA agent charged with lying to obstruct
inquiries into his role in the Iran-Contra affair.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton scheduled the trial after
Joseph F. Fernandez pleaded innocent to four charges that he lied
and obstructed the inquiries of a presidential commission and the
CIA's inspector general.
   Fernandez, who operated under the pseudonym Tomas Castillo when
he was the CIA's station chief in Costa Rica, was allowed to post a
$1,000 personal-recognizance bond pending trial.
   The former CIA agent is accused of lying about his role in
setting up an airstrip in Costa Rica used for transhipping supplies
to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   The indictment charges that the false statements obstructed
inquiries by the presidential Iran-Contra commission headed by
former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, and the CIA's inspector general.
   Each of the four charges carries a five-year prison sentence and
a $250,000 fine upon conviction.
   An indictment brought last year against Fernandez in Washington
was dismissed last fall after prosecutors conceded that the proper
jurisdiction for the case was across the Potomac River in Virginia.
   The charges arise from statements Fernandez made during
questioning at CIA headquarters in Langley, Va.
   Fernandez was arraigned as a federal court jury in Washington
was preparing to resume deliberating 12 related Iran-Contra charges
against former National Security Council aide Oliver L. North.
</TEXT>
