<FIRST>r a PM-Tornadoes     05-01 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tornadoes,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornadoes Touch Down In Florida; No Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tornadoes touched down across
the Florida Panhandle today, but no one was hurt and there was
little damage, officials said.
   One twister hit Eglin Air Force Base, a spokesman said.
   ``We've had some roofs damaged and windows blown in,'' said Lt.
Col. Sam Giammo. He said the buildings hit included aircraft
hangars, dormitories and office buildings.
   Outside the base near Florida's western tip, officials confirmed
a tornado touched down near the Valparaiso police station.
   ``The damage there was light,'' said Hank Christen, director of
emergency management for Okaloosa County. ``There was a shed
destroyed. There was a window broken and some wires down.''
   A Walton County house lost its roof, but ``as far as we know no
one was injured,'' said Angie Henderson of Walton County civil
defense. She said there were reports of trees blown down and roofs
torn off barns near DeFuniak Springs.
   Another twister hit near the Riviera subdivision in Santa Rosa
County. ``There were large trees that covered the highway and there
was some structural house damage,'' said Pat Wadkins, dispatcher
for county emergency services.
