<DOCNO> AP890501-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Lawyer     05-01 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyer,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Says Lawyers Can't Be Forced In Non-Criminal Federal Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers may not be forced by federal law to
represent poor people in non-criminal federal cases, the Supreme
Court ruled today.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court ruled in favor of John A. Mallard, an
attorney from rural Fairfield, Iowa, who specializes in business
cases. He had refused a federal judge's order to represent prison
inmates in a civil rights suit because he said he felt unqualified
for the assignment.
   ``We do not mean to question, let alone denigrate, lawyers'
ethical obligation to assist those who are too poor to afford
counsel,'' said Justice William J. Brennan for the court.
   ``In a time when the need for legal services among the poor is
growing and public funding for such services has not kept pace,
lawyers' ethical obligation to volunteer their time and skills ...
is manifest,'' he said.
   But Brennan said the federal law is clear: lawyers may be
requested to help _ not forced to do so.
   The federal law authorizing legal help for poor people in civil
cases specifically says a judge may ``request'' any attorney take
the case, Brennan noted.
   He was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice
Byron R. White, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said Congress
may have used the word ``request'' but actually meant
``respectfully command.''
   ``In my opinion, Congress gave its endorsement to these judicial
requests, assuming that it would be unthinkable for a lawyer to
decline without an adequate reason,'' Stevens said.
   He was joined by Justices Thurgood Marshall, Harry A. Blackmun
and Sandra Day O'Connor.
   Mallard, who argued his own case before the high court last
February, had been ordered to represent two current inmates and a
former inmate at the Iowa state prison in Fort Madison.
   The inmates said prison guards and officials filed false
disciplinary reports against them, physically mistreated them and
endangered their lives by revealing they were informants.
   A federal judge picked Mallard in 1987 to represent them from a
list of more than 100 lawyers compiled by the Legal Services Corp.
of Iowa and the state's bar association.
   In addition to saying he lacked experience in trial work,
Mallard said the federal courts do not have power to require an
unwilling attorney to represent someone in a civil case.
   The possible penalties Mallard faced for his refusal to take the
prison cases were not discussed. But presumably he could have been
held in contempt and fined or even jailed had the Supreme Court
rejected his appeal.
   Courts routinely assign lawyers to represent indigent defendants
in criminal cases and the lawyers are paid, at taxpayer expense,
generally a fraction of what they would receive normally.
   In civil rights cases, lawyers are paid expenses and may receive
a share of any damages won by their clients.
   U.S. District Harold D. Vietor had denied Mallard's motion to be
excused from the inmates' suit. The judge said Mallard was
competent and had trial experience.
   The case is Mallard vs. U.S. District Court, 87-1490.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0079 </DOCNO>
