<HEAD>Funeral for Baby Removed from Respirator; Other Parents Remember</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with detail, quote from funeral. Picks up
6th graf pvs, `The boy's...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baby Death, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral today for a brain-damaged baby who died
after his father disconnected his respirator has stirred memories
among parents who have faced the impending death of a youngster
they know will never get well.
   Samuel Linares, who had been severely brain-damaged and comatose
since swallowing a balloon last August at a birthday party, was
remembered at a private visitation Sunday and a funeral today
attended by about 80 mourners.
   The 16-month-old's father, Rudy Linares, is charged with
first-degree murder. Police say Linares, 23, held off hospital
workers at gunpoint, unhooked his son's respirator and cradled the
boy until he died.
   He said later that he did it `` because I loved my son ... I
love my wife.''
   Free on bond, Linares attended the boy's private funeral today
at Mary Queen of Heaven Church in suburban Cicero. He and his wife,
Tamara, sat in the front pew with their other two small children.
   ``Over and over again, we ask why, and there is no answer. Not
all the priests, all the bishops, all the popes, all the moralists,
can answer the question why,'' the Rev. John R. Price said in his
eulogy.
   The boy's death has prompted an outpouring of calls from parents
whose children have died. Though some said they were disturbed by
Linares' methods, many sympathized with the emotions that drove him.
   And the boy's physician, Dr. Gilbert Goldman, director of the
pediatric intensive care unit at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's
Medical Center, said mercy should be used in dealing with the
father.
   ``I kept telling the dad (Linares), `I know it's terrible, but
it won't last much longer'' Goldman said of the boy's coma. He said
Samuel beat medical odds by staying alive so long.
   Susan Maher, a parent, said she understands what Linares went
through during those months. Her daughter, Elizabeth, spent the
first two years of her life at the University of Illinois Hospital
in Chicago, the victim of cerebral palsy and chronic lung disease.
   Ms. Maher said there were times she considered unplugging
Elizabeth's life-support equipment.
   ``A lot of times there is hardly anybody else in the hospital
unit,'' she said. ``You could do it. It enters your mind when you
feel you're being selfish by making a child suffer.''
   Ms. Maher didn't do it and Elizabeth, now 7, lives at home with
the aid of a ventilator.
   Ms. Maher said she hopes Linares' wife, Tamara, ``understands
her husband. What they have now is each other. They will have to
really love each other very much right now.''
</TEXT>
