<FIRST>r i AM-MarilynQuayle     05-01 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marilyn Quayle,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Quayle Stressing Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOGYAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle used a visit to this
region in central Java Monday to underscore her new efforts to
stress disaster relief and disaster preparedness.
   Mrs. Quayle, who is traveling with her husband, Vice President
Dan Quayle, spent the day on her own, visiting a 9th century
Buddhist temple, a sultan's palace and two projects that deal with
preventing natural and ecological disasters.
   On her first trip overseas with her husband, Mrs. Quayle has
highlighted the issue she hopes to spotlight _ disasters.
   ``It is something that strikes a chord,'' Mrs. Quayle said,
explaining that Americans have often reached out to people
suffering from natural disasters.
   The 39-year-old Mrs. Quayle is trained as a lawyer, a profession
she says she thinks of going back to but that might be doubtful
while her husband holds the vice presidency, she said.
   But Mrs. Quayle said she intends in her new role to ``dispel the
myth that went on for so long that when you put a wedding ring on
... the brain stops,'' she said.
   Before she decided to adopt disasters as her focus of interest,
Mrs. Quayle said she talked with first lady Barbara Bush. ``The
only person I talked to was the most important person, Barbara
Bush,'' Mrs. Quayle said.
   She added that Mrs. Bush was encouraging about her interest and,
``Basically, she said, go for it.''
   Asked if she feared upstaging Mrs. Bush, Mrs. Quayle said, ``How
can you overshadow her, really.''
   Mrs. Quayle told reporters traveling with her to this city in
the middle of Java Island that she hopes to educate Americans
around the country about disaster relief, but she has to watch her
dollars and cents.
   ``I have no official capacity, nobody pays for me. ... I don't
have a plane, I don't have anything,'' she said. So, Mrs. Quayle
said, she would try to make speeches in the United States when
invited by various groups.
   In this bustling city, Mrs. Quayle visited a center where people
are trained to cope with volcanic eruptions. Indonesia, a densely
populated nation of islands, has about 130 active volcanoes, 18
percent of the world's.
   Then she stopped by a village where the local people, many of
them young children, cheered and clapped. The village, Keji, is the
site of a project funded by the U.S. Agency for International
Development where villagers are taught to recognize insects that
naturally destroy those bugs that damage crops.
   Officials explained to Mrs. Quayle how the ladybug, for
instance, is the farmer's friend.
   Clare Wolfowitz, wife of U.S. Ambassador Paul Wolfowitz, called
Mrs. Quayle's visit ``a tremendous shot in the arm for officials
promoting economic development in Indonesia.''
   ``Our AID people were excited to have her see this at the top of
the list,'' Mrs. Wolfowitz said.
   Then Mrs. Quayle toured the 9th century Buddhist temple at
Bobobudur, which has 10 terraces and is considered one of the
greatest Buddhist temples in the world.
   Mrs. Quayle also toured the palace of a sultan here, viewing his
daggers, hand-carved puppets and elaborate belts, among other
things.
   Quayle, who remained in Jakarta for high-level meetings with
government officials, was jealous of her schedule, Mrs. Quayle
said. When Quayle saw her itinerary, she said he said, ``Can't I
come?''
</TEXT>
