<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Yemen-Floods     05-01 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Yemen-Floods,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says 53 Died in Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOHA, Qatar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flash floods that have struck central South
Yemen since March 19 have killed 53 people and injured 50, it was
reported Monday.
   It was the first official casualty toll cited in the three weeks
of intermittent flooding, the worst in years to hit the
impoverished Red Sea state.
   Mohammed Salem Badinar, secretary of the South Yemen parliament,
told the Qatari newspaper Al-Raya that 3,066 houses and 625 miles
of roads were destroyed in the flooding. In addition, about 48,000
acres of farm land were inundated, destroying 60 percent of the
grain and fruit crop, Badinar said.
   He did not say how many were left homeless by the floods.
Earlier reports from South Yemen put the number of homeless at
between 50,000 and 100,000.
</TEXT>
