<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TunnelDeaths     05-01 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tunnel Deaths,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Dept. Proposes $1.15 Million In Fines For Explosion That Killed
Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Labor Department today cited two
contractors for safety and health violations and proposed $1.15
million in fines for a methane gas explosion that killed three
workers in a sewer tunnel project.
   S.A. Healy of McCook, Ill., the main contractor for the project,
was cited for 68 willful violations carrying fines of $680,000 in
connection with last November's fatal blast. CH2M Hill, of
Corvallis, Ore., hired to supervise the project, was cited for 47
willful violations carrying penalties of $470,000.
   Both companies have 15 days to appeal the citations and
penalties to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration,
said Mike Connors, regional administrator of OSHA's Chicago office.
   The proposed fine of $10,000 per willful violation was the
maximum allowed, Connors said.
   Willful violations are the most serious issued by OSHA and are
based on a finding that the contractors knew that a dangerous
condition violated safety standards and made no effort to correct
it, Connors said.
   ``These penalties are one of the largest I am aware of for the
region and certainly the largest that I am aware of for a tunnel
project,'' he said.
   OSHA investigators believe they have located the exact cause of
the Nov. 10 explosion but Connors declined to release that
information, citing concerns about future litigation.
   Criminal negligence charges could also be filed against the
contractors, he said.
   The citations accused the two contractors of failing to train
workers about the proper response when methane is detected in a
tunnel, using inappropriate electrical equipment and wiring methods
for a ``gassy'' tunnel, failing to have adequate ventilation for
the tunnel, and keeping inadeqauate records of air monitoring in
the tunnel.
   OSHA's investigation concluded that the two contractors were
directly responsible for the deaths of the three workers, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
