<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0494 05-01 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Says April Second-Bloodiest Month In Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: CORRECTs 1988 to 1987 in 6th graf ``The center,... ''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli human rights group said today that
April was the second-bloodiest month of the Palestinian revolt,
with at least 34 Palestinians killed in clashes with Israeli troops
in the occupied lands.
   A 30-year-old man was stabbed to death today in the occupied
West Bank by fellow Palestinians after being accused of
collaborating with Israel's Shin Bet security service, Arab reports
said.
   Palestinians throughout the territories held May Day
demonstrations in celebration of the international labor holiday,
and shouted pro-PLO and pro-communist slogans.
   Arab reports said four Palestinians were shot and wounded in
clashes with soldiers in the occupied Gaza Strip. The victims
included a 10-year-old boy who was shot in the head, the reports
said.
   The Jerusalem-based Israeli Information Center for Human Rights
in the Territories said 33 of the Palestinians killed in April died
of gunshot wounds suffered in clashes with troops or paramilitary
police. The other person died of beating injuries inflicted by
soldiers, it said.
   The center, founded by a number of left-wing parties and peace
movements, said the worst month of the uprising was April 1988,
when 44 Palestinians were killed.
   The center said a total of 423 Palestinians have died since the
uprising began 16 months ago to protest Israeli rule of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Associated Press death count, based on Arab hospital
reports, also listed 34 Palestinians killed by army gunfire last
month, plus seven more killed as suspected collaborators.
   The AP count shows a total of 457 Palestinians killed in the
revolt; the figure includes Arabs killed by Palestinians as
suspected collaborators. Eighteen Israelis also have died in the
uprising.
   An army spokesman disputed the figures, saying 28 Palestinians
were killed during April and that the figure was higher in several
previous months. According to army figures, a total of 351
Palestinians have died in clashes with soldiers.
   In the West Bank city of Tulkarem today, masked youths entered a
photo studio owned by Ahed Ramini and stabbed him several times,
Arab reports and Israel radio said. The army said it was checking
Arab reports that he died on the way to the hospital.
   Ramini's death would bring to more than 40 the number of Arabs
killed as suspected collaborators during the uprising.
   Ariel Sharon, a right-wing Cabinet minister, criticized the army
for arresting a Jewish settler in the death of a 14-year-old
Palestinian during a stone-throwing clash in the West Bank city of
Hebron.
   During a Cabinet debate Sunday, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
rejected right-wing demands that settlers be allowed to fire more
liberally when their cars are stoned.
   Sharon told army radio today: ``The detention of a Jew who was
defending his life while being attacked, under these present
cirumstances when attacks on Jews are everyday events, is something
that is grave and unnecessary.''
   ``To investigate if need be, yes. To detain, no,'' he said.
   The settler, Chaim Ben Lulu, was released on $3,880 bail today
after fellow settlers maintained a two-day vigil outside military
government headquarters in Hebron.
   Israel radio reported Ben Lulu was freed after a hearing before
Jerusalem Magistrate Dalia Koval and quoted her as saying the
settler apparently acted in self-defense when he fired his pistol
Saturday. Israeli media reports said he fired after Palestinian
youths stoned his car.
   Ben Lulu has not been charged, but remains under investigation,
police said.
   Hebron, a city of 79,000 Palestinians where settlers live in two
tiny enclaves, is a frequent site of friction between Jews and
Arabs.
   Most Jewish settlements in the occupied lands are located away
from Arab population centers. More than 70,000 settlers live in the
occupied lands amid 1.7 million Palestinians.
</TEXT>
