<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1351EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     05-01 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita Expected to Ask Ito Next Week to Succeed Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, brought down by a
scandal that reached the top of business and politics, is expected
to ask former Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ito to replace him,
government sources said Monday.
   Takeshita said a week ago he would resign, but the choice of a
successor as leader of the governing Liberal Democratic Party, and
thus as prime minister, has been put off until he returns Sunday
from a nine-day trip to Southeast Asia.
   After Takeshita's announcement, party secretary-general Shintaro
Abe and Keizo Obuchi, the chief Cabinet secretary, informally asked
Ito to take the job. Ito, who is 75 and diabetic, said he would not
take the job because of his age and health.
   The government sources said privately Monday, however, that the
party would have ``no other choice ... but to persuade'' Ito, who
they described as the only candidate on whom all party factions
could agree.
   Ito has a clean reputation and most other party leaders have
been linked to the scandal centered on Recruit Co., an information
and publishing conglomerate. He now is chairman of the Executive
Council, the party's policy-making body.
   Masaya Ito, a critic of the political scene who is not related
to the former foreign minister, said the offer of succession ``is
no more than asking him to lend his clean image without actual
political power.''
   ``It sounds to me no more than an insult for a senior politician
like Ito,'' said the critic, who was an aide to the late Prime
Minister Hayato Ikeda. ``It is apparent that the current party
leadership is trying to remain in control by appointing Ito and
other senior officials. No dignified politician would take such an
offer.''
   Whoever the Liberal Democrats choose will become prime minister
because of their large majority in Parliament. The party has
rejected opposition demands to call elections so voters can pass
judgment on the scandal and an unpopular 3 percent sales tax that
took effect April 1.
   Takeshita said he was resigning to take responsibility for the
scandal. He is to step down after Parliament passes the 1989
budget, which has been approved by the lower house.
   Fourteen people have been arrested on bribery and other charges
so far in the Recruit case, and three Cabinet members were forced
to step down before Takeshita's announcement.
   Recruit sold stocks in a subsidiary to about 160 influential
politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen at bargain prices before
the shares were offered for public sale. The price soared when the
stock went on the market and the buyers made huge profits.
   Prosecutors contend that, in some cases, the deals amounted to
bribes in exchange for favors to the company.
   The prime minister has acknowledged getting more than $1 million
in political donations from Recruit and that an aide, who committed
suicide the day after Takeshita announced his resignation, received
a loan of about $376,000 from the company.
</TEXT>
