<DOCNO> AP890501-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PetroglyphPark     05-01 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Petroglyph Park,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Field Hearing Considers Proposed Petroglyph Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AQ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM McELROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of prehistoric Indian
petroglyphs etched into dark, basalt rock have survived for
hundreds and hundreds of years, but time no longer is on their side.
   The once-remote volcanic ridge they adorn on Albuquerque's west
side is in danger of being swallowed by civilization.
   ``If we don't get the federal authorization from Congress this
year the pressures of development and vandalism are so intense out
there we may be losing the opportunity,'' said Ike Eastvold, a
leader in a move to have Congress create a national monument to
preserve the carvings of humans and animals. ``It really is the
11th hour.''
   Evidence of the threat to the petroglphs is all around the
17-mile escarpment, created by lava flows that began 190,000 years
ago.
   Houses and roads creep closer. One path to the area passes
mounds of rubbish. Some drawings have been marred by spray paint or
damaged by gunshots.
   The drawings are the work of early Pueblo Indians who lived in
the area between 1300 and 1650 A.D. Spanish settlers arriving the
area in the 1500s added their own petroglyphs.
   ``This is the largest concentration of rock art in the world in
a major city,'' said Eastvold.
   He said preserving the more material elements of a culture such
as architecture is not enough. ``The art and religion are what made
them live,'' Eastvold said.
   He said the petroglyphs are even more exciting because they were
done by the ancestors of the present Pueblo Indians of New Mexico
and eastern Arizona, meaning they still are part of a living
culture.
   Eastvold said the petroglyphs also are artistically appealing.
   New Mexico's two U.S. senators, Republican Pete Domenici and
Democrat Jeff Bingaman, have introduced legislation to establish
the monument.
   They conducted an Energy and Natural Resources Committee public
lands subcommittee hearing Friday in Albuquerque to hear from
federal, state and local officials, developers, conservationists
and Indian leaders.
   Those who spoke at the hearing indicated support for the
monument.
   John E. Cook, regional director of the National Park Service,
said at the hearing that if Congress fails to take action within
two years the land will become degraded to the point it could no
longer be considered for monument status.
   Eastvold, head of the group Friends of the Albuquerque
Petroglyphs, said he believes that if the national monument is not
created most of the land will be lost to development.
   ``You would probably end up with little bits and pieces
preserved in an inadequate manner,'' he said.
   The bill introduced by Domenici and Bingaman, and an identical
measure introduced in the House by Rep. Steve Schiff, R-N.M., calls
for the national monument to include 7,100 acres.
   About 4,300 acres of land already is publicly owned. The total
value of the land that would have to be acquired is estimated at
$90 million, with $50 million coming from the federal government
and the remaining $40 million from the city and state. The state
and city already have made provisions for a portion of their
commitments.
   In addition to preserving the estimated 15,000 carvings,
proponents say the monument would draw 400,000 visitors and
generate $5 million in revenue for the city and its businesses in
the first year alone.
   Domenici believes that what should be stressed is not so much
the cost of doing the project but the cost of not doing it because
the drawings would continue to be degraded until they are lost
forever.
   Bingaman agreed.
   ``I think the longer you go into the future the more important
it's going to have been that people at this time took the
opportunity to set some land aside and preserve some of these
petroglyphs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0094 </DOCNO>
