<HEAD>Trippe Commanding Officer Relieved of Duties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of a Newport-based frigate
that collided with another ship 12 days ago has been relieved of
his duties on the frigate, a Navy spokeswoman said Monday.
   Commander Lewis Athow, who was in charge of the USS Trippe, was
suspended after a preliminary investigation and temporarily
assigned to Naval Surface Group Four in Newport, spokeswoman Mary
Silvia said.
   Commander John C. Dranchak has been desginated interim
commanding officer until a permanent relief can report to the
Trippe, which would take two weeks, Silvia said.
   The Trippe collided with the USS Platte off the coast of Florida
on April 19, causing minor flooding and one minor injury to a
Platte crewman. It was during those exercises that the USS Iowa
exploded in an unrelated accident, killing 47 crewmen.
   Silva would not say why Athow was suspended. An investigation
was continuing, she said.
   The Trippe is in Charleston, S.C., for repairs.
