<DOCNO> AP890501-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WineRecorking     05-01 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wine Recorking,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed French Wine House Sending Recork Task Force To U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legendary French wine house Chateau
Lafite-Rothschild is sending a task force to the United States to
recork _ at no charge _ older bottles of the fabulously expensive
Bordeaux.
   Starting Tuesday in New York, the experts will recork some 2,000
bottles of 1962, or older, vintages. The group also will visit
Boston, Atlanta, Miami and Dallas.
   The Lafite team, which was in San Francisco last year, took
reservations for the recorking service through next January. The
demand, said the company, was ``tremendous.''
   An 1806 vintage _ the same year Napoleon ordered the blockade of
Britain and construction of the Arc de Triomphe in Paris _ will be
among the wines to be recorked. A bottle from that year once sold
for $31,000.
   ``There is no charge for this service,'' said David S. Milligan,
president of Seagram Chateau &amp; Estate Wines Co., the major Lafite
importer in this country. ``The chateau does it as the most
remarkable after-sale service in the industry.''
   Milligan would say only that the 1806 is owned by a collector in
Boston whose identity he couldn't disclose.
   The recorking is carried out by Lafite because, as the wine
experts say, ``wine is only as good as its cork.'' Old corks can
become dry, which allows air to seep into the bottle and can cause
wine to spoil.
   Recorking is especially needed for the nobler wines of the
world, made with the view that a very good bottle may not reach the
most drinkable period for years, even decades and generations.
   A minimum of 15 years is often recommended before a given
vintage of Lafite should be consumed. The 1961 vintage, for
instance, wasn't ready for drinking until last year _ 27 years.
   ``As the Rothschilds have tended over a century of vintages at
Lafite, they have determined that their bottles should be recorked
about every 25 years or so,'' said Milligan. ``Even the finest cork
has limited lifespan, and keeping the cork in good condition is
essential to protect the wine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CandyThief     05-01 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Candy Thief,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pastry Chef Seeks Sticky-Fingered Thief With Sweet Tooth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thief with a sweet tooth who
nabbed a painted chocolate wafer and a marzipan witch may have
bitten off more than he could chew.
   The chef said the candy is priceless, and police have classified
the case as grand theft.
   Pastry chef Anneke Jans and her mother, Phyllis Sherohman, were
gone a short time Sunday from a culinary trade show _ just long
enough for the thief to make off with Miss Jans' creations.
   The painting of a turkey on the chocolate wafer and the
5-inch-tall marzipan witch cost Miss Jans about $1,000 each in
supplies and labor. Sentimental value makes them priceless, she
said.
   ``I just fell apart when I saw (them) missing,'' said Miss Jans,
20, who is studying culinary arts at Orange Coast College. ``Like
most people would (value) money and gold, this is my gold.''
</TEXT>
