<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-01 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long time before George and Barbara Bush
lived in the White House, they lived in a white house. Now that
house just got whiter.
   The first couple's first Midland residence was repainted over
the weekend as part of a massive home-renovation project. About
2,500 to 3,000 volunteers used more than 700 gallons of paint to
refurbish about 150 homes. The spruce-up project was the 18th
annual observance in Midland of ``Christmas in April,'' known
locally as CIA.
   The Bushes lived in the residence in the 1940s and '50s. An
elderly woman who lives there now was unable to maintain it,
organization officials say.
   ``What did Bush say about the 10,000 points of light?'' asked
the Rev. Allen Whitman of The Episcopal Church of the Holy
Trinity's Mission Outreach Council, as he stood on a ladder outside
the former Bush home. ``It's ironic a light should be at one of his
own homes.''
   Another point of light, in the form of a glob of white paint,
dried on Whitman's glasses as he spoke.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosie the Duck can have her ducklings anywhere
she chooses, officials say, and the mallard has decided to set up
her nest alongside a downtown high-rise.
   Because the duck enjoys the protection of the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service, she and her 12 eggs cannot be moved from a
planter near the Chicago River to a safer location. It's against
the law, at least until hunting season opens in the fall.
   ``You can't touch her, harm her, or take her,'' declared a
government agent who viewed her Friday.
   Indeed, the duck is protected by the Migratory Bird Treaty Act
between the United States, Mexico and Canada. Anyone who touches
the bird could be fined $2,000 or be sentenced to up to one year in
jail, said the agent.
   Some Rosie watchers had sought to move the duck to a safer, more
secluded spot along the Chicago River below.
   Tishman Speyer Properties, which owns the commercial high-rise,
ordered security guards to keep an eye on the duck after a
maintenance worker found the nest in mid-April.
   ``She seems rather calm and happy there,'' said Paul Collins, a
guard who patrols the nesting site.
   Rosie's eggs are due to hatch this week.
</TEXT>
