<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaTaxes     05-01 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Taxes,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor: Budget Cuts Will `Go Beyond Common Sense'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget cuts forced by voter rejection of
a tax package will ``go beyond common sense,'' Gov. Buddy Roemer
said Monday as the administration studied closing some universities
and hospitals.
   Rejection in Saturday's referendum means the state will have a
projected $720 million deficit when the new fiscal year begins July
1, Roemer said.
   Even with passage of the package, the administration would have
been forced to cut spending by $200 million, including reducing a
charity hospital to an outpatient clinic and laying off 4,100 state
employees, Roemer said.
   ``Now we must go beyond that. The cuts will be deeper than I
wanted, deeper than common sense, but we will not do business as
usual,'' Roemer said wearily at an impromptu news conference.
   The governor referred to projecting oil prices high enough to
balance the budget on paper, a routine practice until Roemer took
office in March 1988.
   With high oil price projections, the state ended each year with
massive deficits which had accumulated to $900 million by the time
he took over.
   Each increase of $1 a barrel in the price of oil, sustained for
a year, means around $28 million in extra state tax revenue.
   Roemer said the state realistically could increase the
projection from $15 to $17 a barrel since the price of Louisiana
oil at this time is about $18, ``but you're only talking about $60
million if we do that.''
   The tradition of having oil companies and other big businesses
pay a big share of state revenues in Louisiana dates back to the
days of populist Gov. Huey Long in the 1920s and 1930s.
   Roemer's plan would have shifted the tax burden away from big
business, putting more of a load on individuals through the income
tax. It would have reduced sales taxes and given businesses
incentives to move to Louisiana and expand.
   The plan also included a $1.4 billion program to improve
highways, airports and shipping ports, funded by a gasoline tax
increase of 4 cents a gallon.
   Romer touted his plan as a way to bring jobs to Louisiana, which
has the highest unemployment rate in the nation at 9.6 percent, and
to end the state's dependence on the oil industry.
   ``We had a number of (industrial) prospects that had anticipated
fiscal reform to open new plants,'' Roemer said. ``I had to call
them this morning and talk it through. It's not all good news.
We'll hang on to what we can.''
   The Legislature could extend for another year a temporary
suspension of sales tax exemptions on food, drugs and utilities
that was put into effect last summer to stave off bankruptcy,
Roemer said. Allowing that suspension to expire on June 30 would
leave a $500 million hole in the budget, he said.
   Roemer said he didn't want to talk about specifics of what
universities or hospitals might have to be closed.
   ``You'll know as soon as we know,'' he said.
   Rep. Robert Adley, chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee and a close adviser to the governor, had said earlier in
the day that his phone ``was ringing off the hook this morning.
They're (lawmakers) scared. Reality is setting in and they don't
want to lose institutions in their districts.''
   Meanwhile, state Rep. David Duke, perhaps the most vocal
legislative opponent of the tax package, said lawmakers might want
to extend sales tax increases to avoid closure of charity hospitals
and universities.
   Throughout the tax referendum campaign, Duke said the people
``don't want any more taxes. None.''
   ``I'll hold an olive branch out to him (the governor),'' said
Duke, a former Ku Klux Klan leader. ``We've got to solve the
financial problems. The Legislature might be willing to restore
some of the temporary taxes if it comes to that. We still have some
time to play with this thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
