<FIRST>r a AM-MississippiBurning     05-01 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Burning,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Mississippi Burning' Coming to Town Near Where Bodies Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ads for ``Mississippi Burning'' adorn
the lobby of the town's only theater, but the manager says there's
been little interest in the film based loosely on the 1964 slayings
of three civil rights workers nearby.
   ``I've had the advertisement up for a couple of weeks _ that
it's coming May 24 _ and I can only recall a couple of people who
had comments,'' said Shelly Steiger, whose family has owned and
operated the Ellis Theater in the town of 7,000 for 35 years.
   Mayor Charles McClain said most of the talk in town now involved
plans for a special memorial program June 21 to honor the three
civil rights workers.
   ``Mississippi Burning,'' starring Gene Hackman and Willem Dafoe,
is a fictionalized account of federal investigation of the murders
of Andrew Goodman, James Earl Chaney and Michael Schwerner in
Neshoba County. Their bodies were found in an earthen dam near
Philadelphia six weeks after their deaths on June 21, 1964.
   The Orion Pictures release has received praise from movie
critics, but harsh criticism from people who were involved in the
civil rights movement, particularly blacks who see the movie giving
too much credit to the FBI.
   ``I'm sure if there were people here who were real interested in
the movie, they have already gone to a town where it has been
shown,'' said Steiger.
   The film was shown earlier this year in Jackson, about 80 miles
southwest, and in Meridian, about 40 miles east.
   Steigher said his theater seats about 500 people, which means
2,500 people could see the movie during its five-day run.
   ``Of course, that would mean a sellout every night and it's been
a long time since that has happened,'' he said.
   McClain said he also had not heard too many comments about the
movie.
   The mayor said he had seen the film and thought it ``just piled
everything on one locality when at the time it was spread out
across the state and the South.''
   He said Philadelphia had good race relations and ``I thought
they really didn't give our city a very fair presentation, even for
1964.''
</TEXT>
