<HEAD>Police Search Wrong House In Crack Raid</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Fixes typo in word `hers.'</UNK>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After complaining to police for nearly
four months to shut down a crack house on her block, Terri
Tillman-Brown said officers raided the wrong house _ hers.
   Police with a search warrant on Friday broke through the front
door of Tillman-Brown's home while she was away, according to
neighbors.
   The undercover officers ransacked her home, left her front door
broken and open, and her dog running free outside, Tillman-Brown
said. They also opened a sealed bag of cremated ashes she said she
had been keeping for a friend's burial. Some of the ashes spilled
onto her bed, she said.
   The police apparently found none of the cocaine and drug
paraphernalia the search warrant said they were seeking. Police
declined immediate comment.
   ``I called the police today and they told me they can't help me
till Monday,'' Tillman-Brown said over the weekend.
   Tillman-Brown, a 38-year-old accountant for the state, said the
raid occurred four days after the drug dealers were evicted from a
house next door. She said she had complained to police about the
nearby drug activity almost weekly since they moved in in January.
