<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     05-01 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Ambush Second U.N. Food Convoy in Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers ambushed a second United Nations
food convoy in southern Sudan, spraying the lead vehicle with small
arms fire, U.N. officials said Monday.
   No one was hit in Friday's attack near Kapoeta and the convoy
arrived Sunday at its destination in Torit with 300 tons of food,
said World Food Program spokesman Paul Mitchell.
   It is the second ambush of a U.N. convoy in less than two weeks
near Kapoeta, a garrison town held by the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army.
   Eight armed rebel escorts were killed April 18 when the first
Operation Lifeline Sudan convoy to Torit was hit by a rocket and
automatic weapons fire.
   The United Nations temporarily suspended operations on the
overland route between Kapoeta and Torit, and last week's convoy
was the first to make a new attempt.
   Mitchell said they will stop using the route again and any
further supplies will be sent to Torit through Uganda.
   The $132 million operation hopes to save 100,000 lives in Sudan,
where officials estimate as many as 500,000 people died from
drought, flood and war-induced famine last year.
   U.N. officials concede that political, logistical and other
problems will prevent them delivering more than than half their
115,500-ton goal of supplies before seasonal rains cut off outlying
villages.
   Mitchell said 27 trucks set out in Friday's convoy from
Lokichoggio, in northern Kenyan, and were 12 miles outside Kapoeta
when attacked.
   ``It was small arms fire from the bush,'' Mitchell said. ``They
didn't see anybody and it's hard to say who they (the attackers)
were or how many there were.''
   Government troops for years have battled rebels demanding more
autonomy in southern Sudan, but both sides agreed in March to allow
safe passage for relief food. Other gunmen in the south include
nomadic tribal warriors and government-sponsored militiamen.
   Nils Enquist, Operation Lifeline's logistics coordinator, said
between six and 10 bullets struck the vehicle.
   ``It was carrying a driver and the convoy leader and it is only
by the grace of God they weren't hurt,'' Enquist said. ``The trucks
following the lead vehicle weren't shot at.''
   He identified the convoy leader as Gerard Vigay, a World Food
Program employee from France, and the driver as an unnamed Kenyan.
   Mitchell said the convoy halted briefly as armed rebel guards
unsuccesfully sought the attackers.
</TEXT>
