<FIRST>r w AM-FishWars     05-01 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Wars,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Protests Illegal Driftnet Fishing by Taiwanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has told the Taiwanese
that their relationship with the United States could suffer unless
they curb illegal driftnet fishing in the North Pacific, a U.S.
official said Monday.
   Ed Wolfe, ambassador for oceans and fisheries, said he delivered
a note of protest to an official of the Taiwanese Coordinating
Council for North American Affairs and warned of the possible
fallout if the government of Taiwan fails to negotiate a driftnet
fishing agreement with the United States.
   ``I delivered a forceful message regarding the potential serious
consequences of recent illegal fishing activities and the lack of
Taiwanese cooperation on driftnet negotiations, specifically the
enforcement aspect of those negotiations,'' said Wolfe.
   Wolfe said he told the Taiwanese that the fishing issue has
attracted interest at the ``highest levels'' of the State
Department and called for an ``immediate resumption of negotiations
to avoid potential bilateral foreign policy problems.''
   The meeting Friday came about a week after the Coast Guard
boarded a Taiwanese ship suspected of illegal driftnet fishing for
salmon in the North Pacific.
   The ship was spotted 450 miles outside the legal driftnet
fishing zone in waters where the Taiwanese government itself has
banned driftnetting. The ship allegedly cut its net and fled after
being spotted by the cutter Jarvis.
   The Jarvis shadowed the vessel for almost 700 miles before
receiving permission from the Taiwanese government to board.
   Wolfe said Monday that a fish scale and fin found on the ship
have been sent to a National Marine Fisheries Service laboratory to
see if they were from a salmon of North American origin.
   American fishermen claim vessels from Taiwan, South Korea and
Japan use driftnets to illegally snare millions of tons of salmon
under the guise of squid fishing. Fishing groups have said the
illegal fishing has already hurt salmon runs in Alaska, Washington
state and Oregon.
   Driftnets can stretch 35 miles in length and cover more than
30,000 square miles of ocean on any given day. Environmentalist
claim the nets are responsible for the deaths of thousands of
porpoises, seals, seabirds and other marine life annually.
</TEXT>
