<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-China     05-01 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-China,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Taiwan Delegation Visits China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from Taiwan arrived Monday on the first
visit to China by a Nationalist Chinese delegation since the
communists won the civil war in 1949 and Chiang Kai-shek's forces
fled to the island.
   The 12-member delegation led by Finance Minister Shirley Kuo
will attend the three-day annual meeting of the Asian Development
Bank that begins in the Chinese capital Thursday.
   ``We're happy that Taipei-China, like any other member of the
bank, will be able to attend this 22nd annual meeting of the ADB,''
said bank spokesman Reynaldo Pacheko.
   Ms. Kuo and the other delegation members went straight to the
hotel where the conference will be held.
   Taipei officials have said the delegation's only purpose is to
fulfill Taiwan's obligations as a founding member of the Asian
Development Bank and no official meetings will be held with the
Communist government.
   Since the defeat in 1949, the Nationalists have had a policy of
no contacts with mainland authorities. The bank meeting, however,
continues a practice of raising the level of exchange that began
with a softening of Taiwan's approach two years ago.
   Taiwan lifted restrictions on visits to the mainland late last
year and several thousand people have traveled to China for
reunions, tourism or business. Indirect trade has grown rapidly,
reaching an estimated $2.7 billion last year.
   Last month, young Taiwanese gymnasts became the first athletes
from the island to compete on the mainland, opening the way for
Taiwan's participation in the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing.
   Only 23 countries recognize Taiwan, while 136 have diplomatic
ties with the Beijing government.
   The Asian Development Bank, a regional development institution
established in 1966, is the only major international organization
in which Taiwan holds membership. It had to accept a name change
from Republic of China to Taipei- China when the 47-member
organization admitted China in 1986.
   Many in Taiwan, including members of the ruling party, see
adherence to the official policy of no contact as an attempt to
avoid the impression of eagerness until Taiwan is assured the
communists will consider it more than a local government.
   ``If this is not an official contact, then what is it?''
legislator Huang Ho-ching, a liberal member of the Nationalist
Party, said before the delegation left Taiwan.
   As a joke, he offered to give Ms. Kuo a pair of gloves so she
could shake hands with Chinese delegates without violating the
government's directive against direct contact.
   Early in April, Taiwan proposed that China be considered a
single nation with two governments, one in Beijing and the other in
Taipei. That would allow the island to rejoin international
organizations as an equal.
   Beijing rejected the idea, saying it would require abandonment
of the one-China policy.
</TEXT>
