<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     05-01 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Announce Monthlong Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Sudan's southern rebel
movement announced Monday a conditional monthlong cease-fire, which
he called a goodwill gesture toward ending a six-year civil war.
   John Garang, a renegade army colonel who leads the rebels, said
the unilateral truce will hold only as long as the government
carries out no troop movements in the war-torn south. This includes
reinforcing beleaguered army forces in the region, he said.
   There was no immediate government response to his offer, which
follows weeks of successes for the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army. Several government garrisons, including in the largest
southern town of Juba, are under severe pressure.
   In a statement broadcast by clandestine Radio SPLA, Garang said
he has ordered his forces to ``remain in their present positions''
throughout May.
   Army troops must do likewise, he said, but added a formula could
be worked out to allow provision of non-military supplies.
   ``Our people are suffering. It is our responsibility to end the
war,'' he said on the broadcast from Ethiopia and monitored in
Khartoum, the Sudanese capital.
   The United Nations in April began a relief operation to ease a
war-induced famine and the flight of potential victims. Garang
refused overtures to declare a ``month of tranquillity'' in the
south, but he did agree to allow passage of goods through specified
corridors.
   Unidentified attackers twice have ambushed U.N. food convoys
since then.
   On Monday, ambushers sprayed a vehicle with small arms fire near
the rebel-held town of Kapoeta. On April 18, a convoy was hit by a
rocket and automatic weapons fire, also near Kapoeta. Eight armed
rebel escorts were killed in that attack.
   Garang said the cease-fire will be extended if necessary and
called on the Sudanese government to reciprocate.
   He said his fighters will ``wait for the government to implement
the requirements of the Sudanese peace initiative, after which a
comprehensive cease-fire will be worked out.''
   In November, the rebels signed an agreement with the Democratic
Unionist Party calling for the suspension of harsh Islamic laws and
a constitutional conference of all political powers.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi initially refused to submit the
agreement to his Cabinet for endorsement. After pressure from the
army and professional organizations and trade unions, he formed a
new, broader-based government and won parliament's approval to
suspend the 1,400-year-old Islamic penal code.
   The rebels started fighting in 1983 against the Moslem-dominated
government, demanding social and economic reforms for the minority
Christians and animists of the south.
</TEXT>
