<DOCNO> AP890501-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush     05-01 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Hopes Gorbachev's Reforms Succeed, White House Brushes
Aside Cheney Comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he hopes Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev succeeds in his economic reforms, and
the White House brushed aside Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's
prediction that Gorbachev would fail.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Cheney's remarks,
in a weekend broadcast interview, were merely his own ``personal
observations'' and did not reflect the views of the administration,
which has adopted a public posture of trying to encourage Soviet
reforms.
   Bush, speaking to the annual meeting of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said, ``Even the socialist world is beginning to see that
socialism isn't just another economic system _ it's the death of
economics. And there is a new breeze blowing.''
   Bush said he told Gorbachev last year ``we wanted to see
perestroika (economic reforms) succeed in the Soviet Union. And
likewise, we want to see success for the economic reforms in
China.''
   The president did not mention Cheney or his remarks. Fitzwater
said he did not think Bush talked about the Soviet reforms because
of Cheney's comments. Rather, Fitzwater said, ``it was a natural
fit'' in a speech about economics.
   The White House and State Department joined forces to
disassociate the administration from Cheney, who had said of
Gorbachev, ``If I had to guess today, I would guess he ultimately
would fail.''
   In the broadcast interview, the Pentagon secretary predicted
Gorbachev then would be replaced by someone ``far more hostile''
toward the West.
   Last Tuesday, Cheney made similar remarks during testimony
before the House Armed Services Committee. He predicted ``a very
real likelihood'' that Gorbachev's reform plans would fail and that
the Soviet leader may either be forced to change course or hand
over power.
   Cheney told Congress that as a result, the United States and its
NATO allies must resist the temptation to respond to Gorbachev's
proposals for reducing arsenals and troop strengths and stick to
the policies it has advocated until now.
   In his speech, Bush said reform efforts in the Soviet Union,
China and other socialist countries were part of ``an exciting
trend and in my view it will continue.''
   ``Whenever in the world there is economic reform, the United
States should be hoping that that reform succeeds. Economic reform,
with its emphasis on incentive and market economics, leads to more
freedom,'' Bush said.
   He joked that the May Day parade in Moscow had included a
delegation from the Soviet Economic Planning Ministry _ 200
economists marching along yelling ``May Day, May Day.''
   However, Bush said, ``Today that is beginning to change.''
   At the White House, Fitzwater said, ``The administration's
position on the Soviet Union, whether expressed by President Bush,
Secretary Baker or Secretary Cheney, reflects the view that we want
reform to succeed.''
   Fitzwater, asked about Cheney's comments, said: ``I don't know
what his motivation was. In reading it (the transcript), it looks
like it was just a question that came up in the interview when he
offered his personal observations. I'm sure it wasn't part of any
grand strategy.''
   He said Bush had not talked with Cheney about the matter.
   On another subject, Fitzwater said the White House did not plan
to release documents that would buttress Bush's contention that
there was no link between his March 1985 meeting in Honduras and
that country's support for the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   Bush and others involved in that meeting ``have all said there
was no quid pro quo associated with the vice president's trip to
Honduras. However, there is no campaign to publicize information,''
Fitzwater said.
   On Capitol Hill, Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell,
D-Maine, said he has not changed his mind about the need for a
review of whether the Reagan White House withheld documents or
other key information from the congressional investigation of the
secret arms sales to Iran and aid to the Contras.
   ``We'll have the Intelligence Committee look into that,''
Mitchell said. ``Questions have arisen that I think ought to be
answered.... I think the Intelligence Committee will make a
thorough review of the matter.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
