<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Professors     05-01 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Professors,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Professors Protest Closure of Arab Universities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli professors Monday protested the
15-month closure of Palestinian universities and called the measure
an unwarranted collective punishment that threatens peace efforts.
   ``Even though closing the universities doesn't kill or maim, it
causes serious injury to the fabric of any society,'' said Ruth
Gavison, a law professor at Hebrew University. ``It disturbs life
in a way that is far reaching.''
   Israeli military authorities closed Bethlehem University on Oct.
29, 1987, and by February 1988 had shut the remaining Palestinian
universities in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. About 18,000
students are affected.
   Authorities called the colleges breeding grounds for
anti-Israeli protests.
   But the 1,200 professors from Israeli universities said the
closures threatened efforts to find moderate Palestinians with
which to negotiate an end to their 16-month uprising. At least 457
Arabs and 18 Israelis have died in clashes, mostly in the occupied
territories.
   ``Universities are the only place the moderate elements of the
Palestinian community can develop,'' said Hava Lazarus-Yafeh, a
professor of Asian and African studies at Hebrew University.
   ``Otherwise Palestinian leaders grow in prisons ... and leaders
who grow in jail tend to be more violent,'' she said.
   State-run primary and secondary schools in the West Bank have
also been closed for all but a few weeks since Feb. 4, 1988.
Kindergarten, first- and second-grade classes in some private
schools were allowed to reopen earlier this year.
   Authorities barred home study for university students and
refused to allow them to use college facilities such as
laboratories or libraries, said David Kretzmer, a Hebrew University
law professor. Recently, a West Bank university was refused
permission to open its Library, he said.
   ``It is hard to understand how opening a library to librarians
could endanger security,'' Kretzmer said.
   Hebrew University's Ms. Gavison called the closures a
``far-reaching collective measure.''
   ``Necessary security measures should be taken not against
institutions but against those individuals who have may have
violated order,'' she said.
   The longterm closures violate international statutes, such as
the Geneva Convention, which governs the treatment of people under
occupation, Kretzmer said.
   He said that a 1982 Israeli Supreme Court ruling determined
military closures of Palestinian schools could not surpass a
reasonable period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
