<DOCNO> AP890501-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-01 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodia Changes Name; Invites Back Banished Prince</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed
government has changed the country's name and flag, and invited its
banished prince to return home and help rule.
   In nearby Indonesia, resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk
welcomed the concessions and appeared ready to make a few of his
own to end the 10-year conflict.
   ``It seems that we are at the end of the tunnel. We are going to
make progress on the way toward a settlement,'' Sihanouk said on
Monday, the eve of new peace talks.
   Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia invited Sihanouk to abandon
his Khmer Rouge allies and ``join us.''
   The official Cambodian news agency SPK Monday quoted Hun Sen as
promising Sihanouk will have real power if he returns to Phnom
Penh. The comments, made at a Phnom Penh news conference Saturday,
appeared tailored for the peace talks in Jakarta, which now are
expected to last longer than a day.
   Hun Sen stopped in Bangkok on his way to Jakarta on Monday and
told reporters the changes are concessions to help settle the war.
He too said he was confident of success in the talks with Sihanouk.
   He said that on Sunday, the National Assembly unanimously
adopted constitutional amendments changing the ``People's Republic
of Kampuchea'' to ``The State of Cambodia.''
   Hun Sen sported a model of the new flag: the top half is red,
the bottom is blue and a gold image of Angkor Wat temple is in the
center. A new national anthem and coat of arms also are in the
works, he said.
   His government was installed by Vietnamese forces that invaded
the country in late 1978 and toppled the brutal Khmer Rouge regime.
It is battling a coalition of three guerrilla groups led by
Sihanouk.
   Diplomats say the changes are to strengthen the government's
domestic and international support as it begins to confront the
resistance without the help of Vietnam.
   Hanoi announced last month that it will withdraw its troops by
Sept. 30 to encourage a political settlement in Cambodia.
   Sihanouk and other resistance officials in the past have
demanded not only changing the country's name and flag, but also
dismantling the government before general elections.
   On Monday, Sihanouk said he would not insist on this, or U.N.
supervision of the Vietnamese withdrawal, so long as an adequate
power-sharing formula can be found.
   He also appeared to drop a call for Hun Sen to join a four-party
government that would include Sihanouk's non-communist followers,
anti-communists under former Premier Son Sann and the communist
Khmer Rouge.
   ``I had a good feeling when I left Phnom Penh that Prince
Norodom has already offered two concessions. If this is true, it
could lead to a political settlement,'' Hun Sen told reporters.
   Although he called on Sihanouk to join his government and
abandon the Khmer Rouge, Hun Sen also stressed the prince's options
are few.
   ``We have traveled 10 years without Sihanouk. We started with
empty hands and have established material and technical bases,''
Hun Sen said.
   The country was known as the Kingdom of Cambodia when Sihanouk
led it to independence from the French in 1953. Sihanouk ruled
until he was toppled in a 1970 coup by Marshal Lon Nol, who changed
the name to the Khmer Republic.
   The Khmer Rouge changed it to Democratic Kampuchea when they won
a civil war and overthrew Lon Nol's U.S.-backed government in April
1975. The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of people in
attempts to fashion a peasant society along fanatical communist
lines.
   The United Nations does not recognize the pro-Vietnamese
government. Instead it seats the guerrilla coalition formed in
1982, called the Coalition Government of Democratic Kampuchea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
