<DOCNO> AP890501-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1731EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w US-Japan     05-01 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>US-Japan,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>FSX Settlement Avoided Rift, Says New U.S. Envoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States averted a potentially
serious rift in U.S.-Japanese relations by going ahead with the
controversial agreement for the two countries to develop jointly a
new jet fighter for Japan, the new American ambassador to Tokyo
said Monday.
   Ambassador Michael Armacost told reporters that despite
persistent, strong objections to the project on Capitol Hill, ``I'm
confident it will meet with the acquiescence of our Congress.''
   President Bush announced Friday that the United States intends
to proceed with the FSX fighter program because it is ``in the
strategic and commercial interests of the United States.''
   After taking office in January, Bush ordered a review of the $7
billion project negotiated under his predecessor, Ronald Reagan.
Critics in Congress and the Commerce Department have said it
amounts to a giveaway of U.S. high technology and have said Japan
should make an ``off-the-shelf'' aircraft purchase, as do other
nations that are U.S. customers.
   Armacost brought up the negative side of scrapping the agreement
in an appearance at the Washington Foreign Press Center on the eve
of his departure for Japan, where he is due next week.
   Proceeding with the FSX project ``is important from our
standpoint because of what it avoided, namely (America and Japan)
going down separate tracks,'' he said. ``It avoids what could have
been an important breach in our relationship if this deal had gone
awry.''
   The FSX agreement ``is a good arrangement for both our
governments. We have had coproduction in past, but major
codevelopment is in a sense the first'' such arrangement with
Japan, said Armacost, a former undersecretary of state for
political affairs.
   ``I hope this will be a model of the flow of two-way technology
which is quite appropriate to a more mature relationship between
our countries in this field,'' the ambassador said.
   The White House said Monday that, with Japan, Bush ``has been
very tough in demanding equity for the United States in terms of
its commercial interests,'' and he ``was successful in getting
everything he asked for.'' Friday's announcement said U.S.
companies would be guaranteed about 40 percent of the production
work on the planned 130 new fighters while certain computer codes
from the U.S. F-16 jet, which provides the model for the FSX, would
be withheld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
