<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     05-01 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Night Stalker' Witness Was Untruthful, Prosecution Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness against the defendant in the
``Night Stalker'' serial murder trial failed to tell the whole
truth, the prosecutor in the case disclosed Monday.
   The unexpected move by Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin
stalled the opening of Richard Ramirez's defense case as Halpin won
permission to reopen his case to question the witness again.
   Jurors were told ``something has come up'' to abort Monday's
court session and were instructed to return Tuesday, when the
witness is to appear.
   Ramirez, 29, a drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged with 13
gruesome murders and 30 related felonies in a string of nighttime
attacks that terrified southern California in the summer of 1985.
   Halpin said the omitted testimony is ``nothing spectacular. ...
It's not significant evidence.'' But he said he was duty-bound to
reveal the omission, which he discovered after he rested his case
April 13 and the judge ordered a two-week recess.
   Halpin, who had called 137 people to testify since opening his
case Jan. 30, refused to identify the witness or describe the
missing evidence. He said only that the witness told him ``the
testimony was withheld to protect someone, to protect a woman.''
   Ramirez had expected his attorney, Daniel Hernandez, to deliver
his opening statement to the jury.
   ``If the district attorney is going to stop the procedures for
this one witness, it must be very significant,'' Hernandez said
outside court.
   But his co-counsel, Ray Clark, said it was not unusual to find
out that a witness didn't tell the whole truth. ``Most witnesses
fudge,'' he said.
   Halpin said the witness is not a victim or survivor of the Night
Stalker attacks of 1985. He said that during the recess he asked
that a few witnesses be interviewed again by investigators.
   ``There ware a couple of things concerning me,'' he said, ``a
lot of hearsay floating around.''
   He added: ``I don't think the testimony is going to change
anything in this case.''
</TEXT>
