<FIRST>r w AM-AirForce-Bombers     05-01 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force-Bombers,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress to Take Close Look at Request for More B-1 Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers said Monday that Congress, painfully
aware of the more than $20 billion invested in the B-1 bomber, will
take a close look at an Air Force request for an additional $1.2
billion to correct major flaws.
   ``It doesn't make a lot of sense not to make the B-1 work if you
can do it,'' said Rep. Marvin Leath, D-Texas, a member of the House
Armed Services Committee. ``We really have to put the arm on the
Air Force.''
   The service has proposed spending the extra $1.2 billion over
five years to improve the B-1, the swing-wing plane resurrected by
then-President Reagan in 1981 as the answer to the aging of the
nation's force of nuclear-armed bombers.
   The B-1B fleet has experienced major problems. Three of the
original 100 ordered by Reagan have crashed and two months ago the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress,
concluded that the cost of planned improvements could be nearly
$400 million for each bomber.
   The GAO cited problems with the aircraft's defense system and
also troubles with fuel leaks.
   In a memorandum circulated to members of the House Armed
Services procurement subcommittee last week, committee chairman Les
Aspin, D-Wis., questioned whether spending more money would solve
the fleet's problems.
   ``Even when these fixes are made, the plane will fall far short
of the original electronic countermeasure specifications. We'll
have to decide if improvement planned is worth the money,'' Aspin
said.
   Congress will review the request within the next two months as
part of the defense authorization process.
   Rep. Andy Ireland, R-Fla., a member of the Armed Services
Committee, said the country has spent more than $20 billion on the
fleet, and abandoning that investment would be difficult.
   ``We do have 97 already invested. We need to finish them up
again under close scrutiny,'' said Ireland.
   The Florida Republican said the B-1 ``performs substantially as
expected in a lot, a lot of ways,'' but an ``area of skepticism
needs to prevail.''
   In addition to the funding request for the B-1, the Air Force
also has proposed shifting nearly $300 million for procurement of
the B-2 stealth bomber to research and development on the aircraft.
   ``We have to take a long, hard look at the B-2,'' said Leath.
``That thing is going to consume tons and tons of money, and I'm
not sure at this point after going through the B-1 if we're up to
that.''
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has already proposed pushing back
production of the B-2 to 1993, and almost $4.1 billion is being cut
from the fiscal 1990 and 1991 budgets for the radar-evading plane.
Recent estimates of $500 million per plane would make it the most
expensive in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
