<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-USSubmarine     05-01 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Submarine,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers Check Waters off Japan for Two U.S. Sailors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY20</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese searchers combed waters off the
southern island of Kyushu for two crewmen of a U.S. Navy submarine
who were washed overboard Monday by a wave during predawn surface
operations.
   Navy officials said the diesel-powered Barbel was carrying out a
routine mission earlier in the day when a wave crashed onto its
desk, sweeping away three crewmen. They gave no details on what the
operation involved.
   One of the crewmen, identified by the Navy as Lt. Richard
Davenport of Norfolk, Va., was rescued by the submarine soon
afterward. Medical personnel on the submarine were treating him for
mild hypothermia, U.S. military spokesman Master Gunnery Sgt. Jake
Rodrigues said.
   The missing men were identified as fireman apprentice James
David Lear of Washburn, Ill. and Lt. Walter Gray Womble II of
Virginia Beach, Va.
   The three crewmen were standing watch without life jackets
because the seas looked relatively calm, Navy officers said.
   Kiyoshi Harada, spokesman for Japan's Maritime Safety Agency,
said the accident occurred about 31 miles southwest of Noma Cape in
Kagoshima Prefecture, or state. The area off Japan's southernmost
main island is about 650 miles southwest of Tokyo.
   Fog and high-wind alerts were in effect at the time of the
accident, but the height of the waves and wind speed are not known,
according to Yoshikazu Nakamura of the local branch of the Maritime
Self-Defense Force.
   The Barbel and another U.S. vessel joined several Japanese ships
and airplanes in the search that went on into Monday night,
officials of both countries said.
   A Japanese Defense Agency official said the submarine had
surfaced before the accident because it was taking on water from a
hatch. He spoke on condition of anonymity and refused to elaborate.
   But a U.S. Navy spokesman based in Yokosuka denied that report.
``We have no information that there is anything wrong with the
Barbel,'' said Navy Lt. Jeff Gradeck.
   However, a Pentagon spokesman said the submarine had some
electrical problems after the wave that hit the men also washed
into its conning tower, which is used as an entrance. The damage
was quickly repaired, said Lt. Cmdr. Jim Kudla, a Pentagon
spokesman.
   The Barbel, built in 1956, is equipped with six torpedo tubes
and normally carries a crew of 77, U.S. military officials said.
The 219-foot-long, 2,145-ton vessel belongs to the last non-nuclear
combat submarine class built by the Navy.
</TEXT>
