<FIRST>r w AM-Afghan-GasMasks     05-01 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Gas Masks,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gas Masks Issued to Afghan Troops in City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan government commanders have issued
Soviet-made gas masks to their troops in the besieged city of
Jalalabad, according to a telephone reports from guerrilla leader.
   Gen. Abdul Rahim Wardak, military commander of the National
Islamic Front of Afghanistan, conveyed the information by telephone
from Peshawar, Pakistan, on April 25 to Marin Strmecki, a
Washington-based analyst who recently returned from Jalalabad.
   ``He informed me by telephone that the Afghan government troops
had been issued gas masks and other chemical warfare equipment, for
example, protective suits and the launchers for chemical warfare
shells,'' Strmecki said Monday.
   The troops, loyal to the Soviet-backed government in Kabul, have
not used chemical weapons to break the siege, said Strmecki, an
aide to former national security adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
   Some reports have implied the failure of the attack against
Jalalabad, involving an estimated 15,000 anti-communist Mujahedeen
guerrillas and a slightly smaller force loyal to the Soviet-backed
government.
   The city, in eastern Afghanistan, was viewed as a gateway to
Kabul.
   Another recent visitor to Afghanistan, Charles Schnabel,
assistant to Rep. Charles Wilson, D-Texas, said he saw Soviet-made
gas masks during a trip to other parts of Afghanistan that ended
last Dec. 13.
   ``I was going to bring some back, but I got tired of carrying
them. These were a long way inside Afghanistan,'' said Schnabel.
   The congressional aide said he heard numerous reports of the use
of chemical weapons, but found no eyewitnesses and did not believe
government troops would use them to defend Jalalabad.
   ``If your back is to the wall, you might do something like that.
There appears to me to a stalemate. So it doesn't appear to me that
they would use it,'' he said.
   Strmecki did not depict the battle as a stalemate, and forecast
a Mujahedeen victory.
   Wardak reported the Mujahedeen ``are slowly and inexorably
tightening a ring around Jalalabad,'' and are within three miles of
the city center, Strmecki said.
   Strmecki said he had visited the eastern and northern edges of
Jalalabad on March 12, six days after Mujahedeen began their siege.
   Government forces, he said, were inflicting heavy casualties on
the guerrillas with high altitude bombing runs by MiG-27 fighters
and converted Antonov-12 transport planes operating above the range
of U.S.-supplied Stinger anti-aircraft missiles, said Strmecki.
   The Jalalabad airport has been closed since the siege began, and
government resupply efforts have been confined to about 20 or 25
helicopter deliveries per day, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
