<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PLO     05-01 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Expects Paris Visit to Aid Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat said he expects his first
official visit to Paris on Tuesday to give Middle East peace
efforts a ``push forward.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization chairman said in an
interview Monday he has ``great confidence'' in Francois
Mitterrand, the French president, as ``a man of principles and a
supporter of the cause of justice.''
   He criticized French Jewish leaders who have protested the visit
and declared: ``I'm sure those who are interested in seeing peace
prevail will change their minds and support the visit, which will
certainly give further impetus to peace moves.''
   Jewish groups have said they will mount protests during the
two-day visit. Arafat will meet with Mitterrand, Premier Michel
Rocard and Foreign Minister Roland Dumas.
   He will be accompanied by Farouk Kaddoumi, head of the PLO
political department; Yasser Abed-Rabbo, the information director,
and Mohammed Milhem and Mahmoud Darwish, members of the Executive
Committee.
   Kaddoumi acts as the PLO foreign minister and Abed-Rabbo has led
the PLO team in meetings with the United States in Tunis.
   PLO sources said Arafat's media adviser, Bassam Abu Sharif, and
spokesman Ahmed Abdel-Rahman also would make the trip to Paris.
   Washington ended its 13-year ban on dealings with the PLO in
December and initiated a dialogue after Arafat renounced terrorism
and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   The changed U.S. attitude and nearly 17 months of Palestinian
rebellion against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip have helped alter Western Europe's perception of the PLO.
Several countries have begun direct contacts.
   Arafat said in the interview, at his heavily guarded military
headquarters in Baghdad: ``I will discuss with President Mitterrand
everything ... including our peace initiatives.
   ``I will be ready to hear from him his ideas on the Middle East
and the Palestinian issue in particular. I have great expectations
that my visit to France and my meetings there will push forward the
peace efforts in the region.''
   In Paris, about 2,000 police were mobilized for the visit,
authorities said. Sharpshooters were stationed on rooftops and
helicopters patrolled overhead.
   Simultaneous demonstrations were planned for Tuesday evening,
one by Arafat supporters and the other by Jewish protesters.
   Premier Rocard told journalists Sunday night the protocol would
not equal that accorded a chief of state because Arafat ``is
neither a head of state nor a prime minister. He is being treated
according to his level of dignity.''
   Neither Mitterrand nor Rocard will meet Arafat at Orly airport,
for example.
   An independent Palestinian state was declared last November at a
meeting of the Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO
legislature.
   On Monday, the Israeli Foreign Ministry complained that the
insignia adopted for it features a map incorporating most of Israel.
   ``It is worrying,'' a ministry official said privately. ``They
say they want the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. Now they introduce
a logo, and it includes Israel.''
   He gave reporters copies of two letters with the insignia, one
signed by Arafat and the other by Nabil Ramlawi, PLO representative
to the United Nations in Geneva.
   In the insignia's center is a map that includes the West Bank,
Gaza Strip and all of Israel except the Golan Heights.
   Israel captured the three territories in the 1967 Middle East
war. It annexed the Golan Heights, taken from Syria, in December
1981.
</TEXT>
