<FIRST>r w AM-OASAppointment     05-01 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OAS Appointment,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran State Department Hand in Line for OAS Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is expected to name one of the
State Department's most experienced Latin American hands as
ambassador to the Organization of American States as part of a plan
to revitalize that 31-member institution, U.S. officials said
Monday.
   Luigi Einaudi, 52, director of policy planning at the State
Department since 1977, is in line to replace former Ambassador
Richard McCormack in the OAS post, said the officials, who asked
not to be identified.
   Einaudi has been a right hand man to the last six assistant
secretaries of state for inter-American affairs. He was once
described by former Secretary of State George P. Shultz as ``the
State Department's leading expert on U.S.-Latin American
relations.''
   At one time, the OAS was the principal forum for hemispheric
debate but it has declined in importance over the past generation.
The officials said Secretary of State James A. Baker III envisions
a more active role for the OAS in narcotics control and other areas.
   In response to a budget crisis that was partly brought on by the
U.S. failure to pay its promised share, the OAS has negotiated
early retirement for about 300 employees over the past several
weeks, which is about 30 per cent of the workforce, the officials
said.
</TEXT>
