<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0595 05-01 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0595,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Group Says April 2nd Bloodiest Month of Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 15 wounded, report that PLO
officials abroad approve most orders to kill collaborators. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Palestinians killed by soldiers
in April was the second highest monthly total of the long uprising
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, an Israeli human rights
group said Monday.
   Also Monday, Palestinian sources said PLO officials abroad
approve most orders to kill Arabs suspected of collaborating with
Israel.
   The Israeli Information Center for Human Rights in the
Territories said soldiers killed 34 Palestinians in April, but the
army disputed the figure. The organization said the monthly total
was second only to 44 killed in April 1988.
   Doctors at Mukassad hospital in Jerusalem said 10-year-old Samir
Merai died Monday of a wound suffered Wednesday in a confrontation
with soldiers at the Tulkarem refugee camp in the West Bank.
   They said he was hit by a plastic bullet that penetrated his eye
and lodged in his brain. The army said it was checking the report.
   Ahed Ramini, a 30-year-old Palestinian was stabbed to death
Monday as an alleged collaborator with Israel.
   A military spokesman confirmed Ramini was killed by masked
youths in Tulkarem town and said the circumstances were being
investigated. The army put the town under curfew, ordering all
30,000 residents to remain at home.
   Chaim Ben Lulu, a 52-year-old Jewish settler arrested in
connection with the shooting death of a 14-year-old Palestinian,
was released on bail of about $13,880.
   Police said he still could be charged in the attack, which
occurred Friday in the West Bank city of Hebron.
   ``I clearly acted in self-defense,'' Ben Lulu said on Israel
radio after his release. Newspapers had quoted him earlier as
saying he fired into the air.
   Palestinians and Israeli Arabs used May Day on Monday to
demonstrate for an independent Palestinian state in the West Bank
and Gaza. About 2,000 people marched in Nazareth.
   Police fired tear gas and rubber bullets to disperse about 50
marchers in Arab east Jerusalem, slightly injuring three.
Authorities said the demonstrators did not have a permit and 15
were arrested.
   Arab reports said soldiers wounded 15 Palestinians in the West
Bank and Gaza, including a 16-year-old boy with a serious chest
wound. The army confirmed three people were wounded.
   The human rights center, founded by leftist parties and peace
movements, said 33 of the Palestinian fatalities in April were
caused by gunshot wounds and the 34th died of beating injuries
inflicted by soldiers.
   An army spokesman said 28 Palestinians were killed and death
tolls were higher in several other months.
   According to the human rights group, 423 Palestinians have been
killed by army gunfire in the uprising. The army figure is 351.
   An Associated Press count shows 458 Palestinian deaths,
including 41 people killed by other Palestinians as suspected
collaborators. Eighteen Israelis also have died.
   Alon Liel, Foreign Ministry spokesman, said at least 10 alleged
collaborators were killed in April, ``the bloodiest month from the
point of view of Palestinian attacks on Palestinians.''
   ``It isn't a coincidence that it came in the month after (Prime
Minister Yitzhak) Shamir suggested elections in the territories''
to chose Palestinians to negotiate an interim peace agreement, he
said.
   Liel said he did not know if any of the victims supported
Shamir's election plan. Palestinian sources say those slain by
other Palestinians are killed for informing and other acts of
collaboration, not for their political beliefs.
   Palestinian sources said local Palestinian activists conduct
underground ``trials'' of Arabs suspected of collaborating with
Israel, and then PLO officials abroad approve most orders to kill
those found guilty.
   The PLO headquarters in Tunis had no immediate comment on the
report.
   The Palestinian sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the orders to kill the alleged collaborators were made by a
Moslem clergyman believed to be based in Iraq.
   The sources said orders are relayed via coded messages broadcast
by Baghdad Radio.
   Israeli soldiers detained a former Jordanian Parliament member,
Farouq Hamdallah, for ``security reasons,'' said the army without
elaborating.
   Israel radio said Hamdallah was detained after endorsing
Palestinian attacks on Arab collaborators in a newspaper interview
this week.
   Hamdallah, of the West Bank town of Anabta, was one of 30
Palestinians who represented the territory in the Jordanian
legislature from 1984 to 1988.
</TEXT>
