<FIRST>r i AM-MissingUSSailor     05-01 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing US Sailor,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing American Sailor Turns Up in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American sailor who vanished from a U.S.
base in Naples nine months ago and was feared dead turned up alive
Monday, hours after her photograph appeared on television, Italian
authorities said.
   A highway patrolman saw Jennifer Muir, a 22-year-old Navy petty
officer third class, on a roadside outside Villa San Giovanni in
southern Calabria at about 4 a.m. and recognized her, said police
Col. Antonino Di Vincenzo.
   The ANSA news agency said another patrolman also saw the show
about missing persons broadcast Sunday night by RAI-TV. On it, Miss
Muir's father Thomas, an IBM engineer from Trumbull, Conn.,
appealed for help in finding her.
   She vanished July 29 from a U.S. military base in Naples and
Italian police originally suspected foul play.
   Di Vincenzo said Monday from police headquarters in Reggio
Calabria: ``She's fine and has been reunited with her father.''
   He said Miss Muir apparently had been living with a man in Villa
San Giovanni, in the toe of the Italian boot.
   Police brought her to Naples on Monday evening for questioning
by a magistrate before being turned over to U.S. military
authorities, ANSA said.
   Lt. Paul Weishaupt, a U.S. Navy spokesman in Naples, said
earlier that Italian authorities informed the Navy they had an
American woman in custody who identified herself as Jennifer Muir.
   Miss Muir had been assigned to the U.S. Military Sealift Command
in Naples.
   In October, an Italian magistrate named an American seaman as
being suspected of murder and concealing a body. He was delivered
to U.S. custody later and no charges have been filed, Weishaupt
said.
</TEXT>
