<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru a0650 05-01 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Shooting Rampage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB grafs 4-5, `Kenneth Macintosh...trouble here.'' with 3 grafs
UPDATING with four hospitalized, additional charges probable. Picks up
6th graf, `A neighbor...' SUBBING 11th graf, `Britons were...' to RECAST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITLEY BAY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday charged a
22-year-old civil servant with murder in a shooting spree that
killed one man and wounded 14 people in a coastal town.
   Lawmakers called for tightening Britain's already strict gun
control laws following the 15-minute shotgun rampage Sunday
afternoon.
   Police arrested Robert Sartin, 22, shortly after the attack in
Monkseaton, a fashionable suburb of the Whitley Bay seaside resort
in northeast England. Dressed in black and wearing sunglasses and
an ammunition belt, the gunman walked the streets shooting
indiscriminately, witnesses said.
   Kenneth Mackintosh, 41, married and the father of two children,
was killed. Four of the 14 wounded remained hospitalized Monday,
three in serious condition.
   On Monday, police granted the suspect a five-minute visit with
his parents, then announced his identity and said he was charged
with the slaying of Mackintosh.
   Detective Superintendent Bob Benton told reporters Sartin
probably will be charged with other offenses later.
   A neighbor of Sartin said she was ``absolutely stunned'' to hear
of the young man's arrest. The woman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said ``he was always a nice boy. ... He has never given
any trouble here.''
   Police said the shotgun found in his car during his arrest was
licensed to his father.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet minister responsible
for law and order, asked for a police report into the shootings.
   Britain's gun laws were tightened following the country's worst
mass murder in August 1987. Gun collector Michael Ryan ran through
Hungerford, 60 miles west of London, killing 16 people, including
his mother, before turning his gun on himself.
   The new laws banned sawed-off shotguns, mortars and self-loading
rifles, a high-powered weapon similar to that used by Ryan.
   Britons were already prohibited from owning such automatic
weapons as machine guns and must obtain a license to own other
weapons. Applicants for gun licenses must satisfy police they have
a good reason to own each firearm and its ammunition, a suitable
place to use them and can store them securely to prevent theft.
   But police and lawmakers said Monday that too many loopholes
remain in the law.
   ``It's far too easy for people to get ahold of shotguns,'' said
Alan Eastwood, chairman of the Police Federation, which represents
more than 120,000 police officers.
   Lawmaker David Winnick of the opposition Labor Party said the
government should make it more difficult for individuals to obtain
a license to own a shotgun. His colleague, Ted Leadbitter, called
for a ban on individuals owning any firearms for private use.
   However, Anthony Beaumont-Dark, member of Parliament for the
governing Conservative Party, cautioned against a ``knee-jerk
reaction.''
   The British Association for Shooting and Conservation said
tighter laws were not the answer.
   ``There are nearly a million legitimate shotgun holders in
Britain,'' said director John Swift. ``One man dressed in black
leather with a knife strapped to his thigh has nothing to do with
those ordinary men and women who take part in country shooting.''
</TEXT>
