<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia     05-01 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Youths On Hunger Strike in Soviet Georgia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight men from Soviet Georgia were holding a
hunger strike in a Tbilisi hospital and demanding an antidote to
gas used by soldiers to quell a nationalist demonstration, a
Georgian activist said Monday.
   The men, ranging in age from 19 to 26, have been fasting since
Friday, said David Nadiradze, a member of a Georgian
pro-independence group. He said they also are demanding an
inspection by the International Red Cross.
   Nadiradze said in a telephone interview that the strike aimed to
``defend the poisoned people,'' referring to the dozens of Tbilisi
residents still hospitalized with symptoms that Georgian health
officials say resemble the effects of nerve gas.
   At least 20 people died and 1,100 were injured in ethnic unrest
in Tbilisi, the capital of Georgia, on April 9. Georgian activists
say the soldiers attacked a peaceful demonstration with shovels,
clubs and chemicals.
   Soviet officials have acknowledged tear gas was used on some
protesters, but they deny nerve gas or other lethal chemical
weapons were turned on the demonstrators.
   Members of a citizen's commission investigating the
confrontation and doctors treating victims say a second gas that
paralyzes the central nervous system was used.
   Georgia's Communist Party chief, Givi Gumbaridze, said some
victims died of gas poisoning.
   The southern republic's minister of internal affairs, Shota
Gorgodze, on Monday denied a military officer's claim that soldiers
and their families have been beaten and their apartments stoned
because citizens blame them for the April 9 confrontation.
   Pravda quoted Gorgodze as saying that his ministry had received
eight reports of attacks against soldiers, and all turned out to be
false. He said no official complaints had come in of attacks
against families, and rumors to that effect proved wrong.
   Gen. I.N. Rodionov, commander of the Caucasus military district,
said Saturday that people in Tbilisi are blaming Red Army soldiers
for the clash and taking revenge on their families.
   He pointed out the troops involved belonged to the Interior
Ministry and suggested they should wear special uniforms that would
help identify them.
   Demonstrations in Georgia first began April 4 when protesters
criticized calls from members of the republic's ethnic Abkhazian
minority to break away because of alleged discrimination by
Georgians.
   Other protesters have demanded Georgia secede from the Soviet
Union because of alleged interference from the central government.
</TEXT>
