<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HealthInsurance     05-01 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Insurance,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Bush Adviser Criticizes Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expansion of private and public health
insurance to the nation's 37 million uninsured is ill-advised
because it doesn't target people who need help most and doesn't
curtail spiraling health care costs, a former health adviser to
President Bush said Monday.
   The testimony from Deborah Steelman, a Washington lawyer and
formerly chief health adviser to the Bush, came as the Senate Labor
and Human Resources opened hearings on the measure introduced by
the panel's chairman, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. Henry
A. Waxman, D-Calif.
   While Steelman now has no formal ties with the Bush
administration, she is widely regarded as an expert on health
financing issues and the criticism she laid out of the
Kennedy-Waxman bill amounted to a blueprint of the strong
opposition to the legislation that is likely to produce protracted
debate.
   ``This bill offers no proposals to counteract a dangerous trend:
Over the last 15 years, health-care expenditures in the United
States have risen at an average annual rate of 12 percent,'' she
said.
   Kennedy has acknowledged that his bill does not try to get at
the larger issue of across-the-board health cost control, but says
that shouldn't be used as a reason to oppose it.
   Kennedy and other proponents maintain it would be unfair to wait
until broad-based programs to control costs are developed before
extending health care to the uninsured.
   The Massachusetts Democrat has acknowledged that his bill
probably would cost an additional $12 billion a year when fully
phased in about 10 years, but argues that costs should not stand in
the way of a nation taking care of its ill and injured.
   Steelman, however, predicted ``there will be great fanfare over
minor increases totaling less than $500 million nationwide'' and
questioned where the support would come for such massive
expenditures as envisioned by the Kennedy bill.
   ``We have not seen any domestic program increases of this since
at either the state or federal level, since the early 70's,'' she
said.
   She said there are variety of ways to deal with the problem of
the medically insured, but argued that Kennedy's bill tries to do
too much through a government program.
   ``Obviously, the proper role of government and the first
priority of a program for the uninsured must be to cover low-income
individuals through a carefully targeted improved and expanded
Medicaid program,'' she said.
   The bill was supported by a panel of four individuals who
recounted their difficulties in paying medical bills on low
salaries and by representatives of th American Public Welfare
Association, the National Association of Public Hospitals, and the
American Diabetes Association.
</TEXT>
