<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0628 05-01 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian, Christian Forces Battle Despite Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: ADDS three grafs to UPDATE with bombardment preventing ship
from unloading cargo. No pickup. ^By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian forces pounded the coast north of
Beirut on Monday after a night of tank and mortar battles with
Christian army units outside the city despite a three-day truce.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt demanded Christians topple their
Gen. Michel Aoun as a condition for peace, and Aoun charged the
Syrian-Druse alliance broke the cease-fire organized Friday by the
Arab League.
   Police said two Lebanese soldiers were killed and seven
civilians wounded in overnight fighting around the Christian
garrison town of Souk el-Gharb _ the first casualties since Friday.
   Jumblatt's spokesman announced in Damascus, Syria, that
Christian shells Monday killed one of their militiamen and wounded
two.
   This brings the toll to 276 people killed and 1,002 wounded
since March 8, when fighting erupted.
   Rocket-propelled grenades and anti-aircraft fire crackled Monday
across the abandoned commercial district straddling Beirut's port.
   ``This ominous escalation ... threatens plans by the Arab League
to dispatch a pan-Arab observer force to Lebanon to monitor the
truce,'' said a police spokesman who cannot be identified under
regulations.
   Despite the fighting, neither side appears to consider the truce
irretrievable.
   Beirut radio stations said Lakhdar Ibrahimi, the Algerian envoy
of Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi, was due in Beirut
within 24 hours to finalize deployment of the multinational Arab
observer force.
   The police spokesman said at least 45 shells and rockets
exploded on a 10-mile strip of beach between Byblos and Jounieh
ports, paralyzing shipping activity.
   An Aoun spokesman said his units ``fired back in self-defense''
in Souk el-Gharb and Beirut port, but did not respond to shelling
of the Christian coastline.
   Souk el-Gharb sits atop a strategic network of mountain roads.
If it falls, the Moslems will be poised to flush out the Christians
from mountain strongholds protecting their 310-square-mile enclave.
Syrian army troops and the Druse militia outnumber Aoun's mainly
Christian army by 3-1.
   Jumblatt issued a May Day statement saying: ``It's impossible to
reach a compromise with Michel Aoun. He must be removed or
toppled.''
   Aoun, who also heads the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, has refused to call off the blockade of three illegal
harbors run by Moslem militias, which triggered the fighting.
   Although the Arab League cease-fire plan provides for lifting
air, sea and land blockades, Aoun contends his gunboats and
helicopter gunships are ``applying Lebanese laws.''
   The rival Moslem Cabinet under Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss
has insisted raising the blockade ``is an integral part of the Arab
League's peace plan. Without it there will be no cease-fire.''
   Aoun imposed the blockade in a bid to restore state authority
and recoup lost annual taxes of $100 million.
   The rival Cabinets emerged in September after outgoing President
Amin Gemayel and Parliament was unable to elect a new leader.
   The French navy tanker Penhors returned to Lebanese waters
Monday with 15,000 tons of fuel from the European Economic
Community to boost rationed electricty in Beirut.
   The rival Cabinets said the tanker will unload 75 percent of the
shipment in the Christian port of Zouk and the rest in the Moslem
oil terminal of Zahrani.
   Christian radio stations later said the Syrian bombardment
prevented the Penhors from approaching Zouk.
   Police and the French Embassy withheld comment. But Hoss, who
had pledged to the 12-nation trade bloc that no shelling would
occur when the Penhors approached, apologized.
   ``I feel bound to extend my apology to the European Community
for being unable to honor my obligations due to surprise
developments that caused a delay in the unloading operation,'' he
said in a statement.
</TEXT>
