<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-JailRiot     05-01 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Jail Riot,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoners Riot to Protest Jail Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARRINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners rampaged through two cell
wings of a jail Monday, and dozens conducted a rooftop protest of
living conditions, prison officers reported.
   The Risley remand center, designed to hold just over 500 men in
single cells, now accommodates 600 men and 140 women awaiting
trial. It is near Warrington, 10 miles east of Liverpool on the
northwest coast.
   Trouble began Sunday night when 17 prisoners tried to overpower
guards who were unlocking cells in B wing for an exercise period,
authorities said.
   Scores of men wrecked furniture and water pipes. A similar
incident began in D wing Monday when it was announced that visits
would be canceled because of the violence, officials said.
   They said B wing was under control Monday night but up to 40
inmates remained on the roof of D wing. Several who hurled objects
from the roof at prison officers wore hoods to hide their faces.
   Three cell areas were wrecked and both wings were flooded by
water from the broken pipes, said Graham Harrison, chairman of the
Risley branch of the Prison Officers' Association.
   Four guards suffered minor injuries to fingers or ribs but no
prisoners were injured, he said.
   Two guards locked themselves in a second-floor cell when the
prisoners broke out, their colleagues said. Rioters tried to enter
the cell to get at the men, but other officers rescued them by
breaking through an outside wall with sledgehammers, they said.
   Banners on the roof repeated common complaints about conditions
in the jail.
   A report last year by the Inspector of Prisons described
conditions at Risley as ``squalid and barbarous.'' The
investigation was conducted after seven suicides were reported at
the jail in 18 months.
   Several prisoner protests, including rooftop demonstrations,
have occurred since.
   Harrison said 250 inmates were moved from Risley to nearby jails
Monday because their cells were smashed.
   ``Most of those who have been moved out have not been involved
in the trouble, but we had to move them because they had nowhere to
sleep,'' he said.
</TEXT>
