<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rumble Through Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled through the Southeast on Monday and heavy
rains drenched much of the East, flooding parts of North Carolina
and Kentucky and washing out two small bridges in Indiana.
   A tornado touched down in southeast Georgia near Leesburg, but
there were no reports of damage.
   A thunderstorm whipped up strong winds south of Lake City, Fla.,
that uprooted trees and produced small hail. Thunderstorm winds
also caused damage in Acree, Ga.
   Thunderstorms and showers extended Monday afternoon from
northern Florida to eastern Alabama, Georgia, the Carolinas,
eastern Tennessee, eastern Kentucky, West Virginia, Virginia,
Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, eastern Ohio and
southern New York. Scattered rain fell from eastern Iowa to
northeast Minneosta and northwest Illinois.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included more than 2 inches at Atlanta, and more than an 1{ inches
at Troy, Ala., Dothan, Ala., and Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   Heavy thunderstorm rains washed out two small bridges near
Hartsville in southeastern Indiana, and many roads were underwater.
   Rain also caused flooding in the southeast Kentucky towns of
Letcher, Whitesburg and Jenkins, and in Raleigh, N.C.
   The low temperature for the nation Monday morning was 9 degrees
at Gunnison, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT
ranged from 39 degrees at Grand Marais, Minn., and Moline, Ill., to
92 at Cottula, Texas.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms
from the Florida Peninsula to the Georgia coast and the coasts of
North and South Carolina; showers from the rest of Virginia to New
England, the Ohio Valley and the lower Great Lakes region, as well
as in northwest and north central Montana; and scattered showers
over north central Texas.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 50s from New England to
the Great Lakes and the Ohio Valley, and in Montana; the 60s and
70s from New Jersey to North Carolina, the Tennessee Valley, inland
sections of the central Gulf Coast states, much of the Mississippi
Valley, central Texas, northern sections of New Mexico and Arizona,
Nevada, the northern third of California and the rest of the
California coast, and the Pacific Northwest, as well as in the
Dakotas and the rest of Montana; the 90s in the desert Southwest;
and in the 80s in the rest of the nation.
