<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Panama 1stld-writethru a0600 05-01 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Panama, 1st ld-writethru, a0600,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Panama's Military Should Defy Noriega on Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with statement from four senators, inserts 4 grafs
after 6th graf previous, Asked for </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III called
Monday on Panama's Defense Forces to ensure next Sunday's elections
are fair by blocking what he said are Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
efforts to rig the balloting through ``massive fraud.''
   Baker issued the unusual appeal in a State Department speech but
left unclear the precise steps he believes the Defense Forces
should take in defiance of their commander.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said later that Baker feels all
institutions in Panama, including the Defense Forces, should do
what is necessary to promote an honest outcome next Sunday.
   Speaking to the Council of the Americas, a business group, Baker
said the military forces are the key to a free election.
   ``They can fulfill their constitutional duty as professional
soldiers and allow the elections to proceed freely and fairly. Or
they can face the consequences of the path on which Gen. Noriega
has placed them,'' Baker said.
   Asked for elaboration, Ms. Tutwiler said Baker was merely
pointing out that all of the people and institutions in Panama,
including the Defense Forces, ``are paying a price because of the
isolation and economic crisis'' resulting from Noriega's rule.
   Meanwhile, four U.S. senators, two from each party, wound up a
visit to Panama and predicted that ``we are about to see a totally
fraudulent election.''
   In a statement, they said they had learned Noriega's government
will be the only organization permitted to count the votes, that
the Panamanian Defense Force which he commands will be responsible
for safeguarding the ballots, that no exit polling will be
permitted and that following the government tally, all ballots will
be burned.
   In a letter, the senators urged the Organization of American
States to demand that Noriega permit the election to be ``free,
fair and open'' and said they were concerned that the continuation
of undemocratic government in Panama ``would also likely result in
a situation dangerous for hemispheric peace.''
   Signing the letter were Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz.; Connie Mack,
R-Fla.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; and Chuck Robb, D-Va.
   Baker's comments were part of a stepped-up administration effort
to call attention to what officials believe is an effort by Noriega
to stay in power through manipulation of voter lists and other
devices.
   The administration hopes to weaken Noriega as much as possible
by discrediting the election process in advance.
   The principal contest Sunday matches Carlos Duque, a Noriega
ally who is the presidential nominee of a coalition of
pro-government parties, against an opposition slate headed by
Guillermo David Endara.
   Free elections could usher in a new era for financially strapped
Panama, Baker said, but he contended Noriega is preparing for a
``massive fraud and to restrict the presence of international
observers and press.''
   Baker reaffirmed the longstanding U.S. position that there will
be no accommodation with a Noriega-dominated government. With the
help of the Defense Forces, he said, there is still time for the
Panamanians to save their country from the ``increasing destruction
wrought by the Noriega dictatorship.''
   Baker's remarks followed by three days Panamanian charges in the
U.N. Security Council that the United States has interfered in the
election by supplying millions of dollars to opposition candidates
and by sending commandos, special weapons and helicopters to Panama.
   Baker also warned the Soviet Union not to become ideologically
or militarily involved in Central America.
   ``Together with the other democracies, we must send a clear
message to others outside this hemisphere: This is not a dumping
ground for their arms or their failed ideologies.''
   He said the Soviet Union now has an opportunity ``to demonstrate
its so-called new thinking and to demonstrate it in Central
America.''
</TEXT>
