<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Boyd     05-01 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Boyd,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sir John Boyd, Former Union Leader, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir John Boyd, a miner's son who fought off
leftists to lead the powerful British union of engineering workers,
has died. He was 71.
   Boyd died Sunday at his home in Eastbourne, Sussex County, south
of London, the British Broadcasting Corp. said.
   A chairman of the Labor Party in 1967, he was knighted in 1979.
   Boyd started his career as an engineering worker but began work
as a trade union organizer in 1946. He stepped up to the presidency
of the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions in 1964.
   Boyd spent years fighting communists and left-wing elements for
control of the 1.5 million-member Amalgamated Union of Engineering
Workers.
   From 1975 to 1982, he served as general secretary of the union,
which is one of the largest in Britain. It includes jobs ranging
from professional electrical engineers to manual workers such as
mechanics.
   He believed that the well-being of workers is tied to the health
of the economy.
   ``We no longer represent a hungry mob of people crying out for
bread,'' he once said, adding that union members ``know that if our
economy breaks down, they will break down with it.''
   From 1967 to 1975, Boyd sat on the general council of the Trades
Union Congress, the national organization of unions. Boyd was a
director of the British Steel Corp. from 1981-86.
   He was married and had two daughters. No information on funeral
services was immediately available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
