<FIRST>r w AM-Democracy-SovietUnion     05-01 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democracy-Soviet Union,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Dissident Predicts Bloodshed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet dissident, dismissing
Moscow's reform campaign as a one-sided attempt to save a failed
system, predicted on Monday that President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policies will lead to ``a terrible clash ... bloodshed of huge
proportions.''
   But turmoil inside the Soviet Union could lead Moscow to release
its grip on such eastern European nations as Poland and Hungary,
Vladimir Bukovsky told a forum of democratic leaders from around
the world.
   Bukovsky, who was jailed and sentenced to internal exile in the
Soviet Union, then released in 1976 after an international campaign
on his behalf, now heads the Center for Democracy in the U.S.S.R, a
New York-based human rights group.
   He spoke before the annual conference of the National Endowment
for Democracy, which brought to Washington advocates of democracy
from Eastern Europe, Africa, Asia and Latin America to present
report cards on what many of the speakers called ``a universal
democratic revolution.''
   The endowment is a U.S.-financed, private-sector attempt to
foster democracy as an alternative to totalitarian and
authoritarian regimes.
   Speaking at the forum in the meeting room of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, Bukovsky contended that in spite of the
widespread impression that genuine reform is taking place in the
Soviet Union, ``the politburo has not moved toward democracy.''
   ``Perestroika is no attempt to establish a free market
economy,'' Bukovsky said. ``Glasnost does not mean the same as
freedom of speech.''
   ``This is an attempt to square a circle, to find a form of
socialism that can survive,'' he said. ``But you cannot square a
circle.''
   Bukovsky predicted ``a terrible clash in the Soviet Union
between the people and the government, bloodshed of huge
proportions.''
   He said the process has already started with the bloody
suppression of demonstrations in Soviet Georgia and the arrest of
nationalists in Soviet Armenia.
   Citing what he said are other signs of a crackdown, Bukovsky
added: ``The good news is that when there is turmoil in the Soviet
system, some countries like Hungary and Poland may have a chance to
get out.''
   He said the West is confused about Gorbachev and his aims and
mistakenly wants to help him with economic credits.
   Instead, he said, the West should be supporting the democratic
opposition inside the Soviet Union because ``the more cohesive and
organized the opposition is, the less likely the government is to
repress it.''
   But Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said it is clear to him there is
a ``new element'' in the Soviet leadership, which is ``prepared to
make major compromises.''
   ``We've got to deal with them,'' Lantos said. ``We are trying to
urge them to establish a social compact with all elements of their
own society.''
   But Bukovsky replied the West is ``doing nothing'' to help the
Soviet Union's democratic forces.
   He asserted that billions of dollars of economic credits, mostly
from West Germany, are flowing into the Kremlin's coffers.
   ``This will prop up the Soviet regime and help them not to
reform,'' he said.
   He suggested that the West allocate 10 percent of any credits
given to the Soviet Union to democratic forces there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
