<SECOND>AM-Anglican-Hostages,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Primate Appeals for Release of Countryman Held In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Robin Eames, the Anglican
primate of Ireland, made a special appeal Monday for the release of
an Irishman and 14 other foreigners held hostage in Lebanon.
   Eames is among 27 Anglican church leaders attending a weeklong
conference in this Mediterranean tourist resort about 110 miles
from Lebanon.
   ``May I appeal to anyone who has control of Brian Keenan to
release him. To do so would win respect from the world outside,''
Eames said in a written appeal.
   Keenan, 38, from Belfast, Northern Ireland, an English-language
teacher at the American University of Beirut, disappeared while
walking to work on April 11, 1986.
   No organization claimed his abduction, but he is believed held
by pro-Iranian Moslem fundamentalists in Moslem-controlled west
Beirut where 14 other foreigners are also held.
   The other hostages are nine Americans, three Britons _ including
Anglican special envoy Terry Waite _ an Italian and a Belgian.
American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, was seized on March 16, 1985, and is the longest
held hostage.
   Eames said that ``as a churchman from Brian's home country I
have joined with the other Anglican primates in urging the release
of all hostages.
   ``I write these words in the earnest hope that they may be read
by someone who is in contact with Brian at this time ... In God's
name and in the name of justice and peace I appeal for his
release.''
   The archbishops represent 70 million Anglicans worldwide. Such
meetings are held every three years.
