<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-MayDay     05-01 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-May Day,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dozens Detained in Prague May Day Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police broke up anti-government
protests Monday at an official May Day parade in the capital,
punching some people and detaining at least 76, unofficial sources
said. At least two people were reported injured.
   Several prominent dissidents, including Stanislav Devaty of the
independent Charter 77 movement, and British journalist Misha
Glenny were among those detained, the sources said. Devaty was
recently freed from jail after a hunger strike.
   Protests broke out at the start and close of a 90-minute parade
opened by Communist Party leader Milos Jakes. At least 600 people
shouted demands for more freedom and the release of people they
view as political prisoners, including playwright Vaclav Havel.
   At the beginning of the parade for the day to honor labor, about
100 people unfurled banners supporting Charter 77.
   ``Let Us Live!'' they yelled when police called for them to
disperse. When told their demonstration was illegal, they shouted
back, ``Long Live the First of May!'' and shouted, ``This is
dialogue?''
   Officials have been holding dialogues with young people since
last January, when police used force to end a week of protests.
   Police detained at least 76 people in Prague during Monday's
protests, activist Anna Sabatova said. She said 18 other people
were detained in the city of Brno, but she gave no details.
   Most of those detained were released by early evening.
   Glenny, central Europe correspondent for the British
Broadcasting Corp., said he was punched once in the face after
uniformed police detained him. He said authorities also smashed his
tape reporder on the ground and took his cassette.
   He was held for five hours and released after being fined $10
for not carrying identification papers. Newly arrived at his post,
he was not due to receive official accreditation until Tuesday.
   In London, the Foreign Office said it would protest to
Czechoslovakia about his arrest and treatment.
   Glenny said he was taken to a nearby police station with about
20 other people. He said one of them, peace activist Tomas Tvaroch,
suffered a concussion when police grabbed him and punched him in
the head and back.
   The bulk of the protesters eventually dispersed when hundreds of
security forces marched toward them.
   While embracing economic reform, Jakes and the other Communist
leaders have not endorsed political changes promoted by President
Mikhail Gorbachev in the Soviet Union. This country's current
leadership was installed after the Soviets led a Warsaw Pact
invasion to crush party reforms in 1968.
   Jakes reiterated in his speech opening Monday's rally that
authorities in Czechoslovakia would not allow ``unrest and tension
in society'' or anti-Communist projects under the guise of reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
