<FIRST>r a AM-Super7     05-01 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lottery Winnings Frighten Super 7 Player</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claims for a record $115.5 million
lottery jackpot were filed Monday by three more potential winners,
including a woman who didn't want any publicity because she feared
the reaction in her drug-infested neighborhood.
   All three are women from Philadelphia: Blanche Downing, 55;
Betty Rubin, a housewife; and Angeline Pavloski, a 69-year-old
retired waitress who plans to split her prize with her brother,
George DeLorenzo.
   Ms. Downing told lottery officials her neighborhood ``has lots
of cocaine activity'' and she fears for her safety now that she has
apparently won a Pennsylvania Super 7 lottery prize worth $8.3
million, to be distributed over the next 26 years.
   She was accompanied by a former Philadelphia policeman and two
other friends. They quickly walked out of lottery headquarters
after filing the claim, trying to duck photographers, and climbed
into a car. She declined to answer reporters' questions.
   Lottery spokeswoman Terry Murphy said the lottery suggested Ms.
Downing not return to her neighborhood.
   ``We realize the position she's in,'' Ms. Murphy said.
   In order to claim her winnings, Ms. Downing had to agree to
allow her name to be used.
   If tickets held by her and the other claimaints prove to be
winners, the first checks will be issued next week, Ms. Murphy
said. The ticket validation process, which started Monday for all
11 of 14 winning tickets presented so far, will be completed
sometime this week, the spokeswoman said. Each annual payment will
be $317,524.67, before taxes.
   Ms. Murphy said lottery officials took a call from a woman in
Maryland who said she had the winning numbers, but wouldn't file a
claim until later in the week. Winners have a year from the date of
the drawing to file a claim.
   Asked why she waited until Monday to file her claim, Mrs. Rubin
said: ``We just had other things to do.''
   Neither Mrs. Rubin, who refused to give her age, nor Mrs.
Pavloski said they had any plans for the money.
   Mrs. Pavloski was sick last week and didn't check her tickets
until Friday, three days after the winning numbers were drawn.
   She said she has played the lottery since its introduction in
1972.
   ``I always said to myself one of these days I'm going to hit
real good. And I never knew I was going to hit this big,'' Mrs.
Pavloski said.
   The $115.5 million jackpot was a North American record. The
previous record was $69.9 million in Illinois, split by four
winning tickets April 15.
</TEXT>
