<FIRST>u i AM-Senegal-Mauritania     05-01 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senegal-Mauritania,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlift Taking Tens of Thousands of Expatriates Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of expatriate Senegalese and
Mauritanians flew to their homelands Monday in an airlift aimed at
ending a wave of violence that has left hundreds dead.
   About 55 Mauritanians were reported killed Friday and Saturday
in Dakar and the provinces by angry Senegalese seeking revenge for
the deaths of hundreds of their countrymen in neighboring
Mauritania earlier last week.
   Unconfirmed reports said as many as 400 Senegalese were killed
April 24-25 in Nouakchott, Mauritania's capital, in a wave of
violence that began over a land dispute. Nouakchott is 375 miles
north of Dakar.
   States of emergency and curfews were in effect in both West
African nations' capitals, but vandalism continued in Dakar. The
French news agency Agence France-Presse reported bands of pillagers
attacked the shops of some Lebanese merchants after all
Mauritanian-owned shops were burned or vacated.
   Officials said the airlift, which started in full Sunday, had
carried about 8,720 Senegalese home from neighboring Mauritania by
midday Monday and about 5,785 Mauritanians back home from Senegal.
   France, Spain and Morocco were assisting in the airlift. Planes
were making an average of four round trips per day, airport
officials said.
   Among the Senegalese brought back from Mauritania, some had
their sex organs or limbs mutilated, and most of the corpses
brought home had been decapitated, reporters said.
   Senegalese officials began a program to integrate the returning
citizens and provide measures to fill the vacuum created by the
departure of the Mauritanians, who ran 80 percent of the small
businesses in this country.
   ``Absolute priority is being accorded to the distribution of
basic foodstuffs in Dakar as well as the provinces,'' the Commerce
Ministry said in a statement.
   The violence was prompted by the killing of two Senegalese April
9 in a border village in a dispute over grazing rights between
Mauritanian shepherds and Senegalese peasants.
   Mauritania straddles Arab north and black West Africa.
Two-thirds of its 2 million people are Moors of Arab-Berber
extraction. The rest are black, mostly from the southern river
region. Nearly all of Senegal's 7 million people are black.
   The dispute concerns the right of Senegalese to farm on a
Senegal River island. After both countries became independent from
France in 1960, the black Toucouleur people of Senegal continued to
farm the Mauritanian side they had considered their own for
generations.
   Moors to the north, traditionally nomadic herders, did not farm.
   But the recent completion of two dams on the river has opened up
new farmland, spurred Mauritanian interest in agriculture and
prompted them to force Senegalese off the land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
