<FIRST>u a AM-SecondAbduction 2ndLd-Writethru a0713 05-01 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0713,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Reports `Masked Gunman' Took Second Infant in Three Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `Jersey County ...,' to CORRECT spelling of
sheriff's name to Yocom, sted Yocum.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police investigated a report Monday that a
masked gunman abducted a baby girl from a couple who made the same
complaint three years ago about another daughter who was found dead
yards from their house.
   On Saturday, Robert and Paula Sims reported their 6-week-old
daughter, Heather, missing from her bassinet after a masked gunman
knocked Mrs. Sims unconscious, police said.
   The report was identical to one filed in 1986 in nearby Brighton
when the Sims' 13-day-old daughter, Loralei, turned up missing. Her
body was found five days later about 150 feet from the Sims' house.
No arrest was made although the parents were considered supsects.
   ``What are the chances of somebody breaking into your house and
taking your small infant child once in your life?'' said police
Sgt. Billy Lawrence. ``You figure out the odds, and then figure out
the odds that it could happen a second time in a completely
different city. But I'm not trying to say anything.''
   The Sims have an unlisted telephone number and could not
immediately be reached. Madison County State's Attorney Bill Haine
also did not immediately return telephone calls.
   On Monday, police in this Mississippi River city across from St.
Louis said they were still treating Heather's disappearance as a
reported kidnapping.
   ``We are doing everything we can possibly do, but we have no
idea where the child is,'' said police Sgt. Bud Pyatt.
   ``We were told (Mrs. Sims) was approached by a male outside the
home, forced back inside the house and knocked unconscious,'' said
Pyatt. ``But we have no information other than what was obtained
yesterday.''
   Sgt. Rick McCain of the Alton Police said there was ``no
physical evidence'' that Mrs. Sims had been struck.
   ``There is nothing that disproves their allegations,'' said
McCain. ``But we are not discounting the information from the other
case.''
   The reported timing of the abductions was nearly identical. In
1986, Mrs. Sims said she was knocked out about 10:20 p.m. On
Saturday, she told police the assailant struck at 10:30 p.m. as she
took out the trash.
   Police said a 15-month-old son was sleeping in the house at the
time Mrs. Sims said Heather was abducted, but the boy was not
disturbed. No valuables were reported missing.
   Mrs. Sims told police her husband arrived home Saturday night
about an hour after she was knocked out and revived her.
   Police searched around the Sims home on Sunday, and Pyatt said
investigators might broaden the search.
   Sims' brother-in-law, Herb Condray, of Cottage Hills, said
police had advised the couple to make no public statement about the
case. ``They told the parents to let the police handle it and
that's what they're doing,'' he said.
   The family lived in Brighton, about 10 miles north of Alton, in
1986 when Mrs. Sims, then 27, reported a masked gunman entered her
home, ordered her to lie down, and took Loralei from her bassinet.
   In each case, Sims was at work at the time his daughters
disappeared. Sims works at Laclede Steel Co. in Alton.
   Jersey County Sheriff Frank Yocom said Sims and his wife were
suspects in Loralei's death. But the couple declined to testify
before a grand jury investigation, citing their constitutional
right for protection against self-incrimination, and the panel took
no action, Yocom said.
   Loralei's disappearance touched off an intensive search.
Leaflets with the infant's picture were distributed and the parents
pleaded for help finding their daughter. When her body was found
five days later it was so decomposed a cause of death could not be
determined.
   Sims and his wife insisted in 1986 they had nothing to do with
Loralei's disappearance and death.
   The couple moved to the two-story frame home in Alton about two
years ago. Sims, then 34, installed a tall chainlink fence around
the front yard shortly after moving to Alton, neighbors said.
</TEXT>
