<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     05-01 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>25 Tamil Rebels Break Prison; Jeep Ambush Kills Four Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 25 imprisoned Tamil rebels
overpowered Indian soldiers guarding a jail in northern Sri Lanka
on Monday and escaped with weapons and ammunition, residents said.
   Residents and witnesses to the breakout at Vavuniya town, 135
miles north of Colombo, said other Tamils apparently created a
diversion by firing at a nearby Indian sentry post.
   An Indian High Commission spokeswoman could not confirm the
break, the first by Tamil separatists since Indian troops began
peacekeeping operations in 1987. The spokeswoman cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   In other violence:
   _Ambushers thought to be Sinhalese exploded a mine under a
passing police patrol jeep in Polonnawara and then fired automatic
weapons, killing four policemen and wounding two, military
officials said. The town is 100 miles northeast of Colombo. The
officials cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   _Three gunmen believed to be Tamil rebels killed Mutthiah
Panchalingam, 52, the senior administrator of Jaffna district, in a
village outside Jaffna town, 185 miles north of Colombo, military
officials said.
   Jaffna has been headquarters of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, a rebel group spearheading the separatist campaign that has
claimed 10,000 lives.
   But a Tamil Tiger leader in Colombo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, denied the group was responsible for Panchalingam's
death.
   A senior Tiger leader is holding talks with the government to
end the separatist war.
   Previous government peace overtures to Tamil rebels touched off
a violent backlash by Sinhalese militants, who complained that
offers made in the India-sponsored peace accord of July 1987
conceded too much to the Tamils and who then launched their own
agitation against the government.
   Sinhalese form 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
dominate the government and the military. Tamils make up 18
perecent and claim they are discriminated in jobs and education by
the Sinhalese.
   Indian soldiers are deployed in the island's north and east to
enforce the 1987 accord and disarm Tamils who have fought for six
years for a separate nation.
</TEXT>
