<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Bomb     05-01 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Bomb,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Blamed on Separatists Shakes Power Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion blamed on ethnic
Albanian militants rocked an electric tower Monday in the restive
province of Kosovo, an official report said.
   The bomb went off underneath the power line at 5 a.m. near the
town of Podujevo, about 20 miles north of the provincial capital of
Pristina, the state news agency Tanjug said.
   No injuries were reported.
   The agency said the attack was mounted by ethnic Albanian
``nationalists and separatists'' who had ``continued their hostile
activities even on May Day.''
   In the same report, the news agency said grafitti was found in a
village near Podujevo which contained ``hostile slogans from the
position of Albanian nationalism and separatism.''
   Tanjug said the slogans denounced Slobodan Milosevic, the
Communist Party leader in the republic of Serbia. The southern
province of Kosovo, though technically autonomous, is an
administrative part of Serbia.
   Minority Slavs in the province have clashed with majority ethnic
Albanians for many years. The Slavs have demonstrated to support a
drive by Milosevic to increase Serbian control of the province.
   The ethnic tensions fueled riots in March that killed at least
25 people.
