<FIRST>r a AM-ChiracVisit     05-01 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chirac Visit,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former French Premier Starts U.S. Trip With Sentimental Journey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former French Premier Jacques Chirac
took a sentimental journey through this college town Monday on the
first day of a nine-day cross-country trip.
   Chirac, who recently began his third term as mayor of Paris,
planned the trip as a way of ``staying in touch with the major
players in the United States,'' spokesman Pierre Lellouche said.
   Chirac plans to meet with President Bush. He is scheduled to
meet this week in New York with former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar before
traveling to Los Angeles, where he plans to visit former President
Reagan and dine with such actors as Gregory Peck and Jane Fonda.
   ``I prefer the East Coast and my daughter likes the West Coast,
so we're doing both,'' said Chirac. His daughter Claude, 25, was
among a dozen French advisers and journalists along for the trip.
   Chirac attended a luncheon at the John F. Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University before wandering awhile along the
Cambridge streets he first haunted in 1952 as a summer student at
Harvard's business school.
   Chirac, 56, smiled as familiar sights jogged his memory. He
recalled the giddiness of his first visit to the United States and
the American woman he fell in love with while working as a soda
jerk at the old Howard Johnson's in Harvard Square.
   ``It was a wonderful time,'' he said. ``It pleases me to relive
it.''
   More recently, times have been tougher for Chirac, head of
France's neo-Gaullist party, who lost his bid last year to unseat
socialist President Francois Mitterand.
   Not only did the conservative candidate lose the May 1988 race,
his party also lost its majority coalition in the National
Assembly, forcing him to resign as prime minister.
   Chirac had held the posts of prime minister and Paris mayor
simultaneously. It is not uncommon for French officials to hold two
important elected jobs.
   Lellouche said Chirac has emerged from a post-election letdown,
during which he was relatively withdrawn.
   ``This is a man who was defeated,'' the spokesman said. ``It's a
time of opposition, and a time of learning.''
   Later Monday, Chirac spoke in French to an audience of about 150
students, faculty and members of the local French community at
Harvard's Center for European Studies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
