<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 2nd ld-writethru, a0624,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Meets With Sihanouk, Suharto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with Cambodian report, inserts 2 grafs after 4th graf
previous, The fourth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle repeated his
support for Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk on
Monday, but the vice president and his aides said a meeting between
the two had brought no changes in U.S. policy toward that country.
   Quayle, spending a day here after touring Australia, met for 45
minutes with Sihanouk. The vice president also talked about trade
issues and human rights with Indonesian President Suharto.
   But much of the day's focus was on the meeting with Sihanouk,
who is visiting Indonesia along with the leaders of two other
factions hopeful of running Cambodia after the promised fall
withdrawal of Vietnamese occupation troops.
   The fourth group vying for control in Cambodia is the Khmer
Rouge, a Chinese-backed organization that was responsible for
killing as many as 1.5-million Cambodians from 1975 to 1979. Quayle
and other U.S. officials have said they will not tolerate a
Cambodian government dominated by the Khmer Rouge.
   Meantime, Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed government has changed
the country's name and flag, and invited Sihanouk to return home
and help rule.
   Sihanouk welcomed the concessions and appeared ready to make a
few of his own to end the 10-year conflict. ``It seems that we are
at the end of the tunnel. We are going to make progress on the way
toward a settlement,'' Sihanouk said.
   Quayle has said that the United States is considering giving
military aid to Sihanouk and possibly the other non-communist
Cambodian faction, headed by Son Sann.
   But Quayle said such aid did not come up in his discussions with
Sihanouk.
   Asked if U.S. military aid might be overt or covert, Quayle
responded there was a mixed view on the subject _ ``mixed being
some overt, some covert.''
   What he and Sihanouk did discuss, Quayle said, was ``the process
and moving the process forward and timetables and ... who the
players are and what some of the expectations would be.''
   Sihanouk supports an international conference on Cambodia that
could lead to an enforcement mechanism to monitor the withdrawal of
the Vietnamese and to cope with a transition government until
elections are held.
   The United States backs making Sihanouk the interim leader until
free elections can be held.
   Later, at a news conference before leaving Indonesia, Quayle
said, the United States remains totally opposed to giving the Khmer
Roupe any controlling role in Cambodia.
   ``It's a non-starter from the very beginning,'' he said. ``We
don't believe that Khmer rouge offer anything...but mass murder,''
   An aide to Quayle, speaking on condition he remain anonymous,
said that Quayle will relay his information to Bush and that it
might be several months before the United States decides whether to
alter its policy toward Cambodia.
   With Suharto, Quayle took up human rights issues, particularly
allegations that Indonesia has more than 400 political prisoners
and has used repressive tactics in East Timor, a former Portuguese
colony annexed by Indonesia in 1975. Some 30 members of Congress
had urged Quayle to take up the human rights issue.
   In addition, Quayle met with three human rights activists,
including Shamet Bratanata.
   With Suharto, Quayle advocated that Indonesia practice
``political development'' as well as economic development.
   Other issues that were brought up with officials of Indonesia,
considered a strong U.S. ally, were trade and space.
   On Tuesday Quayle heads for Singapore and then on to Thailand,
the last two overseas stops on his 12-day trip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
