<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Mr.Right Adv05   05-01 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Mr. Right, Adv 05,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, May 5 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Single Women Stalk Mr. Right in West German Comedy Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of four single women
who look for the perfect prince but have to kiss a lot of frogs
along the way is the latest hit comedy movie in West Germany.
   The movie also blasts others in West Germany's young social
scene, from yuppies who marry only for tax breaks to far-out
leftist activists.
   The movie ``Beim naechsten Mann wird alles anders'' (``With the
Next Man Everything Will Be Different'') is based on a best-selling
book of the same title by writer Eva Heller, who has also published
collections of satirical cartoons.
   The film, released in January, was rated No. 5 on the hit movie
list published by the Hamburg-based weekly magazine Stern in its
March 2 issue. That made ``Beim naechsten Mann'' the second-highest
ranked West German movie on the list after ``Herbstmilch,'' the
poignant tale of a young Bavarian farm woman during the Nazi era.
   Movies focusing on women are still unusual in West Germany,
despite the success in recent years of woman directors such as
Doris Doerrie, whose 1985 film ``Maenner'' (``Men'') was an
international hit.
   The heroine of the movie is Constanze Wechselburger, a film
student who sees herself as intellectual, political and prominent
in the feminist movement, even though she spends most of her time
hunting for men.
   The film opens with a chaotic battle between Constanze and her
boyfriend, Albert, a young doctor whom she eventually dumps for
allegedly being both bourgeois and cheap. Albert criticizes
Constanze for her wastefulness, cutting open a discarded toothpaste
tube with a scalpel to show there was enough toothpaste left for
several more brushings.
   Constanze is quick to retaliate. ``This is what I think of your
cheap Christmas present,'' she yells, flushing her own gift to
Albert, an expensive watch, down the toilet.
   Constanze confides her troubles to her girlfriends over numerous
glasses of wine, most frequently in a local bar called the Cafe
Kaputt.
   ``I'm looking for a relationship that is built on an
intellectual basis, not a material one,'' she says. She also
insists on ``emotional freedom,'' rejecting marriage as a bourgeois
institution.
   Ironically, she lands in the arms of a married man. Film
instructor Gottfried Schachtschnabel, a veteran of the 1960s
student revolts, sports a three-day beard and pretentious leftist
political attitudes.
   He, too, rejects the notion of marriage, but doesn't bother
getting divorced. He ``forgets'' to inform his girlfriends about
his status, and defends himself when he's caught.
   ``Marx was married, too. And he had an affair with his
housekeeper. We can only learn from that,'' he tells Constanze.
   There's also Sieglinde, a social-climbing dental assistant whose
yuppie boyfriend marries her for tax savings; the old-fashioned
Birgit, who looks for her dream man in the want ads; and Julia, a
psychologist who also falls prey to Schachtschnabel.
   It's a film with which West Germans can apparently both laugh
and identify. ``The characters may be cliches, but everybody
recognizes a few things that are true in real life, aspects he can
relate to,'' Angela Marquis of the film's Berlin-based production
company said in a recent interview.
   Although the film focuses on women and the title indicates
disappointment with men, it is not just a work for feminists, she
said.
   ``The story is really about curiosity, not disappointment,''
Marquis said. ``Both men and women are often bored with what they
have and think another relationship would be better. But, as the
film shows, that isn't always the case.''
   By the end of the film Constanze succumbs to bourgeois society
and gets married after all. She chooses Albert, deciding that
thriftiness is not the worst vice in the world.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri May 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
