<FIRST>a i PM-SpanishGamblers Adv05   05-01 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spanish Gamblers, Adv 05,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>Adv for Fri AMs May 5 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Group to Help Gamblers Formed in Spain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD LORANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel Melgarejo is trying to cool the
fever in a country where gambling is a major sport, musical slot
machines abound and nearly everyone takes a flyer on El Gordo, the
fat Christmas lottery.
   His shoestring version of Gamblers Anonymous is called the
Madrid Association of Recovering Gamblers. The telephone has been
ringing constantly since he mentioned the number on a radio program
and told listeners with gambling problems to call.
   In the four months since, he says, the membership has grown from
nearly zero to more than 200. An estimated 50,000 addicted gamblers
live in and around the capital.
   ``It's hang up, answer, hang up, answer,'' said Melgarejo, a
reformed gambler who blamed the addiction for ruining his first
marriage.
   He interrupted the interview at a temporary office in a Madrid
Roman Catholic church to talk with a middle-aged woman who walked
in off the street to confess an addiction to slot machines.
   Spain has 420,000 ``habitual gamblers,'' 3 percent of the adult
population, according to the National Gambling Commission. They are
caught in a tradition that goes back at least to 1763, when King
Carlos III started the world's longest-running public lottery.
   ``The difference between `habitual gamblers' and `addicts' is
basically a semantic one,'' said Santiago Mendioroz, head of
gambling commission.
   Spaniards placed $29 billion in bets last year, according to the
commission. It regulates state-run lotteries and sports pools, and
casinos, bingo halls and slot machines, which were legalized in
1977 after a 53-year ban.
   Mendioroz said the government's take from lotteries, pools and
fees last year was more than $2.2 billion.
   Press reports say Spain ranks second in the world in gambling
expenditures per capita, behind the United States and ahead of the
Philippines. Mendioroz says there are ``no reliable figures, but
because of the slot machines in bars and restaurants gambling is
omnipresent.''
   Slots, which blare bits of music as reminders of their presence,
are found in 80 percent of the more than 200,000 bars and cafes,
commission figures indicate. Mendioroz said Spain has 310,000 of
the machines.
   One sure sign of a gambling problem, he said, is that 8,000
people have asked his commission not to let them into casinos and
bingo halls.
   He described the number as surprisingly high considering the
custom in this Roman Catholic country of hiding such failings.
   ``Gambling is considered a vice, almost a sin, and the person
who has that problem is very reluctant to admit it,'' he said.
   Melgarejo, a 44-year-old insurance agent, devotes much of his
time to unpaid missionary work with gamblers. He says 18 years of
gambling cost him his first wife, ``10 or 12 jobs'' and about
$217,000.
   Last year he spent three months at the Cordoba Association of
Recovering Gamblers and managed to conquer the habit. His
organization and the original self-help group in Cordoba are the
only two in Spain, but Melgarejo said a national federation may
result if enough others are formed.
   He believes the Spanish character encourages gambling.
   ``It's like Don Quixote,'' he said. ``The Spaniard ... is a
romantic. He believes in fantasy, in destiny. He thinks he can
solve a lifetime's worth of problems with one stroke of luck.''
   End Adv PM Fri May 5
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 0812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:RadioPioneer Adv08   05-01 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Radio Pioneer, Adv 08,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, May 8 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Story of Spanish-language Radio Pioneer Told in New Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With about 200 stations now programming in
Spanish to the tune of $176 million in advertising revenue last
year, U.S. Hispanic radio is booming.
   But the sound wasn't always sweet, as seen in the new film,
``Break of Dawn.''
   The movie, released in selected Southwestern cities, re-creates
the story of Spanish radio pioneer Pedro J. Gonzalez, who was
imprisoned after his on-air protests of Depression-era deportations
of Mexicans.
   ``It's a story about justice prevailing over injustice,'' said
producer Jude Pauline Eberhard. Set in Los Angeles in the 1920s and
'30s, the film tells how Gonzalez was paroled after being sent to
San Quentin on trumped up rape charges following his advocacy
broadcasts.
   Gonzalez parlayed his musical talents and eye for business into
a popular Spanish-language radio program. But it ended when he was
sent to prison on charges that were later recanted by the woman who
had allegedly been raped.
   Mexican recording star Oscar Chavez plays Gonzalez, portraying
him as he first translates radio commercials into Spanish, then
sings with his guitar and, finally, pays a station for early
morning airtime. Gonzalez and his wife sold advertising on the
show, making a profit on the difference.
   Called ``Los Madrugadores'' (``The Early Risers''), the Los
Angeles-based program developed a strong following among Hispanics
with a mix of live music, discussion of issues and commercials.
   Now 94, Gonzalez lives with his wife, Maria, in Northern
California and was a consultant for the film, said Isaac
Artenstein, who wrote and directed the movie.
   To insure realism, Artenstein used both Spanish and English
dialogue. ``You can't have Pedro talking and singing in English if
you say he was the first (radio broadcaster) in Spanish,'' said
Artenstein.
   But the bilingual approach can pose distribution problems.
Eberhard said exhibitors are shying away from the film because they
don't know whether to market it as an English or Spanish movie.
``It's scary for the distributors because of the natural language
flow,'' she said.
   Though he changed some characters' names, Artenstein said that
all of the film's main roles are based on real people, including an
activist Mexican consul, a district attorney who helps frame
Gonzalez, and a teen-age girl who falsely accuses Gonzalez of
raping her.
   Courtroom testimony in the film is taken from Gonzalez' trial
transcripts unearthed by a law library archivist. Artenstein said
Los Angeles' Spanish-language daily, La Opinion, also had extensive
coverage of Gonzalez' case, but the English-language media did not
have one story.
   ``Break of Dawn,'' which was shot for $850,000, also stars Maria
Rojo as Gonzalez' wife. Others in the film include Tony Plana, Pepe
Serna, Peter Henry Schroeder, Kamala Lopez, Valarie Wildman and
Socorro Valdez. The film was independently produced by San
Diego-based Cinewest Productions.
   Los Angeles is now the nation's largest Hispanic media market,
with $32.7 million spent on Spanish-language radio advertising in
1988, according to Hispanic Business magazine. Seven radio stations
and two television stations now air Spanish broadcasts full time in
the city.
   It is a far cry from the days when Gonzalez and his wife had to
pay stations in advance for pre-dawn airtime.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
