<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--WhiteHouseStones ADV14-1stAdd   05-01 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--White House Stones, ADV 14-1st Add,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sun., May 14</HEAD>
<TEXT>WASHINGTON: of this.''    Carved swags of foliage, dogwood blossoms,
fish scale designs and roses surround the windows. Rich scrollwork tops
the Ionic columns.    But time, weather, the successive layers of paint
and some clumsy restoration efforts along the way dealt unkindly with the
Scotsmen's work.    Just west of the main entrance on the Pennsylvania
Avenue side of the residence, the keystone of an architrave, an arch-like
stone window frame, cracked. Rainwater seeped in and froze. The resulting
collapse caused a separation of nearly an inch between two of the windowframe
blocks.    The ornamental border of the window is also blackened, believed
to have been caused when the British burned the White House in 1812. 
  Most of the damage is less dramatic _ a piece missing here and there
from a moulding, a crack in a ledge, a damaged rosette under a windowsill.
   Some broken dentils, the teeth-like blocks that project under the cornice,
had been rebuilt by being encased with lead, apparently in a restoration
carried out when President Theodore Roosevelt had the West Wing built in
1901.    The lead boxes held the moisture inside rather than letting it
escape. ``I took off one of those boxes and the stone was just like mud,
like mud,'' Palumbo says. All of the stones had to be replaced.    All
in all, the work has added up to more than they expected. Congress has
appropriated $2.4 million for the job, and Walters says more money may
be needed.    Walters is saving chunks of crumbling stone to take with
him to the next appropriations hearing.    The stone being used in the
restoration was removed from the Capitol during an expansion project in
1960 and 1961. It was quarried from Aquia Creek at the same time as the
White House sandstone.    This is the stone that the Park Service keeps
in its maintenance yard in Rock Creek Park.    ``Coming from the same
quarry at the same time, it's the same density and has all the same characteristics,''
says Jim McDaniel, White House liaison officer for the Park Service.
``It's as authentic as you can get.''    However, Walters says, ``one
of the problems is that the big blocks of stone have been sitting there
so long, and they weren't in the greatest of shape when they were taken
off anyway.'' Palumbo estimates that about half of the stone is not usable.
   ``Anybody would say this is no good,'' says Palumbo, pointing to a
battered block lying outside the North wall, trucked there after he marked
it in the maintenance yard. ``But I go in the middle. This is a very good
piece of stone inside. Very tight veined. Not porous. It will give you
a very smooth face, very smooth.''    The veteran stonecutter likens the
process to removing the bark from a tree to find the good wood.    At
the White House, he makes blue chalk marks on the wall to show sections
that need to be replaced. A cardboard pattern is cut to fit, and the new
piece hewn from the good stone.    ``The paint has sealed the stone,''
he says. ``Stone needs to breathe, too. After they remove the paint, you
will be surprised at the nice little foliage that will come out that people
never knew was there.''    Palumbo recommends that the paint be stripped
from the structure every 10 years and the stone be left exposed to the
air for five or six months.    On this day, the master carver had clambered
under a clear plastic tarpaulin erected to protect the bare wall and was
watching as Matteo Gennaro, who also worked on the project at the Capitol
nearly two decades ago, labored with a carbide tool and an air hammer.
   ``You've got to chip away little by little, so it takes time, even
with the air compressor,'' Palumbo says. ``If you want to do the job in
an accurate way, want to do what you are supposed to do, restoration is
very slow motion work.''
</TEXT>
