<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-01 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Clara's Heart'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
PG-13)
   
   Clara Mayfield is a brutally direct woman who colors her human
   relationships with a good deal of common sense,
self-righteousness and tenacity. She also has an overwhelming
humanity about her, and that specialness attracts people to her
like a magnet.
   Clara is a vibrant and rich role, one that critics last year
said could easily turn around Whoopi Goldberg's dismal film career
after such losers as ``Burglar,'' ``Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and
``Fatal Beauty.''
   Robert Mulligan (``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' ``Inside Daisy
Clover'') restrains Goldberg in his direction of this family
melodrama, allowing none of the bits and business that have become
the trademarks of her wealth of comic stage characters. That
restraint is essential to Clara herself, a Jamaican with a dark
secret.
   Clara enters the lives of the affluent Hart family from
Maryland's Eastern Shore, shortly after the crib death of their
daughter. Leona (Kathleen Quinlan) and Bill (Michael Ontkean) have
gone to Jamaica to help get over the tragedy. Clara is their hotel
maid.
   She coaxes Leona out of her depression and encourages her to get
on with life. Leona decides to bring her back to Maryland _ she
can't quite function without Clara's island sensibilities. But son
David takes an immediate dislike to Clara and accuses his parents _
rightfully so _ of bringing her home so they won't have to deal
with him. The Harts are in the process of a divorce.
   Clara eventually wins over David to the point where he'd rather
spend his weekends in Baltimore with Clara and her West Indian
friends than with his parents. He also picks up Clara's island
patois.
   But his dependency on Clara ultimately leads to her dark
revelation. And it is here that the movie falters. There is no
build-up to this awful experience in her life, and its unfolding is
an abrupt twist. And with the tale, there remain loose ends:
Letters hidden in a suitcase and found by David are never
explained; the father of Clara's child also is a mystery.
   Still, ``Clara's Heart'' is a warm movie with many lessons to
tell, if one is willing to listen. It's a movie that works better
on the small screen than it did theatrically. Its force is aided by
Goldberg's performance and a noteworthy movie debut of Neil Patrick
Harris as David. There's also a lilting score by Dave Grusin, but
once again Hollywood fails in geography: Steel music and calypso
are products of Trinidad, not Jamaica.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Running on Empty'' (Warner Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
PG-13)
   
   What ever happened to all those Weather people from the late
1960s and early '70s, all those revolutionaries who bombed
government buildings and corporations with government contracts?
All those radicals who may have killed innocents in the name of
freedom and liberty?
   They went underground. But underground is as ordinary as the
family next door.
   ``Running on Empty'' looks at such a family, who have been
wanted by the FBI for their part in a bombing in which a security
guard was accidently killed. The young couple made one mistake,
though. Not only did they take their young son, Danny, with them as
they fled, they also conceived another child while underground,
Harry.
   Cut to the '80s. Danny (River Phoenix) is a 17-year-old musical
prodigy. What to do. If he stays with his parents, as they want him
to, he must give up all ambitions in music and indeed give up his
own destiny. If he leaves them and heads for the Juilliard School,
he will never be able to see them again unless they surrender to
authorities.
   There is much tenderness in this movie, especially from
Christine Lahti as the mother. Judd Hirsch's father seems somewhat
outmoded in his '60s politics and '60s perceptions. He's also a
little selfish. He's not a very likeable man until the end, and
resolution of the movie.
   Naomi Foner has a tight and gripping screenplay, and Sidney
Lumet's direction is powerful.
   It's a nice movie for the entire family because ``Running on
Empty'' is ultimately about family.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
