<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Costner Adv12-14   05-01 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Costner, Adv 12-14,1012</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 12-14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Field of Dreams'' goes wide May 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Costner Turns Director and Finds His Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Costner, clad in his customary costume
of jeans, T-shirt, sweater and day-old beard, arrived late for an
interview but presented a valid excuse: He had been picking up tips
on film directing from movie giant Steven Spielberg.
   ``I need all the help I can get, and who could be a better
teacher?'' remarked Costner, who starts directing himself in a film
next July.
   Costner's modest office at Raleigh studios, where he once worked
as a laborer, displays evidence of the new project. On the walls
are dozens of note-pad pages detailing each scene of the film, as
yet untitled. Next he plans to storyboard _ an artist's concept of
each camera angle.
   ``I need to have that backup,'' he explained. ``I'll leave a
window for new things to come in (during filming). I need to
communicate to many people what I'm trying to do. Those ideas can
be built upon.''
   Costner gave no specifics on what he had learned from Spielberg,
but said both men had been ``dancing around each other'' in search
of a mutual project. ``The only time I worked for Steven was when I
did an `Amazing Stories' for him,'' the actor said, referring to
the old TV show.
   Three years ago, Costner was known mostly for playing the corpse
in ``The Big Chill.'' Then came ``Silverado,'' ``The Untouchables''
and ``No Way Out.'' For his new film, ``Field of Dreams,'' he
reportedly was paid $2.5 million. So why take on the added labor of
directing his next film?
   ``I have to maintain interest in what I'm doing. This particular
subject generates a certain amount of interest for me. When this
project was born, it was not on the surface a very commercial
movie. Yet I believe it's very commercial.
   ``The theme of it is people who want to talk to each other but
can't, because of the language barrier (between white settlers and
Indians). It's a period piece set in the 1860s. This is not a movie
to set the record straight, or to reinvent what happened. It's just
a theatrical piece, but it's more than that, too. There's a lot of
action in it.''
   There's not much action in ``Field of Dreams,'' a baseball
fantasy which some critics have described as Capra-esque. Costner
plays an Iowa farmer who heeds a mystery voice and builds a
baseball diamond in his cornfield; soon the ghosts of the infamous
Chicago Black Sox team show up to play.
   Costner acknowledged that the script, based on the novel
``Shoeless Joe'' by W.P. Kinsella, was a tough sell.
Writer-director Phil Alden Robinson worked on it for six years
before getting it made.
   ``I didn't have to be convinced of it,'' Costner remarked. ``The
minute I read it, I thought that I would want to do this movie.
   ``Why? I don't know. I make movies, and you need to have
subjects. The amount of movies I'll do in my life are numbered;
it's a finite number. As a script passes over me, it has to reach
me emotionally. I don't care what genre it is, comedy or action or
something else. Those don't dictate what I'll do. But it just has
to have a certain amount of poignancy.
   ```Field of Dreams' did. It also had what I'm always looking
for: other strong, strong characters. So I knew that we would be
able to attract good actors.'' Among them: James Earl Jones, Burt
Lancaster, Amy Madigan, Ray Liotta.
   Costner was born in a Los Angeles suburb, son of a power lineman
who was part-Cherokee (which helps explain his next project). His
father's work required repeated moves, and Costner recalls of
school, ``I was always on the outside.'' He studied marketing at
California State University, Fullerton, but also acted in a
community theater.
   After marrying his college sweetheart, Cindy Silva, a former
Snow White at Disneyland, Kevin quit a marketing job to try
Hollywood. He spent six years as a set worker at Raleigh Studios,
studying at night in acting workshops. After his flashback scene
was cut from ``The Big Chill,'' Lawrence Kasdan cast him as the
hell-raising gunslinger in ``Silverado.'' He clicked immediately.
   Because he believes he should support all his films, Costner did
the New York media whirl for ``Field of Dreams.'' He readily admits
that he doesn't enjoy it. He is an extremely private man, yet he
doesn't dwell on his loss of privacy.
   ``As many doors that close to you, there are others that open
up,'' he reasoned. ``I don't think anybody has been able to resolve
the privacy issue. You still see people who have a certain amount
of fame and don't know how to deal with it.
   ``There's no good answer for when something that is unique to an
individual _ their privacy _ is taken away. ... When you experience
the loss of that, it's something you'll never ever get back in your
life. There's no reason to cry or to pout.
   ``It's something I'll never get back. It's like my daughter as
she grows older, she'll never be a baby again. You have to enjoy
those times. My son just started to walk. We probably will not have
any more children, so there will never be another helpless,
helpless child. That phase is gone.''
   The Costners recently bought a getaway home in Santa Barbara,
but their main residence is not on the trendy West Side, but in La
Canada, a few miles from the Pasadena Rose Bowl.
   ``We bought our first home in Pasadena,'' he said. ``A lot of
our friends are out there, so we can keep those relationships up.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 12-14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
