<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Mandrell Adv12-14   05-01 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Mandrell, Adv 12-14,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, May 12-14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Barbara Mandrell Revives Memories Of Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Barbara Mandrell curtailed
her career as she recovered from the physical and emotional
injuries of an automobile accident. She also tried to forget the
tragedy, which claimed the life of a young man.
   Now, though, she's revived those memories in her upcoming
autobiography for Bantam Books, ``Never Say Never.''
   ``Until this book, I have never shared these things except with
my neurosurgeon and my attorney,'' the 40-year-old singer said in
an interview.
   ``Other than this book, I have kind of reached a point where I'm
tired of being asked about it. I chose to forget it. But the
tragedy was part of my life, and I had to put it in. In order for
people to know me, I felt I must tell the down side. The chapter on
the crash was very difficult to do.''
   Mandrell was involved in a two-car collision north of Nashville
on Sept. 11, 1984. She suffered a concussion and fractures to her
leg and ankle. Her two children also were hurt, but not seriously.
However, the driver of the other car, a 19-year-old college
student, died.
   The book is being written with author George Vecsey, who helped
country queen Loretta Lynn write her ``Coal Miner's Daughter.''
   Finishing the autobiography is just one of a multitude of
projects for the singer who's been a recording artist for 20 years.
   Her second gospel album, ``Precious Memories,'' has just been
released. Her Las Vegas-style show, regarded as one of the best
among country music-oriented performers, is undergoing its annual
fine-tuning. She has had one week-long stint performing in Las
Vegas this year and has two more scheduled.
   ``My throat won't take more than a week at a time,'' she said.
   And she is selecting songs for another country album due out in
the fall.
   ``I'm working a lot more this year,'' she said. ``I told my
agent that except for January and July, to book me three days a
month. But some of those three days turned into a week.''
   She's rarely been off the TV screen since her network variety
show that began in 1980 and lasted two seasons, ``Barbara Mandrell
and the Mandrell Sisters.'' She's done a half dozen specials with
comedian Bob Hope, including his most recent one in March. And
she's been in countless other TV specials, ranging from appearances
with former President and Mrs. Reagan to one celebrating the
Special Olympics.
   ``I just said no to two more recently,'' she said.
   One of them was to be taped during a week she and her family had
set aside for camping.
   ``My priorities were to be a mommy and wife that week,'' she
said.
   Her gospel album is a follow-up to her previous gospel-oriented
``He Set My Life to Music,'' which won a Grammy Award in 1983. The
new one includes such gospel standards as ``Peace in the Valley,''
``Old Rugged Cross,'' ``Just a Closer Walk With Thee'' and ``I Love
to Tell the Story.''
   ``It was hard to narrow it down to the 20 we picked,'' Mandrell
said. ``I had the best time doing this album. For any Christian,
especially one who sings for a living, the feeling is very special.
   ``These are songs that I feel are mine and you feel are yours.
They belong to each of us. We grew up singing them. I had so many
memories as I recorded them, of singing them in church or singing
along to the radio.
   ``This was a nice, unexpected pleasure. Now I'll have these on
record for the rest of my life. When I'm gone, my children and
grandchildren will have them.''
   She has a persistent passion for another hit record to join her
others: ``I Was Country (When Country Wasn't Cool),'' ``Married,
But Not to Each Other,'' ``Only a Lonely Heart Knows,'' ``Sleeping
Single in a Double Bed'' and ``If Loving You Is Wrong (I Don't Want
to Be Right).''
   ``It's a never-ending desire. My biggest goal is to stay close
enough in tune with what the public wants in order to earn the
career they are giving me. I've never been satisfied with me. I
always want to be better and I pray I never lose that desire.
   ``We're chomping at the bit to make my show better. I compete
with me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 12-14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
