<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, May 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Researchers Try To Develop Artificial Oyster Reefs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine researchers hoping to boost oyster
production in the Gulf of Mexico are experimenting with reefs of
coal ash and cement.
   Oyster fishermen used to dump the shells back into the water,
providing a nice hard bed that the oysters could anchor to, but
they since discovered there was a market for the shells in
road-building and calcium supplements.
   ``If the baby oyster falls on something hard, then he attaches
to it and forms a shell; if he fall on the mud bottom, then he
dies,'' said Mississippi Power Co. spokesman John Hutchinson.
   The utility, which has a steady supply of ash, is working with
Mississippi State University and state agencies on an aggregate of
ash and cement mixed and molded into baseball-sized pellets.
Clusters of pellets form the reefs. Adult oysters were put into
four ponds with artificial reefs several weeks ago.
   Results may not come for a year, the time it takes for oysters
to mature.
   But in a study in Delaware, ``we saw no difference in mortality
in oyster growth or ash and concrete versus oyster growth on clam
shells,'' said Kent Price, associate dean of marine studies at the
University of Delaware.
   Preliminary figures also indicate the artificial beds could be
cheaper than buying clam shells, which are dredged from lakes
Pontchartrain and Maurepas in Louisiana _ a practice decried by
environmentalists. Mississippi $150,000 last year putting clam
shells in the Gulf and $12,500 on oyster shells, Price said.
   Researchers expect the aggregate to cost $9 to $10 per ton,
compared with $15 a ton for shells, Hutchinson said. ``If we can't
beat the price of the clam shells, then we've priced ourselves out
of the market.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Johns Hopkins University $20 Million Heart Disease Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAGERSTOWN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers will be looking for 5,000
older recruits for a $20 million, four-year study of the causes of
heart disease and strokes _ blamed for more than half the deaths of
people aged 65 and older.
   The Johns Hopkins University Researchers, funded by the National
Institutes of Health, will be recruiting people 65 and older in
Washington County, Md.; Forsyth County, N.C.; Allegheny County,
Pa.; and Sacramento County, Calif.
   ``It's only recently that we understand that getting older
doesn't have to be associated with these diseases,'' said Dr. Linda
Fried, who will lead the study. ``There is room to prevent these
diseases and enhance the health of older adults. That is really
what the goal of this study is.''
   The four sites were chosen because they had a stable population
of people ages 65 and over, and had enough trained medical
personnel to do the tests, said Dr. Teri Manolio of the National
Heart, Lung and Blood Institute.
   Participants will be given a physical and asked about their
eating and health habits and medical and reproductive history.
Researchers will measure heartbeats, breathing, blood sugar and
cholesterol, and will determine whether there is any narrowing of
arteries linking the heart and brain. Participants will be
contacted every six months by telephone and in person. After three
years, they will be asked to have a follow-up examination.
   Fried said initial test results would be compiled within two
years. Final research results are expected to be released in four
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
