<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-01 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0882</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's WPP Group PLC has proposed a $730
million buyout of the Ogilvy Group Inc. that would create a giant
advertising holding company vying with Britain's Saatchi &amp; Saatchi
PLC as the world's largest, Ogilvy disclosed.
   Ogilvy, the New York-based parent company of Ogilvy &amp; Mather
Worldwide, said Sunday the offer was unsolicited and that the
company wanted to remain independent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said its chief economic
forecasting gauge took a 0.7 percent nosedive in March, marking the
first back-to-back declines in more than a year in a portent of
progressive weakening in the economy.
   Analysts said the performance thus far of the Index of Leading
Economic Indicators is another sign that the economy is losing
steam and that the slowdown will become more pronounced later this
year.
   Should the index point downward again for April, that would make
three declines in a row, the traditional signal of a forthcoming
recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration charged 34 countries
with erecting significant trade barriers against U.S. products in
the first stage of a process that could result in retaliation
against nations that refuse to open their doors to American goods.
   The U.S. review, ordered by the 1988 trade law, has raised fears
from Bonn, West Germany, to Tokyo about what actions the United
States might take against countries it brands as persistently
unfair traders.
   Japan was given the most space in the report with 18 pages of
complaints about trade barriers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobil Corp., long a proponent of doing business
in South Africa, said it was leaving the racially-divided nation
after 90 years of business there and will take a net loss of $140
million on the move.
   The oil giant said it was selling operations once valued at more
than $400 million to General Mining Union Corp. Ltd. for more than
$155 million in cash plus $10 million that was expected to be the
operation's 1989 profit.
   Mobil Chairman Allen E. Murray blamed U.S. foreign policies,
including a 1987 law that eliminated certain tax credits for U.S.
companies doing business in South Africa, ultimately forcing the
pullout.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire hotelier Jay Pritzker and other
suitors formally have submitted bids for strikebound Eastern
Airlines, but the carrier remained locked on its planned course of
cutting operations and selling $1.8 billion in assets.
   While confirming that the airline had received an offer from
Pritzker, Eastern spokesman Robin Matell insisted ``there are still
no bona fide offers to buy Eastern.''
   Eastern's managers recently detailed plans to operate at
one-third the airline's pre-strike size and raise cash by selling
assets, including planes, airport gates and landing slots at
unspecified locations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever, the European consumer products
conglomerate, said it dropped its plan to purchase the Faberge and
Elizabeth Arden lines of toiletries, cosmetics and fragrances for
$1.55 billion from Riklis Family Corp.
   Negotiations on a definitive pact broke down because the Riklis
group sought ``significant changes in the structure and terms of
the transaction which would have involved Unilever in substantial
additional costs,'' according to an announcement from Unilever
United States Inc., the U.S. arm of the British-Dutch giant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some state securities regulators say they are
ready to go easy on Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the Wall Street
firm that has pledged to admit to felonies and pay millions in
fines to resolve federal civil and criminal fraud charges.
   State securities officials met in Washington to discuss punitive
action against Drexel, which faces losing its state brokerage
licenses and fines for its role in the Wall Street insider trading
scandals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The moisture probe that farmer and
cattleman Jerry Porter poked into the central Kansas wheat field
sunk only a couple of inches and brought up dust instead of damp,
compacted earth.
   ``That tells the story on the moisture here,'' said Porter, who
with more than 70 other farmers and agriculture experts spent 2{
days testing and examining plants in fields of the nation's top
winter wheat-producing states in the central Great Plains: Kansas,
Oklahoma, Texas, Colorado and Nebraska.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's largest horseshoe maker is
hoping President Bush will pitch the backyard sport into the
American consciousness and boost its sales the way his predecessor
helped the jelly bean industry.
   The first 100 days of the horseshoe-happy president have brought
smiles to St. Pierre Manufacturing Co., a second-generation factory
begun by an amateur inventor more than a half-century ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed little change in slackened trading
Friday, bogging down after Thursday's rally to new post-crash
highs. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .19 to
2,418.80.
   The dollar rose sharply against all major currencies except the
Canadian dollar. Gold prices took a tumble.
   Bond prices fell.
   Precious metals futures dropped sharply; wheat futures rose
while corn and soybean prices fell; cattle prices rallied but hog
prices retreated; and energy prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
