<FIRST>r f PM-CapitalSpending     05-01 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Spending,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Companies' Budget For Capital Spending Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. companies' appropriations for spending on
new plant and equipment rose 33 percent in the last quarter of 1988
from the third quarter, the Conference Board said in a report for
release today.
   The budget authorizations rose to $53.7 billion in the fourth
quarter from $40.3 billion in the preceding quarter and $30.8
billion in the fourth quarter of 1987, the business-supported
research organization said.
   Appropriations are considered a good indicator of how high
capital spending will be. They are the first step, preceding the
ordering of equipment, the letting of construction contracts and
actual spending.
   The petroleum industry led all sectors with a 157 percent
increase in appropriations from the preceding quarter.
   ``The best guess is that business investment this year will very
sharply outpace the overall growth in the economy,'' Ken Goldstein,
a Conference Board economist, said in a statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
