<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-CoalTax     05-01 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Coal Tax,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peabody Loses Arizona Tax Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coal company seeking more than $42 million
in refunds on Arizona state taxes it paid for mining operations on
the Navajo and Hopi Indian reservations lost a Supreme Court appeal
today.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that Arizona's
transaction privilege tax properly was imposed on the Peabody Coal
Co.'s on-reservation mining.
   Lawyers for Peabody, which is based in Flagstaff, Ariz., argued
that the tax infringes on tribal sovereignty and is pre-empted by
federal law.
   State courts rejected those arguments after finding that the
taxes imposed no burden on the tribes.
   Under lease agreements, Peabody mines coal from Navajo tribal
land at the Kayenta Mine and from the Navajo-Hopi joint-use tribal
land at the Black Mesa Mine.
   Virtually all of the coal mined at the two sites is sold to
electric power consortiums under contracts that reimburse Peabody
for all state privilege taxes it pays.
   From 1970 through 1979, Peabody paid the state tax without
protest.
   But the company's lawsuit against the state and its Department
of Revenue sought refunds for taxes paid from 1980 through 1985
under protest.
   Lawyers for the coal company said that by 1986 the amount in
controversy was about $42 million. With interest, that sum has
grown.
   The case is Peabody Coal vs. Arizona, 88-1399.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
