<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-DetroitJOA 1stLd-Writethru f0029 05-01 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Detroit JOA, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court To Review Detroit Newspaper Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 6 grafs of reaction after 18th graf, Knight-Ridder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review a
challenge to the partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers.
   The justices said they will judge the validity of former
Attorney General Edwin Meese's decision to allow the newspapers to
form a joint operating agreement.
   A decision is not expected until sometime in 1990.
   The partial merger is being challenged by a group of Michigan
readers and advertisers.
   The federal Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 law authorizes
the attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an
exemption from federal antitrust laws.
   Under the joint operating agreement, The Detroit Free Press and
The Detroit News would combine their business, advertising and
production departments but maintain separate news and editorial
staffs.
   The high court, by a 7-2 vote, cleared the way for the deal
March 20 when it set aside an earlier postponement ordered by
Justice William J. Brennan.
   Only Justices Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens voted in
March to continue the postponement. But it takes the votes of four
justices to grant review to a formal appeal.
   After the March vote, lawyers for the newspapers said they would
await the outcome of the formal appeal, which was acted on today.
   A federal appeals court panel here voted 2-1 last January to
uphold Meese's decision to allow the partial merger. The full
appeals court split 5-4 last February in refusing to review the
three-judge panel's ruling.
   Opponents to the joint operating agreement, calling themselves
Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, contend that the Free
Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., is not a failing newspaper even
though it lost $10 million a year between 1981 and 1986.
   The opponents say the Free Press and News, which lost $50
million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both
papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out
of business.
   ``The losses the papers have suffered are the product of
vigorous competition,'' said the appeal acted on today.
   It contended that the Detroit deal ``threatens the independence
of papers in the 25 cities that have competing dailies, since it
provides a roadmap for profitable papers to obtain a JOA, and the
monopoly profits that can be obtained in a non-competitive market.''
   But in urging the justices to reject the challenge, Bush
administration lawyers cited the ``variety of considerations'' that
went into Meese's decision.
   ``A newspaper in another city could hardly use this case as a
guide for obtaining the attorney general's approval for a JOA,''
the government lawyers said.
   Gannett Co., which owns the News, is the nation's largest
newspaper publishing group. Knight-Ridder is the second largest.
   Knight-Ridder has said it might close the Free Press if the
joint operating agreement is not consummated.
   ``This process has been an extraordinary lesson in patience,''
Free Press Publisher David Lawrence said after the court acted
today. ``The people of the Free Press have already waited more than
three years to assure this newspaper's future.
   ``I remain confident that what is at stake is vital to the
people of Michigan, and confident that what is proposed is fully
justified.''
   News Publisher Robert Giles referred calls for comment to
Gannett headquarters in Arlington, Va., where spokeswoman Sheila
Gibbons declined comment.
   ``We're delighted,'' said David Vladeck, attorney for Public
Citizen, an advocacy group that handled the legal work on the
challenge to the business agreement.
   Public Citizen had not only argued the agreement would threaten
newspaper competition in other cities but that a lower court's
ruling had set precedents for administrative law that would greatly
restrict judicial review of executive actions.
   ``I suspect that the fact that this case presented both issues
made it doubly appealing to the court,'' Vladeck said.
   Under the 100-year agreement, the News would receive 55 percent
of the merged company's profits during the first year but that
percentage would drop to 50 percent by the seventh year.
   Thereafter, the profits would be evenly divided.
   The case is Michigan Citizens For an Independent Press vs.
Thornburgh, 88-1640.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
