<DOCNO> AP890501-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Ben&amp;Jerry's-Dreyer's     05-01 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ben &amp; Jerry's-Dreyer's,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ben &amp; Jerry's To Be Manufactured By Dreyer's In Indiana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben &amp; Jerry's Homemade Inc. has reached a
definitive agreement with Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream Inc. to have
some of its ice cream made at Dreyer's Indiana plant, the companies
announced Monday.
   James Miller, general manager for Ben &amp; Jerry's, said the
company has exhausted its capacity and that demand for the ice
cream is far outstripping supply. He said the company is not
interested in building a third plant in the state right now.
   Under a three-year agreement, Dreyer's will manufacture Ben &amp;
Jerry's products at Dreyers' Fort Wayne, Ind., plant using Vermont
dairy products.
   Dreyer's, an Oakland-Calif.-based company, makes and distributes
ice cream and other dairy-based products, including Ben &amp; Jerry's
in Midwest and West Coast markets.
   By 1992, Miller said, about 3.5 million gallons of ice cream
will be produced in Indiana; the Waterbury-based company currently
sells 5 million gallons annually, and projects it will be selling 8
million gallons a year by 1992.
   The company currently operates two Vermont plants, one in
Waterbury and one in Springfield. The Waterbury plant, built in
1985, produces ice cream in pint packages and bulk ice cream for
franchise shops. The Springfield plant makes ice cream novelties.
   Miller said it would not be economically feasible for the
company to convert parts of the plant for producing pints.
   Since partners Ben Cohen and Jerry Greenfield opened shop in an
old filling station in Burlington in 1978, Ben &amp; Jerry's has grown
into a $40 million corporation.
   Miller said the company is not moving any of its Vermont
operations to Indiana. The decision reflects the current limits of
both its factory and management staff, he said.
   ``Because of our rapid growth, we didn't have the strength up
and down our management to take on another plant,'' he said.
Mnaufacturing staff at the new plant will be Dreyers' employees, he
said, but quality control staff will be hired by Ben &amp; Jerry's.
   The new arrangement will also help Ben &amp; Jerry's' marketing
strategy, enabling the company to move more easily into major
markets west of the Mississippi, especially California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
