<DOCNO> AP890501-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-SexBias 1stLd-Writethru f0062 05-01 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Sex Bias, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0062,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Looks At Sex Bias Case And Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 15th pvs, She later, to make a Scotus
roundup; edits 16th graf pvs to conform, picks up 17th, She had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharply divided Supreme Court ruled today
the burden is on employers to disprove sexual stereotyping when
they are accused of discriminating against women.
   By a 6-3 vote, the justices ordered further lower court hearings
in a suit against the accounting firm Price Waterhouse by Ann
Hopkins, who said she was denied a partnership because of ``macho''
attitudes that she did not behave sufficiently ladylike.
   Today's ruling also is a partial victory for Price Waterhouse.
The court overturned a lower court ruling that would have placed an
even heavier burden of proof on the company.
   Moreover, only four of the justices agreed on the standards that
should govern lawsuits alleging sexual stereoptyping.
   The absence of a court majority enunciating clear guidelines is
likely to sow confusion among lower courts when deciding such cases.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in the court's main opinion, said
when someone ``proves that her gender played a motivating part in
an employment decision, the defendant may avoid a finding of
liability only by proving by a preponderance of the evidence that
it would have made the same decision even if it had not taken the
plantiff's gender into account.''
   Joining his opinion were Justices Thurgood Marshall, John Paul
Stevens and Harry A. Blackmun.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, in a separate concurring opinion,
agreed that in the case of Price Waterhouse, ``the burden of
persuasion should shift to the employer to demonstrate by a
preponderance of the evidence that it would have reached the same
decision concerning Ann Hopkins' candidacy absent consideration of
her gender.''
   But O'Connor said she does not favor ``the strong medicine'' of
forcing employers to bear the burden of proof in all such cases.
   Justice Byron R. White also concurred in today's result. But in
a separate opinion he said he would not require an employer to
submit ``objective evidence'' to disprove sexual bias in such cases.
   As long as ``the employer credibly testifies that the action
would have been taken for legitimate reasons alone, this should be
ample proof,'' White said.
   The three dissenters are Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy. They voted to kill
Ms. Hopkins' suit.
   Kennedy, in his opinion for the three, said there was ample
evidence that Price Waterhouse did not discriminate against her
intentionally.
   Ms. Hopkins quit Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's so-called
``Big Eight'' accounting firms, after she was denied promotion to
partnership in 1983 _ a move that would have made her a part owner.
   She later became a consultant to the World Bank.
   In other actions today, the Supreme Court:
   _Agreed to review a challenge to review to the partial merger of
Detroit's two daily newspapers. The justices said they will judge
the validity of former Attorney General Edwin Meese's decision to
allow the newspapers to form a joint operating agreement.
   _Agreed to hear a Bush administration apeal aimed at allowing
the government to collect potentially hundreds of millions of
dollars in taxes from multinational corporations.
   _Refused to hear an appeal by Hawaii officials seeking to
recover from asbestos manufacturers the cost of removing the
product from public schools in the state.
   In the sex bias case, Ms. Hopkins had joined Price Waterhouse in
1978 and was nominated for parntership in 1982, the only woman
among 88 candidates for partnership that year.
   She had been very successful in getting business for the
company, winning government contracts worth between $34 million and
$44 million.
   Both her critics and supporters at Price Watershouse said she
sometimes was overly agreessive, too harsh, impatient with her
staff and very demanding.
   One critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm
school.''
   A partner who supported her for promotion told her she would
stand a better chance of getting ahead if she would ``walk more
femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear
make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.''
   Ms. Hopkins sued Price Waterhouse on grounds it violated Title
VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting on-the-job
discrimination. She said sexual stereotyping, unconscious or
otherwise, cost her a partnership.
   Professinal partnerships are covered by the 1964 law under a
1984 Supreme Court ruling.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled in 1987 that while
there appeared to be mixed motives in denying Ms. Hopkins a
partnership, Price Waterhouse was unable to prove that
``impermissible bias was not the determinative factor'' for the
decision.
   The appeals court said an employer must show by ``clear and
convincing evidence'' they did not practice bias.
   The Supreme Court today did not go that far.
   The ``clear and convincing'' standard usually means that to
successfully defend against a lawsuit, a company must show that the
overwhelming evidence is in its favor.
   By contrast, the ``preponderance'' standard adopted today means
Price Waterhouse can win if it can show more than half the evidence
is in its favor.
   The case is Price Waterhouse vs. Hopkins, 87-1167.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
