<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0269</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade in the wake of forecasts
for below-average rainfall during the next three months.
   The National Weather Service's 30- to 90-day forecast released
Friday predicts most western crop areas, including western
Illinois, Missouri, Iowa and Minnesota, will be drier than normal
through July.
   Wheat prices opened lower as uncertainty continues over the Bush
administration's position on continuing subsidized grain sales to
foreign countries.
   Today is a holiday in most of the world, and that could slow
trading in the pits.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.17\ a bushel; corn was 2\
cents to 3} cents higher with May at $2.72{ a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 2{ cents higher with May at $1.80{ a bushel; soybeans were
5 cents to 7} cents with May at $7.27 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercaantile Exchange.
