<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Polaroid-Kodak 1stLd-Writethru   05-01 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Kodak, 1st Ld-Writethru,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Refuses To Hear Kodak Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court action; ADD
background on Texaco-Pennzoil case; picks up 14th graf pvs, ``We're not
....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to hear
Eastman Kodak Co.'s appeal of a federal court ruling that the
company infringed on instant film and camera patents held by
Polaroid Corp.
   Kodak argued that the 1985 ruling should be thrown out because
U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel, who presided over the trial, had a
conflict of interest in the case.
   A federal appeals court that earlier heard Kodak's appeal noted
that Zobel announced to both companies in 1981 that her
mother-in-law owned Kodak shares and that Kodak raised no
objection. The appeals court said that it was not until 1988, well
after Zobel's liability ruling against Kodak, that the company
objected.
   Since the Supreme Court refuses to hear the case, the federal
appeal's court ruling against Kodak is the final word.
   In Boston, opening arguments began today in the trial to
determine the damages Kodak must pay Polaroid.
   By copying Polaroid's technology, Kodak forced its rival to sell
some cameras below cost and enormously damaged the instant
photography market, Polaroid lawyers said.
   The trial before Judge A. David Mazzone in U.S. District Court
is expected by many securities analysts to result in Kodak paying
Polaroid about $1 billion, which would be the largest patent damage
award in history.
   The trial is expected to take four to six months.
   ``You start talking and I'll start listening, and as the famous
saying goes, I hope you finish before I do,'' Mazzone told the
Kodak and Polaroid lawyers.
   Polaroid attorney Herbert F. Schwartz argued that Polaroid was
entitled to $3.9 billion in lost profits because of Kodak's sales
of instant cameras and film between 1976 and 1986.
   In addition, Schwartz argued that Polaroid is entitled to
interest and triple punitive damages, bringing the total to just
under $12 billion.
   In a previous trial, a judge ruled in October 1985 that Kodak
had violated seven of Polaroid's key patents on instant film and
cameras _ and booted Kodak out of the instant photography business,
saddling it with $600 million of losses and an estimated $200
million worth of useless manufacturing equipment.
   The only issue in the current trial is the value of the damage
caused by Kodak.
   Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak argues that the most Polaroid should
get is $177 million, representing a 5 percent royalty on all the
instant film and cameras that Kodak sold from 1976 to 1986.
   Lawyers said the record award in a patent infringement lawsuit
was approximately $200 million that Hughes Tool Co. received from
Dresser Industries in 1986.
   A multibillion-dollar verdict could force Kodak to make layoffs,
take on huge debt and sell subsidiaries to raise cash. It could
leave the company unable to make the investments it needs to
compete with Japanese film makers.
   If the award is near the top of the possible range, it could
even force Kodak into a Chapter 11 bankruptcy, just as Texaco Inc.
was forced to reorganize when a jury ordered it to pay $10.3
billion to Pennzoil Co. four years ago. Texaco emerged from Chapter
11 a year ago after paying Pennzoil $3 billion in cash to settle
the case.
   But securities analysts say a Chapter 11 filing is unlikely.
Most Wall Street brokerage houses are predicting an award of about
$1 billion, and traders say the stock prices of both companies
already reflect that expectation.
   ``We're not going to see another Texaco here,'' said Peter
Enderlin, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   Polaroid, which recently spent $1.1 billion to buy back stock
and fend off a hostile takeover by Shamrock Holdings Inc., is
expected to use part of any award to lower its corporate debt.
   Alex Henderson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said he reckoned Polaroid's stock price probably will rise or
fall about $1 for every $100 million of the award that is above or
below Wall Street's expectations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
