<DOCNO> AP890501-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LouisianaTaxes 1stLd-Writethru f0015 05-01 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Louisiana Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0015,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Governor Says Some Hospitals, Universities Likely Will
Be Closed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with governor's comments this morning.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Roemer's plan...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters' rejection of Gov. Buddy Roemer's
tax plan will mean the likely closures of hospitals and
universities and the layoffs of thousands of state employees, the
governor said today.
   ``We don't have all the specifics yet. We'll let you know as
soon as we can,'' an obviously weary Roemer told reporters at an
impromptu news conference.
   The governor was closeted late into the night Sunday with
advisers to decide how to approach a budget that is now $700
million short of balance for the new fiscal year beginning July 1.
   Voters on Saturday rejected the plan by 55 percent to 45
percent, according to unofficial returns.
   Roemer, who traveled around the state for six weeks trying to to
sell the plan, faces questions about his political future just 13
months after he took office as a reformer promising a ``new
Louisiana.''
   ``I'm not worried about that. I'm concerned about this state,''
Roemer said, fielding questions on the Capitol steps. ``There will
be a referendum on Buddy Roemer in 2{ years.''
   Roemer's plan would have shifted the tax burden away from big
business, putting more of a load on individuals through the income
tax. It would have reduced sales taxes and given businesses
incentives to move to Louisiana and expand.
   The plan also included a $1.4 billion program to improve
highways, airports and shipping ports, funded by a gasoline tax
increase of 4 cents a gallon.
   Roemer touted his plan as a way to bring jobs to Louisiana,
which has the nation's highest unemployment rate at 9.6 percent,
and to end the state's dependence on the oil industry.
   The oil, gas and chemical industry paid more than half of the
state taxes for nearly 50 years until its collapse in 1982.
   Since then, state government has hovered near bankruptcy.
   ``I never worked harder in my life to try to turn this around,''
the Democratic governor said. ``We're going to keep building, but
not as fast as I wanted to.''
   ``This plan will tell America that we've changed, that we're
ready to pay our way,'' Roemer said repeatedly during his trips
around the state.
   Opponents condemned it as nothing more than a huge tax increase
and said Roemer had not reduced spending as promised during his
1987 campaign, when he unseated Edwin Edwards.
   Rep. David Duke, an outspoken critic of the plan, said its
defeat was ``going to make a real change in Louisiana.'' He called
on Roemer to work with legislators in tightening spending and
making major changes in its welfare programs.
   Duke, a former Ku Klux Klan leader elected as a Republican to a
suburban New Orleans seat on an anti-tax plank in February,
compared the referendum's outcome to his own victory. ``Every day
that passes, I'm more and more in awe of the intelligence and the
good sense in our state,'' he said.
   Even with passage of the plan, the Legislature would have been
forced to cut spending by $200 million to keep the budget balanced.
   Roemer met all day Sunday with his closest advisers on how to
cut the budget.
   ``The people want closures. I really believe that,'' Rep. Robert
Adley, chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, said as he
left the meeting at the governor's mansion. ``They sent us a signal
that we haven't done enough.
   ``It could be from one to several universities or more.
Hospitals could be from three to five,'' the Democrat said. ``Right
now we're trying to find every way in the world that a degree of
services can be rendered.''
   Louisiana has 18 public universities and eight charity hospitals.
   ``The people sent a signal that they want more cuts,'' added
Steve Cochran, Roemer's chief of staff. ``I'm not sure what goes
through the minds of citizens when they think of budget cuts. They
think of waste, of extras. Unfortunately, to live within the
limitations set here, we'll probably have to do more than the
average citizen expects.''
   Cochran said thousands of the state's 80,000 employees likely
would lose their jobs. The administration would determine within a
week all specific cuts, he said.
   ``When you close institutions, that means people lose jobs,'' he
said.
   As for Roemer's political future, political consultant and
pollster Ed Renwick of Loyola University said the governor was
``badly wounded, but not critically wounded.''
   Silas Lee, a Loyola University political scientist, said,
``Roemer couldn't sell his plan to blue-collar whites, many of whom
think David Duke is on the ball, and he couldn't sell it to blacks,
who didn't think there would really be thousands of jobs for them.''
</TEXT>
