<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;L-Wall     05-01 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L-Wall,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall: Thrift Industry Not Ready To Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny
Wall said Monday that reports of the savings and loan industry's
death have been greatly exaggerated.
   ``Don't get caught up that the industry is some sort of a
dinosaur,'' he told the Society of American Business Editors and
Writers. ``The industry is doing well within the healthy sector.''
   Speaking in typical optimistic fashion, Wall said that 88
percent of the nation's 3,000 S&amp;Ls, representing 92 percent of the
industy's assets, are considered solvent, and Congress is working
to dispose of the rest.
   Troubled thrifts accounted for the bulk of the $12.1 billion in
industrywide losses in 1988, with Texas institutions again emerging
as the biggest losers.
   ``The future of the industry is being made ever clear ... as
legislative discussion continues,'' Wall said. ``Congress continues
to be supportive of the thrift industry and in its purpose.''
   He said that he expected a thrift bailout bill to pass through
Congress by mid-June.
   Last week, the Senate overwhelmingly approved a record $157
billion bailout and reform bill for the S&amp;L industry after
toughening provisions that would require S&amp;L owners to put more of
their own money at risk to stay in business. Similar S&amp;L
legislation is pending in the House.
</TEXT>
