<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-CableDispute     05-01 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Cable Dispute,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Reject Challenge to Dallas Cable System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away a cable
television dispute from Dallas, in which the city was held liable
for violating the free-speech rights of a non-franchised company.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear the city's appeal
in a case still pending in a federal trial court.
   Video International Productions Inc. (VIP) sued the city and
Warner-Amex Cable Communications Inc., the sole franchised cable TV
company in Dallas, for allegedly trying to put VIP out of business.
   A federal court jury awarded VIP $4.4 million in damages, but
major portions of that judgment were overturned by the presiding
judge.
   U.S. District Judge Sidney Fitzwater threw out all claims
against Warner-Amex and claims that the city had interfered
improperly with a contract to sell VIP.
   But the judge upheld the jury's findings that the city violated
VIP's free-speech rights and federal antitrust law. He also ruled
that the city was immune from punitive damages.
   In all, the dollar amount of VIP's legal victory was cut to
$200,000.
   Both VIP and Dallas city officials appealed, and the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals last Oct. 31 ruled that the city was
legally liable to VIP.
   But the appeals court sent the dispute back to Fitzwater for a
new trial on the amount of damages to be paid.
   ``We are unable to discern a reasonable explanation for the
jury's wide-ranging verdicts,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is Dallas vs. Video International Productions, 88-1488.
</TEXT>
