<FIRST>r f AM-ChiChi'sLawsuit     05-01 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chi Chi's Lawsuit,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chi-Chi's Restaurant Chain Sues Local Eatery With Similar Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOMERS POINT, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national chain of Chi-Chi's
Mexican restaurants is suing a local eatery named Chi Chi's that
specializes in crab imperial, not tacos.
   The small-town Chi Chi's _ without a hyphen in between _ was
named in 1968 after the nickname of the previous owner's wife.
Chi-Chi's Inc., a chain of 190 Mexican restaurants headquartered in
Louisville, Ky., opened its first restaurant in Minneapolis in 1976.
   ``We are just a family operation,'' said Jack Bittner, the new
owner who operates the landmark Somers Point restaurant with his
wife, Jillian. ``They're a national company telling little old us
that we can't use the name that we had long before they ever came
along.''
   Bittner's attorney, Allen Vernon of Ocean City, will not say
whether Chi Chi's in Somers Point ever trademarked its name. He
said, however, that he is confident his clients will be successful
when their case comes to U.S. District Court in Camden in July.
   ``We have a long-standing prior uninterrupted use of the name,''
he said Monday.
   But the attorney representing Chi-Chi's Inc., James Rothschild
of Morristown, said, ``There is precedent supporting us.''
   In its lawsuit, Chi-Chi's Inc. claims that the Bittners' use of
the name is ``calculated to confuse, mislead, deceive and
perpetrate a fraud upon the public in New Jersey.''
   The Kentucky company has three restaurants in the state.
Chi-Chi's Inc. seeks to have the Bittners barred from using the
name and made to pay damages.
   ``We have a substantial national chain that has built a
tremendous amount of good will and we feel it's wrong for them to
utilize our name,'' Rothschild said.
</TEXT>
