<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1458EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Scotus-DetroitJOA     05-01 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Detroit JOA,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees to Hear Newspaper Merger Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court's decision Monday to review
the partial merger of two Detroit newspapers will force
Knight-Ridder Inc. to determine how much longer it can absorb
losses from its Detroit Free Press, analysts said.
   By agreeing to hear arguments on the proposed joint operating
agreement (JOA), the court set the stage for its first review of
the 19-year-old Newspaper Preservation Act. A decision is not
expected until next year.
   The Detroit News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., and the Free Press
agreed in 1986 to merge the newspapers' production, circulation and
business operations and to split profits and losses equally for
most of the 100-year arrangement.
   Knight-Ridder's president and chief executive officer, James K.
Battn, said the organization would plan over the coming days what
to do next.
   Batten said Knight-Ridder continues ``to believe strongly in the
fairness and justice of our case on behalf of a JOA in Detroit.''
   Gannett, through spokeswoman Sheila Gibbons, said it was
``reviewing the decision'' and would have no further comment.
   Both newspapers have been losing money for years, and
Knight-Ridder has said it will close the smaller Free Press unless
the partial merger goes through.
   ``Knight-Ridder's decision would be based upon its reading of
the length of time and the likelihood ... of this thing
happening,'' said John S. Reidy, communications industry analyst
with the New York brokerage house Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   ``Clearly, from their point of view, they would like to
eliminate the cash drain of the Free Press. ... On the other hand,
if they wait it out, then they'll have half interest in a JOA,
which will earn considerably more for them than the loss last year.
So it is a tough decision,'' Reidy said.
   The Free Press lost $18.5 million in 1988, Knight-Ridder said in
court filings earlier this year. Gannett has released no annual
loss figures for the News, but Knight-Ridder in testimony has
estimated the News' losses at $75 million from 1979 through 1987.
   The newspapers have said closing the Free Press would cost 2,200
jobs while a joint operating agreement would mean a total of 600 to
800 jobs lost at the two papers.
   Free Press employees at a staff meeting took news of the Supreme
Court's decision with a calm patience.
   ``We've been punched around so many times. It's like, okay,
we'll waltz with it again,'' said Neal Rubin, a feature writer.
   The partial merger, designed to retain newspaper competition
through an exemption to federal antitrust laws, was approved by the
Justice Department last year but was tied up by court challenges
from an organization of newspaper readers and advertisers, Michigan
Citizens for an Independent Press, and the Washington-based
advocacy group Public Citizen.
   They argued that the newspapers' losses resulted from management
decisions rather than being inherent in the Detroit media market
and that if the deal were approved, any well-off newspaper
publishing group could deliberately create conditions for an
antitrust exemption.
   Bush administration attorneys countered that a ``variety of
considerations'' had been behind the Justice Department's decision.
``A newspaper in another city could hardly use this case as a guide
for obtaining the attorney general's approval for a JOA,'' the
government lawyers said.
   William Schultz, a lawyer for Public Citizen, predicted
far-reaching results from the court's decision to hear arguments.
   ``It is the first test the court has heard under the Newspaper
Preservation Act. It is likely it will decide the meaning of the
act and the scope of the act for the future,'' Schultz said.
   A federal appeals court panel in Washington voted 2-1 in January
to uphold the Justice Department's decision to allow the partial
merger. The full appeals court then split 5-4 in February in
refusing to review the three-judge panel's ruling.
   The Supreme Court, by a 7-2 vote, cleared the way for the deal
March 20 when it set aside an earlier postponement ordered by
Justice William J. Brennan.
   Only Justices Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens voted in
March to continue the postponement; the votes of four justices are
needed to grant review to a formal appeal.
   When the court's stay was lifted, Knight-Ridder proposed
proceeding with the partial merger. Gannett declined to do so.
   No stay is in effect, and the newspapers would have the option
of merging while awaiting the Supreme Court's decision on the case.
   Gannett, based in Arlington, Va., is the nation's largest
newspaper publishing group. Knight-Ridder, headquartered in Miami,
is the second largest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
