<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     05-01 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0296</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled back today, faced with
evidence of persistent strength in the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 13.92 points to
2,404.88 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 3 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 517 up, 893
down and 491 unchanged.
   Analysts said investors were caught off guard by signs of a
pickup in business activity, as reported by the National
Association of Purchasing Management.
   The trade group said the pace of business tracked by its members
stepped up in April to a brisk pace.
   That came as unwelcome news to stock and bond traders who had
been banking on a continued slowing in the economy, in keeping with
the Federal Reserve's aim of restraining inflation.
   The news sent interest rates higher in the credit markets.
Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, fell about $5 for each $1,000 in
face value.
   Among the blue chips, International Business Machines dropped ~
to 113\; Philip Morris 1[ to 126; Ford Motor \ to 47{, and American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph ] to 34{.
   Ogilvy Group jumped 17 to 49 in over-the-counter trading. WPP
Group PLC proposed a $45-a-share offer for the advertising firm,
and traders quickly began to speculate about the possibility of a
higher bid.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.73 to 172.40. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .12 at 344.96.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 109.63 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
