<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-01 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0251</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to long-range
forecasts of below-average rainfall in several grain-producing
states.
   The National Weather Service on Friday released 30- and 90-day
forecasts that predicted a return to dry conditions in the western
half of the Farm Belt, including Iowa and Illinois.
   The forecasts fueled talk of a return of drought conditions,
pushing up prices across the board.
   ``It was a very typical weather-related price movement,'' said
Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New
York. ``There is a lot of uncertainty in the market, and the market
should reflect that uncertainty into the summer.''
   Wheat was strong because of severe weather conditions, and
despite continued uncertainty over the Bush administration's
position on continuing subsidized grain sales to foreign countries.
   Prices were helped by rumors that the Bush administration could
make a decision soon that would allow the Soviet Union to purchase
up to 3 million metric tons of grain.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 6\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.23} a bushel; corn was 4\ cents
to 5} cents higher with May at $2.74 a bushel; oats were 4 cents to
6} cents higher with May at $1.84{ a bushel; soybeans were 12{
cents to 17\ cents higher with May at $7.35 a bushel.
</TEXT>
