<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Arco     05-01 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Arco,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arco Profit Up 76 Percent On Gains From Lyondell Stock Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantic Richfield Co. said Monday its profit
rose 76 percent in the first quarter, due largely to gains from the
sale of a half interest in its Lyondell Petrochemical Co.
   Without that gain and other one-time charges against earnings,
net income in the quarter would have risen only 3.5 percent, said
Lodwrick M. Cook, Arco's chairman and chief executive officer.
   For the three-month period ended March 31, Arco's net earnings
totaled $704 million, or $4 per share, up from $401 million, or
$2.20 a share, in the first quarter of 1988. Revenue fell to $3.96
billion, down 14 percent from $4.61 billion a year earlier.
   The results included a $634 million after-tax gain from the sale
of 53.75 percent interest in Lyondell in January.
   Cook, who reported the results at the company's annual
shareholders meeting, said that discounting one-time gains and
charges, profit would have been $415 million.
   The gains were partially offset by $345 in after-tax charges for
unspecified environmental expenses, anticipated losses on the
planned sale of Arco Solar Inc. and a charge related to the sale of
the company's aluminum operation in 1985.
   Cook also said that the March oil spill in Alaska, which forced
a temporary halt to shipments from the port of Valdez, cost the
company about $10 million after taxes.
   Arco spokesman Albert Greenstein said the loss stemmed from a
combination of reduced production and lower oil flow through the
Alaska pipeline over a 12-day period after the March 24 spill.
   ``About 3.2 million barrels net to Arco was not delivered,''
said Albert Greenstein. ``So when you look at reduced deliveries to
Arco and reduced production _ we had to reduce production in one of
our refineries _ the overall after-tax loss was $10 million. Most
of that relates to loss of delivered crude.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
