<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TreasuryBills     05-01 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treasury Bills,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Bill Rates Fall In Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 8.64 percent, down from 8.66 percent
last week. Another $7 billion was sold in six-month bills at a
discount rate which also averaged 8.64 percent, down from 8.72
percent last week.
   The rates were the lowest since April 17 when three-month bills
sold for 8.57 percent and six-month bills averaged 8.59 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.96 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,781.60 and 9.16 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,563.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dipped to 9.22
percent last week from 9.28 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
