<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   05-01 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground Monday, faced with
news suggesting persistent strength in the economy.
   But after an early selloff, prices recovered much of their
losses.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down nearly 20 points
in the early going, closed with a minus-3.84 reading at 2,414.96.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
590 up, 832 down and 528 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came 138.05 million shares,
down from 158.39 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 171.53 million shares.
   Analysts said investors were put off a bit by signs of a pickup
in business activity, as reported by the National Association of
Purchasing Management.
   The trade group said the pace of business tracked by its members
stepped up in April to a brisk pace.
   That came as unwelcome news to stock and bond traders who had
been banking on a continued slowing in the economy, in keeping with
the Federal Reserve's aim of restraining inflation.
   The news sent interest rates higher in the credit markets.
Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, fell about $5 for each $1,000 in
face value.
   Another gauge of the economy's performance last month is due on
Friday with the Labor Department's report on the employment
situation. Advance estimates call for an increase in nonfarm
payroll employment in the 200,000 to 250,000 range.
   Among the blue chips, International Business Machines dropped }
to 113]; Philip Morris } to 126]; Ford Motor [ to 47|, and American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph ] to 34{.
   Ogilvy Group jumped 17[ to 49[ in over-the-counter trading. WPP
Group PLC proposed a $45-a-share offer for the advertising firm,
and traders quickly began to speculate about the possibility of a
higher bid.
   Carson Pirie Scott ranked among the top Big Board percentage
gainers, climbing 4] to 27. The company, which had earlier rejected
takeover bids of $20 a share and $24 a share from P.A. Bergner &amp;
Co., agreed to be acquired by Bergner for $27.50 a share.
   Kollmorgen lost 1{ to 23}. The company settled a takeover battle
by agreeing to a $25-a-share bid from Vernitron Corp.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $3.41 billion, or 0.11
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .31 to 172.82.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell .81 to 355.77, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down .52 at 309.12.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped .08 to 427.47. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 345.28, up .20.
</TEXT>
