<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1723EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-01 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens As Intervention Has Little Impact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Most European financial markets were closed Monday for a holiday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar wound up higher against all major
currencies in a thin market Monday as an unexpectedly strong
economic assessment from the nation's purchasing managers triggered
buying.
   Gold prices barely budged. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid of $377.45 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, 5
cents lower than Friday's late bid.
   Victor Polce, a vice president at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said
intervention by a few central banks had little lasting effect on
the dollar's movement.
   Trading volume was light in the United States. Most major
European financial markets were closed for a holiday. Individual
transactions have more of an impact on exchange rates in a market
in which relatively fewer trades are taking place.
   Foreign exchange dealers attributed part of the dollar's
strength to a monthly survey by the National Association of
Purchasing Management, which suggested economic growth regained
momentum in April.
   The purchasing managers' index, which measures new orders,
production, vendor deliveries, inventory and employment, went up to
53 percent in April after falling to 50.4 percent in March. Last
month's growth rate was roughly the same as the first quarter's
pace.
   An implication of the purchasing managers' survey was that
economic activity may not be slowing enough to induce the Federal
Reserve to ease its grip on credit. This would mean interest rates
would remain at current levels.
   Rising interest rates in the United States this year have
enhanced the appeal of dollar-denominated investments.
   Here are late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's
late rates: 134.125 Japanse yen, up from 133.05; 1.89065 West
German marks, up from 1.8810; 1.6870 Swiss francs, up from 1.6755;
6.375 French francs, up from 6.3580; 1,383.25 Italian lire, up from
1,377.00; and 1.18725 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1853.
   The dollar strengthened against the British pound in New York
trading. Sterling was quoted at $1.6798, less expensive for buyers
than Friday's late rate of $1.6855.
   Gold prices were little changed in U.S. dealings. There were no
quotes available from overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery edged up to $378.20 a troy ounce from Friday's settlement
of $377.90.
   Silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.646 a troy
ounce on New York's Comex compared to $5.601 on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
