<DOCNO> AP890501-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Carson-Bergner     05-01 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carson-Bergner,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>P.A. Bergner To Acquire Carson Pirie Scott For $454 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midwest department store operators Carson Pirie
Scott &amp; Co. and P.A. Bergner announced Monday they have agreed to
merge, with Bergner acquiring Carson for about $454 million.
   ``This merger fulfills our long-term objective to have a major
presence in the Chicago area,'' said Alan R. Anderson, Bergner's
chief executive officer and board chairman.
   The announcement wraps up a month-long courtship of
Chicago-based Carson that began in mid-April when Bergner made a
$282 million buyout offer worth about $20 a share. That bid was
rejected, as was the sweetened offer one week later of $24 a share.
   ``Together, the Bergner family of stores _ Bergner's, Boston
Store and Carson's _ will constitute one of the largest
department-store operations in the Midwest and will be No. 1 in
sales,'' said Anderson, who added the Carson's stores would
continue to operate under the Carson Pirie Scott name.
   At an afternoon news conference, however, he said some of
Carson's subsidiary stores _ including the County Seat and Arcadia
stores _ will be offered for sale.
   Anderson also said there were no plans to release any of
Carson's employees but that Peter S. Willmott, Carson's chairman
and chief executive officer, would resign.
   Willmott called the linkage of the two retail chains ``the
beginning of another stage in the company's ongoing 135-year-old
history'' and said it would serve shareholders' best interests.
   ``It had been my strong personal preference to continue the
two-year restructuring program we began in 1987 and to remain an
independent, focused retailer,'' said Willmott.
   The company fended off a 1986 takeover attempt by Chicago-based
Baytree Investors Inc.
   Carson lost $38.8 million in the fiscal year that ended in
January, partly because of problems integrating the Donaldson's
stores it bought in 1987 in Minnesota. Two years ago, the company
finished $26.7 million in the red.
   Willmott said the merger with Bergner's ``will combine two
companies with similar strategic objectives and will give Carson's
and Bergner's a stronger position in the highly competitive Midwest
market. Carson Pirie Scott's valuable name and position in the
retail industry will be maintained.''
   Carson Pirie Scott operates 33 stores under its own name. They
are located in Chicago, central Illinois, northwest Indiana,
Minnesota and Iowa. It also operates 391 County Seat specialty
stores, mostly in Midwest and Sunbelt states, and 23 Arcadia shops,
primarily in Chicago.
   With the acquisition, Bergner's _ a Swiss-owned chain that has
operated in the Midwest for 100 years and has 33 stores in Illinois
and Wisconsin _ will become one of the top 15 U.S. department-store
operations with consolidated revenue of about $1 billion. Bergner,
owned by the Maus and Nordmann families of Switzerland, has
headquarters in Milwaukee for its U.S. holdings.
   Under the agreement approved by boards of both companies, a
Bergner's subsidiary will begin a tender offer within five business
days for all the outstanding Carson's shares for $27.50 each. Based
on 16.5 million shares outstanding on a fully diluted basis, the
takeover will cost $453.75 million.
   Shares not acquired in the tender offer will be acquired in cash
in a subsequent merger.
   Merrill Lynch Capital Markets is advising Carson's, and Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. and Finance Co. are advising Bergner's.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
