<DOCNO> AP890501-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-01 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0686</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Gloomy Weather Forecasts Force Grains Higher ^By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose strongly Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to long-range forecasts of
below-average rainfall in several grain-producing states.
   On other markets, gasoline and crude oil prices rallied; cattle
and hogs were up, and gold and silver prices gained moderately.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 6\ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.23} a bushel; corn was 4\ cents to 5} cents
higher with May at $2.74 a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 6{ cents
higher with May at $1.84{ a bushel; soybeans were 12} cents to 17}
cents higher with May at $7.35\ a bushel.
   The increased grain and soybean prices came on the heels of the
30- and 90-day forecasts released Friday by the National Weather
Service, which predicted a return to dry conditions in the western
half of the Farm Belt, including Iowa and Illinois.
   The forecasts fueled talk of a return of drought conditions,
pushing up prices across the board.
   ``It was a very typical weather-related price movement,'' said
Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., in
New York. ``There is a lot of uncertainty in the market, and the
market should reflect that uncertainty into the summer.''
   Wheat finished strong despite doubt over the Bush
administration's position on continuing subsidized grain sales to
foreign countries.
   Mao noted that a lot of people are questioning the export
subsidy program, which finances cheap wheat sales to certain
nations, in the light of its costs and the prospect of a poor wheat
crop.
   Bush spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that Bush will soon
have a decision of a new grain sale to the Soviets.
   Petroleum prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange closed
mixed in light trading because of the May Day holiday celebrated in
Europe and Asia.
   Crude oil and gasoline moved up as buyers took advantage of
lower prices, while heating oil prices dropped in a selloff.
   Jim Ritterbusch, an analyst with Carson Petroleum Co. in
Chicago, said traders who sold their gasoline contracts last week
were buying the fuel and selling heating oil, betting that gasoline
prices would rise.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 24 cents
higher with June at $20.66 a barrel; heating oil was .18 cent to
.31 cent lower with June at 49.46 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .45 cent to 1.39 cents higher with June at 72.61 cents a gallon.
   Cattle and hogs were up and pork bellies down on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in moderate trading.
   ``There's little I can tell you about the market,'' said Charlie
Richardson, an analyst with Lind-Waldock &amp; Co. in Denver. ``It has
given no clear direction.''
   Richardson said some traders are selling because they expect
more cattle and hogs will be brought to market, while others are
buying because they expect a decrease in deliveries.
   Live cattle settled .02 cent to .37 cent higher, with June at
71.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with May at 76.30 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent lower to
.30 cent higher with June at 46.92 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .13 cent to 2 cents lower with May at 30.87 cents a
pound.
   Gold and silver futures settled slightly higher on New York's
Commodities Exchange as traders cashed in on what is thought to be
an oversold market.
   Despite the rise in prices, the market remains bearish because
of the lowering of the inflation mentality, said James Steel, an
analyst for Refco Inc. in New York.
   Without the threat of inflation there is little reason for
investors to buy gold.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents higher with May at $378.20 a
troy ounce; silver was 4.5 cents to 6 cents higher with May at
$5.646 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
