<DOCNO> AP890501-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 1806EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ConsumerConfidence     05-01 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Confidence,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Consumer Faith in Economy Remains Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence in the U.S. economy remains
strong despite growing indications of a slowdown caused by rising
interest rates, the Conference Board business research group
reported Monday.
   Its monthly Consumer Confidence Index, which tracks the spending
plans and perceptions about the economy in 5,000 households
nationwide, totaled 116.3 points in April, down only slightly from
the 117.7 figure in March. The index is calculated on a 1985 base
year of 100 points.
   An analysis of the latest index showed 28.8 percent of
respondents believe current business conditions are good, unchanged
from a month earlier, and 34.7 percent believe jobs are plentiful,
slightly higher than the March percentage.
   Respondents were slightly less optimistic about the next six
months, however. Only 16.5 percent anticipate an improvement in
business conditions, vs. 18 percent who said so a month earlier.
   The index also showed only 3.1 percent of respondents plan to
purchase a home, unchanged from March, reflecting continued concern
with rising interest rates and the resulting higher cost of
financing a mortgage.
   Nonetheless, the Conference Board said in its analysis, the
index showed consumer confidence remained resiliently high.
   ``The consumer's sustained sense of well-being is justified, at
least for the moment, by the continuing vigor of the economy,''
said Fabian Linden, executive director of the group's consumer
research center.
   The Conference Board, based in New York, describes itself as a
worldwide business network of companies and executives in more than
50 nations that conducts research and provides forums for
exchanging information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
