<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Tenneco     05-01 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Tenneco,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenneco Inc. Posts $109 Million First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc.'s earnings soared 73 percent in the
first three months of 1989, and officials said Monday the results
reflected favorably on the company's decision last year to get out
of the risky oil business.
   The Houston-based company earned $109 million, or 82 cents per
common share, in the 1989 first quarter on revenues of $3.3 billion.
   For the same period last year, Tenneco earned $63 million, or 38
cents per share, on revenues of $3.2 billion. Those results
included $53 million from discontinued operations.
   Tenneco sold its oil and gas operations last year to a number of
firms for a total of $7.3 billion.
   During the first quarter this year, the company's natural gas
pipelines posted earnings of $112 million, compared to $87 million
in the same period last year.
   The increase resulted primarily from improved earnings in the
non-federally regulated sectors of intrastate pipelines, methanol
and natural gas liquids, and other non-jurisdicational marketing
areas.
   Tenneco's shipbuilding division had a decline in earnings, going
from $34 million in the 1988 first quarter to $30 million this
quarter. The company said the decline was caused by lower margins
on naval construction.
   Tenneco had an overall loss in its other divisions, which
include farm and construction equipment, automotive parts,
packaging and chemicals and minerals.
</TEXT>
