<FIRST>r f AM-TunnelDeaths 2ndLd-Writethru f0233 05-01 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tunnel Deaths, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0233,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Department Proposes $1.15 Million In Fines For Fatal Tunnel
Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with reaction from second company;
picks up 6th graf, `Connors said ...'. A version moved on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Labor Department proposed $1.15
million in fines for two contractors cited Monday for 115 safety
violations in a methane gas explosion last year that killed three
sewer tunnel workers.
   S.A. Healy Co. of McCook, Ill., was cited for 68 willful
violations carrying fines of $680,000; CH2M Hill Central Inc. of
Corvallis, Ore., was cited for 47 willful violations carrying
penalties of $470,000.
   Healy, the main contractor for the project, and CH2M, hired to
supervise construction on the tunnel, have 15 days to appeal the
citations and penalties to the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, said Mike Connors, regional administrator of OSHA's
Chicago office.
   Healy President George Malina said in a statement that his
company had cooperated with OSHA's investigation and the citations
were ``not a verdict but rather a starting point.''
   ``We intend to vigorously defend against the OSHA citations and
look forward to presenting all the facts,'' he said.
   CH2M said in a statement the company was ``surprised and
distressed'' by the citations and that all equipment listed in the
47 citations belonged to the contractor.
   ``The responsibilities of CH2M Hill as program manager do not
include supervising or performing any of the construction'' on the
project, the statement said.
   Connors said his agency's investigation found that electrical
power had not been turned off after workers were evacuated from the
tunnel Nov. 10 after dangerously high levels of methane were
detected.
   Tony Bell, 25, of Sturgeon Bay, Wis.; Ron Kohne, 49, of Big
Sandy, Tenn.; and Rick Sochacki, 34, of South Holland, Ill.; were
killed by a explosion after they re-entered the tunnel to check
methane levels.
   Work has not resumed at the tunnel, but spokesmen for the
project have said they hope work might resume later this month.
</TEXT>
