<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HotelBel-Air     05-01 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hotel Bel-Air,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Company Buys Celebrity Site For More Than $100 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hotel Bel-Air, haunt of movie stars and
the Hollywood elite, was sold Monday to a Japanese company for more
than $100 million by its Texas owner.
   The price for the rambling, low-rise landmark works out to more
than $1 million per room, a record for hotel sales that real estate
experts say is unlikely to be surpassed any time soon.
   It demonstrates Japanese investors' continued appetite for such
``trophy'' real estate as prestigious big-city office buildings and
resort property.
   Dallas oil heiress Caroline Hunt, through her Rosewood Property
Co., announced that the Bel-Air had been sold to Sekitei Kaihatsu,
a 95-year-old Tokyo company that operates hotels, resorts and
restaurants in Japan.
   Rosewood said the landmark, which had been on the market for
about two months, sold for more than $100 million, but didn't
reveal the precise amount.
   Rosewood will continue to operate the hotel, it said.
   The Bel-Air's restaurant ranks with the nearby Polo Lounge in
Beverly Hills among the city's chic dining spots. Recent diners
have ranged from entertainers Mel Gibson, Kathleen Turner and
William Hurt to CBS executive Bud Grant and Walt Disney Co. chief
Michael Eisner.
   One-time hotel resident Tony Curtis once called the hotel the
best wife he'd ever had.
   The Hotel Bel-Air, which sits on Los Angeles' tony west side not
far from the UCLA campus, has room rates ranging from $195 to
$1,300 per night, with an average of $375 a night. Occupancy
averages 90 percent, compared with a national average of 68 percent.
   Ms. Hunt's company bought the mission-style hotel and its
11-acre grounds in 1982 for $22.7 million and spent $20 million
renovating it and adding 30 rooms, for a total of 92 rooms.
   The previous record per-room price for a hotel was $200 million,
or more than $750,000 a room, paid for the Beverly Hills Hotel by
the Sultan of Brunei in 1987.
   Last week, another Japanese company completed purchase of the
nearby Riviera golf and tennis club for more than $100 million.
</TEXT>
