<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PensionSuit     05-01 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pension Suit,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Department Sues Shearson For Alleged Misuse Of Teamsters Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday sued a brokerage
firm, an investment manager and several trustees of $561 million in
Teamsters union benefit funds for allegedly abusing their positions
for financial gain through stock deals and other transactions.
   Among the allegations in the Labor Department suit is that the
Utica, N.Y., office of the brokerage firm Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. manipulated stock purchases for the funds to benefit other
clients.
   Shearson, investment manager Stein Roe and Farnham Inc. and
several of their agents were charged with violating federal pension
laws by causing the Teamsters funds to engage in prohibited
financial transactions.
   A copy of the complaint was released by Labor Department
officials in Washington after normal business hours Monday and
attempts to reach Shearson and Stein Roe officials were
unsuccessful.
   A telephone call to Shearson's Utica office was not answered and
a woman who answered the phone at Stein Roe in New York said there
was no one available to comment.
   Included in the alleged abuses were ``stock parking'' schemes in
which Shearson, acting through three of its employees, set up an
account in its Utica office that it used to purchase stocks with
the funds' assets.
   Instead of immediately transferring the stocks to the funds, the
suit alleged that Shearson ``parked'' them for a period of time to
determine their short-term profitability and used accounting tricks
to transfer securities that had increased in value to the accounts
of friends, relatives and customers of two former Shearson brokers
who handled the Teamsters account.
   One of the former brokers, George Inserra, allegedly used his
knowledge of the funds' investment plans to benefit some of his
individual clients by purchasing stock for them just before the
funds made large purchases of the same stock. Inserra then
allegedly sold the individual clients' stock at the higher prices
caused by the bulk purchase.
   Shearson and Stein Roe also allegedly benefited through fee
arrangements with banks issuing certificates of deposits to the
union funds. Shearson allegedly concealed indirect fees on assets
invested in the certificates; Stein Roe allegedly was paid to
manage those investments but performed no services.
   The funds involved are the New York State Teamsters Conference
Pension and Retirement Fund, the Upstate Teamsters Pension and
Retirement Fund and the New York State Teamsters Council Health and
Hospital Fund. Together they have about 65,000 participants and had
$561,231,396 in cumulative assets as of the end of 1985, the Labor
Department said.
   Eight current and former trustees of the funds were named as
defendants for allegedly violating their fiduciary responsibily to
the plans.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Syracuse, N.Y., seeks
a court order requiring the defendants to determine and restore
with interest all losses incurred by the funds because of improper
activities.
   It also seeks court-appointed monitors to review the practices
of Shearson and Stein Roe and an order prohibiting four current and
former employees of Shearson and Stein Roe from involvement in
pension plans covered by the federal Employee Retirement Income
Security Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890501-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Minorco-GoldFields     05-01 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minorco-Gold Fields,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Wants Bush to Block Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., suggested Monday
that President George Bush safeguard national security by blocking
the proposed acquisition of American mineral interests by a South
African-linked company, but government lawyers said the president
lacks the authority to intervene.
   ``By allowing this takeover we are undercutting the
effectiveness of our country's anti-apartheid policy,'' Florio
wrote in a letter requesting that Bush act under a provision of the
1988 trade bill that the New Jersey congressman co-authored with
Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb.
   Florio asked that Bush investigate a $6 billion takeover offer
made by Minorco, a Luxembourg-based holding company controlled by
South African interests.
   Minorco wants to acquire Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, a
London-based mining company whose American holdings include
Associated Minerals USA and the Newmont Mining Co. _ producers of
gold, rutile, zircon, monazite, and other strategic minerals with
military and nuclear applications.
   Florio said he's concerned the deal could increase South
Africa's control over production of the minerals.
   ``I believe this takeover raises important security questions
for the U.S., which may not have been adequately considered
previously, when this matter was under review by the inter-agency
Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States,'' said
Florio, chairman of the subcommittee on commerce, consumer
protection and competitiveness.
   However, Steve Canner, staff chairman of the inter-agency
committee, said the panel had fully reviewed the merger and decided
against proceeding with an investigation.
   ``If the committee decides not to go forward, that's it,'' he
said.
   According to documents supplied by the Treasury Department,
government attorneys reviewed the deal's potential impact on
strategic metals as well as anti-apartheid laws before concluding
``the transaction posed no threat to the U.S. national security.''
   Government attorneys said Monday that based on the legislative
history that accompanied the trade bill and the executive order
implementing the bill, once the 30-day review period ended without
a decision to proceed to an investigation, action under Exon-Florio
had concluded and the president had no authority to resurrect the
issue.
   Minorco, which is 60 percent owned by Anglo American Corp. of
South Africa and De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., is the largest
producer of gold in the non-communist world. Gold Fields is the
world's second-largest gold concern.
</TEXT>
