<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru f0186 05-01 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0186,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wholesale Gasoline Rallies Anew</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs on BP raising its Alaskan crude price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market turned mixed in light
trading Monday, with gasoline and crude oil rising in price and
home heating oil continuing to decline.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for
wholesale unleaded gasoline settled 1.39 cents higher at 72.61
cents a gallon. The May contract, which expired on Friday, had lost
3.91 cents.
   The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 24 cents to $20.66 a 42-gallon barrel,
after falling 50 cents on Friday.
   June heating oil, which gained 0.34 cent Friday, closed 0.31
cent lower at 49.46 cents a gallon. Heating oil has been on the
decline in reaction to the warmer weather.
   Andrew Lebow, an energy analyst at E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., attributed the rise in gasoline to strong
fundamentals, which, in turn, helped push up crude prices.
   ``We're motoring into the driving season and ... approaching the
Memorial Day holiday,'' he said.
   Gasoline has been the market's star performer recently due to
concerns of tight supplies for the summer driving season. Those
concerns escalated following the Exxon oil spill off the Alaskan
coast in March and a North Sea explosion recently.
   In a related move Monday, BP Exploration raised the price of
North Slope Alaskan crude by more than $2 a barrel, pushing the it
to its highest level in more than three years.
   The increase is partly attributable to the Prince William Sound
oil spill and interruptions of production in the North Sea, said
Chuck Lodgsdon, Alaska's chief petroleum economist.
   BP set its May contract price at $19.77 on the Gulf Coast and
$19.33 on the West Coast. The difference reflects a variation in
transportation costs.
   The prices represented a $2.25 a barrel increase on the Gulf
Coast and $2.20 more on the West Coast.
   BP is the only North Slope producer that makes its prices
public, but other North Slope producers usually follow BP's lead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
