<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SunState     05-01 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sun State,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officers Of Struggling S&amp;L Try To Talk Customers Out Of Withdrawing
Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top officers of Sun State Savings and Loan
Association descended to the lobby of their thrift Monday in an
attempt to talk customers out of pulling their deposits from the
struggling S&amp;L.
   In some cases, they were successful, said Sun State spokesman
Michael Million.
   ``We had as many standing in line to make deposits or cash
checks or do some other kind of transaction as we did for
withdrawals,'' Million said.
   ``Monday is our busiest day anyway, and when you add to that
that people are concerned about the news that they heard over the
weekend, most people were quite satisfied when they heard our
answers.''
   On Friday, Sun State announced a $63.5 million annual loss, the
resignation of its two top executives, the reduction of
stockholders' equity to a negative $17.3 million, and the signing
of a ``supervisory agreement'' under which the S&amp;L acknowledged
that grounds might exist for a federal takeover.
   Federal regulators have required Sun State to maintain at least
$34 million in working capital. Friday's announcement also said the
thrift had only $7 million.
   Million said new Chairman Thomas E. Arnold and new Vice Chairman
Robert F. Amos were successful in persuading some depositors not to
withdraw their money.
   ``You could say it (the effort) is extraordinary, but not in
light of a $63 million loss,'' Million said.
</TEXT>
