<FILEID>AP-NR-05-01-89 2223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Corrigan-Kravis     05-01 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corrigan-Kravis,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.Y. Fed President Takes Swipe At Junk Bond King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Federal Reserve official took an impromptu
swipe Monday at Henry Kravis, the king of leveraged buyouts.
   E. Gerald Corrigan, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York, noted that Kravis had won an award for leadership in business
in 1988 from Columbia Business School's alumni association.
   ``It raises in my mind a question about your definition of
business,'' Corrigan said at the alumni association's 1989 awards
dinner at the Waldorf-Astoria.
   The unprepared remark drew murmurs from the black-tie audience.
   In his speech, Corrigan said the nation should but more emphasis
on mechanical and electrical engineering and less on what he called
financial engineering.
   Across town at the New York Hilton, Kravis was defending
leveraged buyouts as keynote speaker at the annual dinner of the
Harvard Business School of Greater New York.
   Kravis is a founding partner of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.,
which led such debt-financed deals as the record $24.53 billion
takeover of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   ``I see LBOs as one tactic, among others, to free U.S. business
from the paralyzing clutches of hidebound corporate bureaucracies
and to increase our competitive position in the world economy,''
Kravis said.
   At Columbia's dinner, Corrigan received an award for leadership
in government, while Charles E. Exley Jr., chairman and chief
executive of NCR Corp., got the award for leadership in business
and W. Edwards Deming, the quality control guru, received a
lifetime achievement award for public service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
